<FIRST>u a AM-GospelMusic 1stLd-Writethru a0840 04-14 0501</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Gospel Music, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0840,0509</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sandi Patti Dominates Early Awards At Gospel Music Awards</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with final awards; CORRECTS to
make it Stryper, sted Striper; picks up 11th graf pvs: `Bruce Carroll ...</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sandi Patti won or shared five awards
and Amy Grant was voted artist of the year Thursday night at the
20th annual Gospel Music Association awards show.
   Ms. Patti was voted No. 1 female vocalist for the eighth
straight year, but her two-year reign as top artist was broken by
Ms. Grant, whose songs have crossed over to the pop music charts.
   Ms. Patti also won inspirational song of the year for ``In
Heaven's Eyes,'' inspirational album for ``Make His Praise
Glorious,'' choral collection album for ``Sandi Patti Choral
Praise'' and instrumental album for ``A Symphony of Praise.'' The
instrumental award was for the musicianship on the album and not
for her vocals.
   ``In heaven's eyes, there are no losers,'' Ms. Patti said in
accepting her award for top inspirational song.
   Ms. Grant, in accepting the top award at the close of the
3{-hour gala, said singing gospel music has brought her closer to
her associates in the industry. ``In this field, you are with
family,'' she said.
   Ms. Grant also won for contemporary gospel album and short-form
video, both for ``Lead Me On.''
   The new a cappella group Take 6 won four honors to go with the
two Grammy awards it won in February. Take 6 won group of the year,
best new artist, top black gospel album for ``Take 6'' and No. 1
contemporary black gospel song for ``If We Ever.''
   Wayne Watson, who has had 15 straight single songs on the Top 10
of the gospel music charts, was named male vocalist of the year.
Among the other five finalists was Larnelle Harris, who had won the
honor three times previously.
   ``I try to be grateful to the Lord and not get puffed up,''
Watson said in his acceptance speech. Watson also won
song-of-the-year honors for his ``Friend of a Wounded Heart.''
   Veteran gospel singer Shirley Caesar also was a double winner,
taking awards for black gospel song for ``Hold My Mule'' and
traditional black gospel album for ``Live in Chicago.''
   Two heavy metal categories were added to the awards this year
for the first time, and both were won by the four-member group
Stryper. Their ``In God We Trust'' was voted recorded metal gospel
song of the year and also metal album of the year.
   Bruce Carroll was a double winner, taking honors for country
gospel recorded song for ``Above and Beyond'' and country gospel
album for ``Richest Man in Town.''
   The awards are called the Dove Awards to signify the bird that
appeared in the biblical account of the baptism of Christ. Winners
were chosen by the singers, musicians and songwriters in the
3,000-member association, based in Nashville. The ceremonies were
not televised.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
