<FIRST>r a PM-OccultReligions     04-14 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Occult Religions,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Occult Religions Muddled On Drug Scene</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Ritual Slayings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Violence and human sacrifice among believers in
occult religions usually involve a mixture of pantheistic beliefs
that often are distortions of ancient rituals.
   That kind of mingling and twisting of strange, heterodox ideas
and practices seemed apparent in the gruesome killings of at least
13 people near Matamoros, Mexico, across the Rio Grande from
Brownsville, Texas.
   There were hints of assorted primitive religions and
superstitions, perhaps stemming from traditions such as these, or
aberrations of them:
   _Satanism is characterized by its antagonism toward the
Christian deity and worship of the adversary, Satan. Devotees
consider him a supreme being of evil, rivaling God.
   Their rites consist of mockery or perversion of Christian
ritual, sometimes called the Black Mass at which Satan is believed
to preside. Ritual killings sometimes have been associated with the
cult.
   It also has been linked to assorted sexual, sado-masochistic and
psychopathic activities, including grave robberies and
blood-letting, both animal and human.
   Symbols of the cult include the pentagram, a five-pointed star
with the single point down, and the ``horned god'' in the form of a
goat.
   _Voodoo is a set of animistic beliefs and rites stemming from
Africa, and sometimes interweaving Roman Catholic practices in its
form that became pervasive in Haiti.
   Voodoo worshipers believe in one God but also in numerous
spirits or lesser deities. Magic and witchcraft have proliferated
in relation to voodoo, including casting of spells and fates on
others, good or ill. This often involves use of effigies of
another, along with bits of clothing or hair from the person.
   Certain advanced practicioners, or ``houngans,'' are considered
healers, also enabled to take posssession of the spirit of others.
Singing and dancing are part of the rituals.
   The chief deity is called ``Damballah,'' sometimes symbolized by
a serpent.
   _Santeria is an offshoot of voodoo that has spread into Latin
America and which calls its main god ``Chango,'' a god of fire and
stone. Santeria, like voodoo, involves use of various botanical
ingredients and other items considered magic.
   Related cults have derived from Santeria with pantheons of gods
such as Elegba, god of luck; Ogun, god of metal; Ifa, god of
divination, and Eshju, the trickster.
   Practices of Santeria and its related cults include animal
sacrifice, polygamy, ecstatic dancing and the appeasement of gods
by various offerings.
   Derivatives of these cults and aberrations of them also have
turned up in various parts of the United States.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890414-0006 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0223EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon-Irish     04-14 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon-Irish,0763</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanese Villlagers Get Their Wish _ Irish Are Staying</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIAD KAHWAJI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TYRE, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Villagers in southern Lebanon got their
wish. The Irish government has decided to keep its 750-man
batallion in the United Nations peacekeeping forces here.
   The government in Dublin had been reconsidering the Irish
battalion's presence in Lebanon because four of its soldiers had
been killed and one wounded in three attacks in the past three
months. Three of them were killed by a landmine March 21.
   ``We greatly need the Irish contingent in south Lebanon,'' said
Abbas Fawaz, the mayor of Tibnin, a town 11 miles north of the
Israeli border.
   The estimated 100,000 Shiite Moslems living in 20 hamlets around
Tibnin, the Irish headquarters, ``enjoy their protection,'' Fawaz
said.
   Before making the decision, the Irish Cabinet reviewed a report
by Lt. Gen. Tadhg O'Neill, chief of staff of the Irish army, who
had come here to investigate the landmine explosion March 21.
   The Cabinet renews Ireland's commitment every six months, and
the Irish political opposition had called for a policy review after
the deaths. The fourth death occurred earlier.
   ``Our presence here is very vital to the security of the area
and to the locals who depend on our humanitarian aide,'' said Lt.
Col. Pat McMahon, commander of the Irish contingent in the United
Nations Interim Force in Lebanon (UNIFIL).
   On March 30, hundreds of Tebnin's 5,000 residents participated
in a memorial ceremony for the three Irish soldiers killed by the
landmine.
   ``The Irish contingent lives among its people in the south,''
said one of the banners at the ceremony. ``Aggression against it is
aggression on the southerners.''
   The U.N. peacekeeping force, made up of 5,800 personnel from
nine nations, has monitored a narrow strip of 65towns and villages
in south Lebanon since March 1985.
   The population in the force's area of operation increased from
about 50,000 when the force first arrived to about a half million
people today.
   ``Before UNIFIL came to south Lebanon ... the area was a free
terrain to militiamen and terrorists who spread fear and death
everywhere,'' said Fawaz, 64, who has been mayor for 20 years.
   ``Now everyone is moving around here peacefully and freely,
thanks to the Irish battalion.''
   An Irish sergeant about to be moved out on routine rotation said
he was leaving with mixed feelings.
   ``There are a lot of poor people here who are in great need of
our humanitarian work, which is worth risking my life for,'' said
the sergeant who could not allow his name to be used because of
standing regulations.
   An Irish major at headquarters in Tebnin said it ``would be a
fire zone without us.''
   ``When the Irish battalion first came here, the villagers did
not have any electricity and had shortages of water,'' he said,
``But we helped them, and now they are confident in their future
because of us.''
   The Irish battalion has lost 30 soldiers in attacks by various
groups over the years.
   Investigations were still under way to determine who planted the
landmine that exploded under a UNIFIL jeep near Haddatha on March
21 and killed the three soldiers, Lt. Col. Patrick Hayes said.
   The other two recent attacks were carried out by the
Israeli-backed South Lebanon Army (SLA) militia, which controls a
narrow strip of Lebanese territory that Israel refers to as its
``security zone.''
   Israel maintained the zone when it pulled out the bulk of its
invading army from south Lebanon in the summer of 1985, ending a
three-year occupation.
   The terrain, which extends from the Mediterranean Sea in the
west to the slopes of snow-peaked Mount Hermon in the east, serves
as a buffer against cross-border infiltrations by Palestinian
guerrillas into northern Israeli settlements.
   Col. McMahon blamed Israel for the South Lebanon Army attacks on
the Irish battalion. He said such hostilities were due to ``the
lack of control from the Israeli army command on the SLA
militiamen.''
   Hassan Fawaz, the son of Tebnin's mayor who owns a gift shop
near the Irish battalion headquarters, said, ``Tebnin residents
notify the Irish command about the possibility of any attack on
them that we come to know of.''
   The younger Fawaz stressed the economic value that the Irish
battalion represents to the area. The troops spend at least
$500,000 annually on souvenirs and goods they buy duty-free from
local stores.
</TEXT>
