<FIRST>r w PM-JudicialCandidates     04-14 0552</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Judicial Candidates,550</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Freezes Action on Three Judicial Candidates</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The failure of three candidates for federal
judge to answer whether the White House screened them on how they
would rule on cases has frozen Senate committee action on the
nominations for at least a week.
   ``We have a responsibility to advise and consent to the
selection of judges and to know what the process was in that
selection,'' Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass., said Thursday after
calling for a halt in Judiciary Committee action.
   Responding to Kennedy, Chairman Joseph Biden, D-Del., postponed
for one week consideration of District Judge Pamela Ann Rymer of
Los Angeles as an appellate judge and Robert C. Bonner of Pasadena,
Calif., and Melinda F. Harmon of Houston as district judges.
   None of the three responded to written questions from Kennedy on
whether they had been screened by the administration on how they
might decide cases that could come before them.
   Some lawmakers also were critical of a letter on the subject
sent by the Justice Department on Wednesday. ``It is one of the
most dramatically inept letters I have ever seen come before this
committee,'' said Sen. Patrick Leahy, D-Vt.
   Kennedy had asked Judge Rymer to ``list all interviews or
communications you had with the White House staff or the Justice
Department regarding your nomination and the dates of such
interviews or communications and identify all persons present or
participating in such interviews.''
   His questions, submitted in writing by Biden, asked if she had
``any communication with any member of the White House staff or the
Justice Department referring or relating to your views on any case,
issue, subject or area of the law that could come before the court
to which you have been nominated.''
   They also asked for names and dates as well as ``any
communication relating to your judicial philosophy or your legal
writings or judicial opinions.'' Similar questions were put to
Harmon and Bonner.
   Biden said that when there was no response to the questions he
contacted the Justice Department and received a ``draft'' letter
replying to the queries. The letter was a draft and not the
finished product because Attorney General Richard Thornburgh could
not show the letter to each of the candidates before sending it to
the committee, the chairman said.
   Phrased as if written by a nominee, the letter said:
   ``1) I did not make any commitments with regard to how I might
rule on any specific case or issue nor were any such commitments
sought.
   ``2) My personal views on controversial cases or issues were not
solicited in a manner to suggest that it should commit myself to
rule in a particular way on issues or cases to advance my nomination
   ``3) I do not believe I have been subjected to an `ideological
litmus test.'
   ``4) I have no doubt that everyone who interviewed me expected
me, if nominated and confirmed, to exercise my best independent
judgment on every matter brought before me.''
   David Runkel, a spokesman for the attorney general, said ``we
think the letter is responsive.''
   Kennedy said that he had not heard of the letter until he was on
his way to the Judiciary Committee session and wanted more time to
consider the issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
