<FIRST>r a PM-CroquetFirst     04-14 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Croquet First,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Church Gym Plays Host To First Indoor Croquet Tournament</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: `Xandra' in 3rd graf is cq</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN LUMSDEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A contest billed as the nation's first
indoor croquet tournament will include the use of balls that don't
need grass to slow them down.
   At least 50 players from 14 colleges have signed up for the
Third National Collegiate Croquet Tournament at the former Bible
Speaks headquarters in Lenox.
   The three-day tournament, which began today, marked the U.S.
debut of croquet balls invented 18 months ago by Townsend Croquet
Ltd. of England, said organizer Xandra Kayden of Cambridge.
   The hollow balls, filled with fluid and glass beads, create an
internal resistance that slows them as if they were on grass,
company owner Charles Townsend said in a trans-Atlantic call
Thursday. ``The insides swish around and absorb the energy of the
ball on a hard surface,'' he said.
   ``They're wonderful,'' said croquet coach Steven Sprague of
Lenox, whose mother discovered the balls in a Christmas catalog.
``It slows the ball down a little differently than balls slowed by
grass, but you get used to it.''
   Townsend said he invented the balls at the request of several
Britons who wanted to use village halls for croquet matches during
their wet winters. He also invented spikeless wickets that can be
taped to floors.
   The balls have been used in a few small tournaments in England,
but not, to Townsend's knowledge, in the United States. Ms. Kayden
said the Lenox tournament is the first to be played indoors and to
use the balls.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
