<FIRST>u a PM-Spill-AlaskaOpinion Bjt   04-14 0702</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Alaska Opinion, Bjt,0721</SECOND>
<HEAD>Letters Columns Swell With Alaskans' Angry Responses To Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUSAN GALLAGHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANCHORAGE, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In newspaper columns and editorial
pages, Alaskans are unleashing their fury at the oil spill that has
defiled Prince William Sound and imperiled livelihoods drawn from
the sea.
   The volume of letters to newspaper editors in some areas remains
high even three weeks after the spill that sent 10.1 million
gallons of oil into the sound, and at least two editorial boards
have recast their positions on a tax change for oil companies.
   Editors of the two Anchorage daily newspapers said they can
think of no other issue that has generated so much mail. Much of it
has hammered the oil industry.
   ``We're busier than we've ever been,'' said Michael Carey,
editorial page editor of the Anchorage Daily News, which on April 9
devoted a section front and inside space to letters about the spill.
   Anchorage Times Editor in Chief William J. Tobin said most of
his in-state mail has condemned Exxon, the owner of the tanker
involved in the spill.
   ``The tone of the letters from outside (the state) says, in
effect, `Alaska, we mourn with you in this terrible tragedy,'''
Tobin said.
   ``I really haven't seen (a letter) yet that was favorable to the
oil companies,'' said Andy Williams, editorial page editor of the
Fairbanks Daily News-Miner.
   Even industry friend Val Molyneux, president of the Alaska
Support Industry Alliance, was cautious in a letter sent to the
Homer News and several other papers.
   ``We, as Alaskans, share in a collective sense of loss and shock
as a result of the tragedy in Prince William Sound,'' Molyneux
wrote. ``There must be a lesson learned.''
   In a telephone interview Wednesday, Molyneux said that despite
the Exxon accident, Alaskans should not forget the good things the
oil industry has brought.
   ``I still believe the long-term future of the state is in the
resources, and the major resource is oil,'' Molyneux said.
   That is apparently on the minds of few letter writers.
   ``The oil industry has created a system that is a disaster
waiting to happen,'' wrote Lara Purtel in the Anchorage Daily News.
Another reader, James Sykes, said oil companies had little
incentive to guard against spills or conduct speedy cleanups
because of liability limits, spill-related tax write-offs and the
ability to raise gasoline prices.
   Among the few letters supportive of the oil industry was one
from Suzanne McLaughlin of Anchorage.
   ``Oil really does feed my family and pay my taxes,'' she wrote
in a letter in The Anchorage Times. ``And don't kid yourself _ it
does yours, too.''
   Oil finances 85 percent of Alaska's state budget, and it was oil
wealth that created the Permanent Fund, a state savings account
that generates annual dividends for Alaskans. The 1988 payment for
every qualified man, woman and child in the state topped $800.
   To most editorial writers, the figures behind the industry's
impact on Alaska wealth are as familiar as their home phone
numbers. But two newspapers say the statistics are no longer
sufficient to support positions they held less than a month ago
giving tax breaks to the oil industry.
   The tax structure was altered to reduce the burden on oil
companies as marginal oil fields declined, but the still-rich
Prudhoe Bay region was inadvertently included as well. An effort is
underway to revise the structure, which now provides oil companies
with a $150 million annual tax break.
   The Ketchikan Daily News modified its position on the proposed
revision, and the Juneau Empire reversed its stand.
   Ketchikan Daily News Publisher Lew Williams said his newspaper
had been ``wavering'' on the tax issue, ``but there's no wavering
now. We've got to make some changes and get some money'' from the
oil companies.
   ``Before, we felt as though the oil industry had been paying its
share of the cost of running state government,'' said Carl Sampson,
Empire managing editor. ``Two and a half weeks ago, though, we
started thinking about ... some of the non-monetary costs that
would come out of the oil spill.
   ``We felt as though there had been a betrayal of trust between
Alaskans and the oil companies.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
