<FIRST>r p PM-Wright-Impact     04-14 0617</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright-Impact,630</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wright Problems Becoming Democratic Party Problems</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Ohio Democratic Party chairman put the
best political face on the nerve-wrenching drama surrounding the
speaker of the House: ``My candidate for mayor of Toledo isn't
going to be hurt by Jim Wright,'' he said.
   But many Democrats fear Wright's troubles are their troubles.
   The Texas congressman is the party's highest ranking elected
official and one of its most visible spokesmen.
   As such he is an easy target for Republicans, their House
leadership sharpened by the recent selection of Wright tormentor
Newt Gingrich as GOP whip.
   Among House Democrats as well as among party officials across
the country, the concern was palpable Thursday as it became clear
the House ethics committee was prepared to charge Wright with
violating House rules.
   ``I'm not hearing much,'' said Iowa Democratic Party chairman
Bonnie Campbell, when asked if Wright was becoming a political
issue in her state. ``To the extent I do, it's Democrats fearing
the worst.''
   The speaker went on the offensive, declaring that he was
``confident that in the 34 years I have been in the Congress, I
have not violated those basic rules, nor any commonly accepted
standard of ethical conduct.''
   He vowed to ``fight to the last ounce of conviction and energy
that I possess'' to clear ``my good name.''
   Watching on television as Wright defended himself was Charles
Whitehead, chairman of the Florida Democratic Party.
   ``It certainly doesn't help us,'' Whitehead said later. ``It
gives the Republicans an awful lot of openings.''
   Jim Ruvolo, Whitehead's Ohio counterpart, said, ``It obviously
depends on the extent of the charges, how seriously they're
perceived in terms of his personal integrity. If he makes a
convincing case that these are minor infractions and he regrets
them, then they may not have long repercussions.
   ``If he's unable to do that, clearly then it's a problem for
Democrats and some Democrats have to sit down and talk to him about
it,'' Ruvolo said. ``The next couple of days will tell because it's
going to be on the news tonight.''
   Rep. Dale Kildee, D-Mich., said, ``I think there's deep concern,
both as to the person of the speaker and the Congress itself. Agony
is probably the best word.''
   But Greg Schneiders, a Democratic political consultant,
questioned whether there would be much political impact from
Wright's problems.
   ``Voters are so cynical about politicians in general that
whenever they hear about a politician doing something or being
charged with unethical activity, they say, `So what else is new?'
They assume that about politicians until it gets to a point where
it is really unacceptable,'' Schneiders said.
   He said he does not believe the allegations against Wright have
``captured the public imagination.''
   Whitehead disagreed about the depth of cynicism.
   ``I don't think it's gotten that bad yet,'' he said. ``They're
cynical, yes. They expect some wrongdoing. And in Wright's defense,
I think this will be played out of proportion.''
   When the speaker appeared before reporters to defend himself, he
was flanked by the House Democratic leadership.
   House Majority Leader Thomas Foley, D-Wash., next in line to
Wright, said the speaker's arguments were ``very moving and very
persuasive. Support for the speaker remains very, very strong
indeed among many Democrats.''
   Asked whether he'd be more comfortable with Wright or Foley
speaking for his party, Whitehead replied:
   ``At this particular time, I would feel much more comfortable if
it was Tom Foley and I would think that any Democrat who would be
honest and candid would say that.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Donald M. Rothberg is the chief political writer
of The Associated Press.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
