<FIRST>r w PM-Coelho-Bonds     04-14 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Coelho-Bonds,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Democratic Whip Says He and Not Campaign Committee Purchased Bond</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Democratic Whip Tony Coelho blames an
error by an investment firm for records listing his campaign
committee as the buyer of a $100,000 junk bond when in reality he
purchased it himself.
   ``I borrowed the money, made the investment, sold it, made a
profit and reported the transaction on my financial disclosure
statement for 1986 as I am required to do,'' the California
lawmaker said Thursday in a statement.
   Conversion of campaign funds to personal use is against House
rules.
   The third-ranking Democrat in the House acknowledged that
records of the brokerage firm of Drexel, Burnham, Lambert listed
``Coelho for Congress'' as the purchaser of the bond on April 10,
1986.
   An aide, David Dreyer, said it remains unresolved why Coelho's
records show he bought it the following month.
   ``We're going by our records,'' Dreyer said. The bond was sold
in October on the vice of Coelho's accountant, the statement said,
at a profit of $6,882.
   Drexel propelled itself into the vanguard of the 1980s corporate
buyout binge by developing the technique of financing such
operations with junk bonds, so called because they pay high
interest but also represent high risk. Since then, however, the
firm's Beverly Hills-based junk bond operation has been rocked by
scandal.
   Drexel's junk bond king Michael Milken and two others were
indicted March 29 by a federal grand jury in New York on fraud and
racketeering charges.
   Coelho's statement said that as the ``result of an error made by
Drexel, Burnham, Lambert Inc., my campaign committee was
inaccurately carried as the purchaser, even though it provided no
money for the investment.''
   ``Repeated efforts by my staff to correct what I now believe to
be a computer error made by Drexel finally resulted in my name
being accurately listed,'' he said. He said his decision to buy
``had nothing to do with either Drexel, Mike Milken or an employee
of Drexel, and neither Drexel nor Milken recommended it to me.''
   ``The purchase was reviewed and approved by my accountant as
reasonable and prudent, and I relied on my accountant for that kind
of advice,'' he said.
   ``It was this kind of situation,'' he said, ``among other
reasons, that prompted me to put my investments in a blind trust.''
   A letter to Harris Trust and Savings of Chicago, made public by
Coelho's office, said Drexel erroneously set this account under
Coelho for Congress.
   ``It has since been changed to Tony Coelho and ... I would
appreciate it if you would reissue the check to Tony Coelho
personally,'' said the letter dated Oct. 21, 1986, and signed by
Coelho administrative assistant Fred Hatfield.
   Aides to Coelho and Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., said that
Cranston, at the urging of Coelho, wrote to the Securities and
Exchange Commission to warn of the harmful effect on the Los
Angeles-area employment situation if the agency went ahead with a
plan to close Milken's Beverly Hills headquarters.
   Coelho, himself, however, did not write such a letter, Dreyer
said.
</TEXT>
