<FIRST>r w PM-Wright-Procedure     04-14 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wright-Procedure,470</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lengthy Process to Play out in Wright Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House ethics committee will have
considerable work to do on the Jim Wright case, even if it grants
the speaker's request to appear quickly to defend himself against
allegations he broke House rules.
   There could be weeks and even months of committee legal
proceedings before the panel _ officially called the Committee on
Standards of Official Conduct _ would make a recommendation to the
full House.
   Those recommendations could include no punishment, a fine, a
reprimand, a censure, or, in the most extreme case, expulsion. A
reprimand involves a House vote. A censure requires the additional
step of calling the member to the front of the chamber, to have the
censure resolution read to him.
   The next step for the committee in the Wright case will come
next week, when it issues a statement of alleged violations.
   This is similar to an indictment, and based on a finding that
``there is reason to believe'' violations occurred. Each alleged
violation must be listed as a separate count.
   The statement will then trigger other proceedings.
   The accused would have at least 21 days to provide a response,
which must be in writing.
   Wright could object to any count ``on the grounds that it fails
to state facts which constitute a violation.''
   If Wright files any motions, such as a motion to dismiss, the
committee would have 30 days to make a ruling. The speaker would
then have 14 days to respond to each count not dismissed.
   Any of these timetables can be changed by the panel chairman,
Rep. Julian Dixon, D-Calif., who can make proceedings go faster or
slower.
   After the timetables expire, the committee would vote either to
hold a disciplinary hearing or to defer action. The latter course
is reserved for cases where a judicial proceeding is pending.
Failure to achieve a majority for either action would constitute a
dismissal of the statement of alleged violations.
   A disciplinary hearing is held in two parts.
   The first phase would determine whether or not the counts have
been proved. Counts are considered proved by a majority vote.
During this phase, witnesses for and against the person charged
could be heard and cross-examined. The burden of proof rests with
committee staff.
   The second phase would determine what action to recommend to the
House.
   If the committee decides a violation is technical, it could
direct that the violation be reported to the House without a
recommendation for a sanction.
   A reprimand is considered appropriate for serious violations,
censure is for more serious violations and expulsion is for the
most serious violations.
   A fine is considered appropriate if it is likely the violation
was committed to secure a financial benefit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
