<FIRST>r w PM-CIA-North     04-14 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CIA-North,440</SECOND>
<HEAD>CIA Agent Criticizes North</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-North Trial</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN L. HERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A CIA officer publicly condemned former White
House aide Oliver North for his actions during the Iran-Contra
affair, but the agency says he was not espousing an official CIA
position.
   ``The agency doesn't comment on a current matters in
litigation,'' said CIA spokesman Bill Devine.
   CIA officer Arthur S. Hulnick, speaking at American University
on Tuesday, condemned North's actions and said the covert operation
should have been handled by the CIA.
   ``You shouldn't use a bunch of amateurs to try to carry out a
covert action when they don't know what they're doing and that you
shouldn't use guys at the National Security Council staff _ willing
though they may be _ because as Ollie North admitted the other day,
he wasn't trained for it and we are,'' Hulnick said.
   Following his speech, in remarks to an Associated Press
reporter, Hulnick compared North's defense _ that he was just
following orders _ to the defense used by Nazi war criminals at the
Nuremberg trials.
   ``I thought we settled this 40 years ago,'' he said.
   Hulnick said North's defense is also the same one used by Army
Lt. William Calley, which didn't wash when the Vietnam War officer
said he had massacred civilians at My Lai because he was following
orders.
   Devine said Hulnick is a full-time agency officer and the CIA's
coordinator for academic affairs, but Hulnick is ``not exactly in
the loop'' regarding the Iran-Contra affair. Devine would neither
confirm nor deny if Hulnick is an active case officer.
   ``He's a man with a long career in the agency,'' DeVine said.
   During his speech, Hulnick said the Reagan administration's
Iran-Contra program was ``bad policy, badly carried out. We've
learned a lesson from that.''
   Hulnick said such covert actions in the Bush administration
would likely be carried out by CIA, not the NSC.
   ``There's an interesting signal being sent,'' Hulnick said.
``When the Bush administration came into office they selected an
officer to serve as intelligence manager in the National Security
Council staff who is not a covert action guy, in fact he's not even
an agency (CIA) officer.''
   The appointee is Bill Working, the NSC's senior director for
intelligence programs.
   ``He's a former Air Force officer whose job on the intelligence
community staff was to deal with the budget and management. What
this tells me is that the administration is going to be more
interested in long-term planning to deal with things like the START
treaty rather than in covert action of some kind or another,''
Hulnick said.
</TEXT>
