<FIRST>r w PM-Governors-Trade     04-14 0465</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Governors-Trade,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>For Release 11 a.m. EDT; Time set by source</HEAD>
<HEAD>Governors Association Calls for Focus on International Trade</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Governors can encourage more international
trade by businesses within their states and should appoint
top-level ``trade czars'' to give exports a higher priority, a
group of the nation's governors said today.
   The National Governors' Association's task force on foreign
markets said in a report that states must develop new links with
foreign countries if their citizens are to succeed in a future
economy that will be increasingly dependent on international trade.
   ``While the federal government sets the rules on trade, success
in developing and expanding foreign markets depends on the
decisions of thousands of corporations and business people,'' said
Virginia Gov. Gerald Baliles, a Democrat and chairman of the
governors' association. ``State governments are positioned to
help.''
   The task force of governors, which included unsuccessful
Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis, the three-term
governor of Massachusetts, was releasing the report at a news
conference today.
   The governors have made international trade a focus of their
gatherings this year. In February the governors' association
released a report calling on states to require more international
instruction in public schools and to offer foreign languages to
students as early as the first grade.
   The report said each state should come up with its own realistic
and innovative plan for finding new markets and developing new
products that will be in demand by foreign nations. Governors can
elevate foreign trade to a top priority and increase public
awareness of the connections between their own economy and
international markets, it said.
   ``We can do something about international competition,'' Baliles
said. ``We can develop an export culture. We can develop programs
that identify markets.''
   The report suggested governors appoint a ``trade czar,'' an
official with state cabinet-level rank who would direct and
coordinate the state plan for encouraging international trade.
   It said state governments should help firms obtain financing for
export deals, either through direct loans and loan-guarantee
programs, or by serving as brokers and clearinghouses to match
commercial lenders with businesses.
   The report recommended groups of states consider pooling
resources for trade and tourism promotion and strengthen cultural
exchanges with foreign countries.
   States and governors have looked for ways to increase
international trade in recent years, and many governors have gone
on foreign trips to promote trade.
   The report cited recent successes in new markets, such as the
sale of Mississippi catfish to the Soviet Union. It said Virginia
chicken processors have begun exporting chicken feet, once
discarded as waste, to the Far East, where they are considered a
delicacy.
   ``Business as usual is just not enough,'' the report said. ``As
the world gets smaller, state initiatives must become more
far-reaching.''
</TEXT>
