<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0430EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Exxon-Money     04-14 0321</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon-Money,320</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Making Oil Spill Down Payment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Exxon Corp. is releasing a $15 million
down payment for the Alaska oil spill in an agreement announced one
day after Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan publicly complained about
delays.
   ``I am pleased that Exxon has acknowledged its long-term
responsibility to provide not only for the cleanup but for the
far-reaching effects (of the spill),'' Lujan said Thursday when the
agreement was announced.
   The ``up front'' money is to help assess the environmental
damage caused by the Exxon Valdez oil spill and plan for a recovery.
   On Wednesday, Lujan had complained that Exxon was not moving as
fast as he would like in providing the money. He said government
and Exxon attorneys had been negotiating for 10 days without an
agreement.
   But the department announced late Thursday that the oil company
had earlier in the day agreed on procedures for transferring the
$15 million to the government, with about half of that immediately
to be distributed to four federal agencies already working in
Alaska.
   The government has said it wants the $15 million in advance so
authorities, including the state of Alaska, can develop a long-term
recovery plan and assess the extent of damage along Alaska's
southern coast to wildlife, waterfowl, fish and public lands.
   Lujan has said that eventually these costs, separate from the
direct cleanup costs, are likely to be ``in the tens of millions''
of dollars.
   Lujan said he considers the money ``an initial step'' in Exxon
paying for the environmental damages caused by one of its tankers
when the vessel ran aground in Prince William Sound, spilling more
than 10 million gallons of oil into the pristine waters.
   Exxon spokesmen said in response to Lujan's complaints that they
were perplexed by his remarks. The spokesmen said the oil company
all along has been willing to provide the money, although
procedures had to be worked out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
