<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0645EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w BC-WrightExcerpts     04-14 1015</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Wright Excerpts,1090</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wright's Statement Defending Himself Against Ethics Charges</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Wright Probe Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are excerpts from House Speaker Jim
Wright's statement Thursday as he defended himself against ethics
charges.
   It appears from news accounts that the Committee on Standards of
Official Conduct has made a decision that there may be some reason
to believe that I, in my personal business dealings, could have
violated some rules of the House. ...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   I have asked the committee for the opportunity to appear ... to
answer every question they may wish to ask, and to demonstrate that
there is clear and convincing proof that I have not violated those
rules of the House.
   I am confident that in the 34 years I've served in the Congress,
I have not violated any of those basic rules nor any commonly
accepted standard of ethical conduct. ...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   I think I am the most fortunate of men to have been privileged
to serve in this institution.
   And certainly under no circumstances would I knowingly or
intentionally violate any of its rules.
   And I am convinced that I can demonstrate that to the
satisfaction of the committee or of any other reasonable person. ...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   I'm not accused of any personal immorality or of any dishonesty
or of misusing tax dollars.
   We're dealing here with three issues concerning my personal
finances and the technical reporting requirements of the Congress.
...
   ... Questions concern whether my wife's employment, at a salary
of $18,000 a year, for a small corporation in which we provided
half the capitalization and owned half the stock, was truly and
properly employment, or whether it was some concealed gift.
   The second question involves whether or not my business partner,
George Mallick, had a direct interest in legislation, as defined
under the rules of the House.
   And the third question involves whether royalties that I
received from a book that I wrote were properly received as
royalties, or whether they actually should have been reported in
some other way as a gift or an honorarium.
   I am prepared to demonstrate that in each of these instances, no
rule has been violated. ...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   I must say that I do find that personally offensive, for anyone
to suggest that my wife, Betty, did not perform services worth
$18,000.
   It is quite interesting to observe, I believe, that both before
and after the few years that she worked for our small investment
corporation, Betty made considerably more money than the $18,000 a
year that she accepted from the corporation for serving it in many,
many capacities. ...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Those who are married to people in public office, in the
Congress, are entitled to lives of their own.
   Perhaps half of the wives of members of Congress, spouses of
members of Congress, are engaged or employed in a professional or
business relationship on their own. ...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   I want to say to you that my wife is a good, decent, caring,
thoroughly honorable person.
   I'll damned well fight to protect her honor and her integrity
against any challenge by any source, whatever the cost. ...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   I've known Mr. Mallick and he's been a personal friend of mine
for the better part of 30 years _ more than a quarter of a century.
   In all the years that I've known him, he has never once asked me
to intercede in his behalf with any branch of government, any
agency of government, to do anything for him personally in my
official capacity.
   Not one time has he ever asked me to vote for or against any
piece of legislation, any provision of law, any amendment.
   It just never has happened _ not one single time. ...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   I have not received gifts of the type forbidden from Mr. Mallick.
   And even if I had, they would not be forbidden, because he has
never had a special interest in legislation. ...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Now, the third question involves the publishing of books that I
wrote _ a little book called ``Reflections of a Public Man.''
   I have written other books that have been published and I got
advance payments for the other books and relatively smaller
royalties.
   But the rules of the House do not stipulate what size royalty
you should get.
   The rules clearly exempt royalty income from books from the
outside earning limitations that are imposed. ...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   I've abided by the rules.
   I have been interested in a widespread distribution of the book,
yes.
   I want people to buy the book, yes. ...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   It has been suggested that because one or more organizations to
which I had made a speech had seen fit to purchase copies of the
book, distribute them among their members, or students or others,
that therefore, I was trying to avoid the outside earning
limitations imposed on honoraria, and actually was receiving a
honorarium for the speech.
   Well, that was never my intention.
   I never asked anybody to buy books in exchange for my making a
speech. ...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   I've reported my wife's source of income, I've reported every
penny of income that I made from the sale of the books and from the
corporation in which we own half interest.
   The question involves whether I should have reported them in one
column or in another column.
   And I believe I reported them in the right column. ...
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   I am 66 years of age.
   Sixty-six years of living and giving, striving and sometimes
failing, and sometimes succeeding, treating my fellow man with
decency, and dignity, and respect, I believe have earned me a
reputation as a person of decency, and as a person of honor, and as
a person of integrity.
   I know that my wife deserves to be known in that way, and that,
to me, is the most important thing, and the only really important
thing, and for my good name which is the legacy I intend to leave
my children and my grandchildren.
   I will fight to the last ounce of conviction and energy that I
possess.
</TEXT>
