<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0305EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     04-14 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Off, Share Prices Rebound</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar lost ground against the Japanese
yen Friday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange
moderately rebounded in the afternoon session despite losses in
early trading.
   The dollar closed at 132.45 yen, down 0.35 yen from Thursday's
132.80-yen finish. The currency opened at 132.00 yen and fluctuated
in a range of 131.92 yen to 132.53 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, which lost
192.51 points Thursday, regained 86.50 points, or 0.26 percent, to
finish the week's trading at 33,150.44 points.
   Although the index shed 138.67 points by the end of the morning
session, it gained ground in the afternoon.
   Dealers said the market's main index recovered as institutional
investors started to pick up cheaper issues.
   In the currency market, traders said the dollar fell in Tokyo
after slipping in New York to 132.06 yen, down 0.99 yen from its
133.05 yen close on Wednesday.
   The U.S. currency weakened in overseas dealings after a rise in
Swiss interest rates and the appointment of a new West German
finance minister, the traders said.
   Nervousness over U.S. trade figures was also discouraging
trading in the foreign exchange market, a dealer at a Japanese
commercial bank said on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
