<FIRST>r i PM-Vanuatu     04-14 0276</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Vanuatu,0284</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals Court Frees Former President Convicted In Coup Attempt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT VILA, Vanuatu (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An appeals court today threw out the
convictions of former President Sokomanu and three politicians who
were accused of trying to overthrow the elected government of this
South Pacific island chain.
   The official Radio Vanuatu said the Vanautu Court of Appeals'
ruling was greeted with wild celebrations in Port Vila, the capital.
   The court ruled there was insufficient evidence to convict
Sokomanu, his nephew Barak Sope and two other politicians allegedly
involved in the coup attempt.
   On March 7, Sokomanu was sentenced to six years in prison, Sope
and opposition leader Maxime Carolot were sentenced to five years
and former member of Parliament Willie Jimmy was sentenced to two
years.
   Sokomanu was accused of inciting mutiny within Vanuatu's
paramilitary forces in December in an attempt to replace the
elected government of Prime Minister Walter Lini with an interim
administration headed by Sope.
   Sokomanu, who had been president since 1980, was dismissed from
office in January by the Electoral College, which accused him of
gross misconduct.
   Sokomanu and the other defendants were arrested in late
December. At the time of his arrest, Sokamanu acknowledged that his
action was unconstitutional but said Lini was unable to govern
after suffering a stroke.
   Sope, a minister for transport, tourism and public works, had
been engaged in a power struggle with Lini for more than a year.
   Vanuatu, formerly the Anglo-French New Hebrides, had been
jointly administered by Britain and France since 1906 until it was
granted independence in 1980. Vanuatu, about 1,200 miles northeast
of Sydney, Australia, has a population of about 130,000.
</TEXT>
