<NOTE>Japan Charged With Destroying Rain Forests</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A private environmental group charges that
Japan is speeding the destruction of tropical rain forest in
southeast Asia because of its demand for timber.
   ``Tropical forests are being destroyed, for ineffective plywood
uses and even disposable chopsticks,'' said Robert Buschbacher,
director of the World Wildlife Fund's forestry program.
   ``As forests are eradicated in Asia, Japan will look towards
South America _ specifically the Amazon _ to exploit,'' Buschbacher
said in a statement released with the report on Thursday.
   The report, entitled ``Timber from the South Seas,'' said that
in 1987 Japan got 96 percent of its tropical hardwoods from Sarawak
and Sabah in Malaysia, and from Papua New Guinea. A statement by
the fund said some of the world's most biologically valuable
forests are threatened with destruction in Sabah and Sarawak, on
the island of Borneo.
