<NOTE>Government Seeks Fines Against Illinois Manufacturer</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government is seeking $1.4 million in
fines from an Illinois manufacturer of catalytic converter
replacement pipes that the Environmental Protection Agency charges
are ineffective.
   A formal complaint was filed by the Justice Department on behalf
of the EPA in federal court in Chicago against Ced's Inc., of
Addison, Ill., the EPA said Thursday.
   The EPA accused the company, which also does business as
Products for Power, of failing to abide by a 1987 settlement
agreement in which the company allegedly said it would pay $75,000
in fines and stop selling the replacement pipes.
   The pipes, rather than helping automobile performance, ``are
merely lengths of plain exhaust tubing cut to fit in place of
catalytic converters and offer no performance advantages over
properly functioning catalytic converters,'' said the EPA.
