<NOTE>Extension Power Strips Being Recalled</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A New Jersey company is recalling extension
power strips sold in North Carolina and the Washington, D.C., area
because they could give users a severe electrical shock.
   The power strip is a foot-long, beige-colored bar containing six
ordinary electrical receptacles, an on-off switch, a circuit
breaker and a three-wire power cord six feet long. The base is
labeled ``Temporary Power Tap Model No. WP-002B, Made in Taiwan, UL
46K7, E95914.''
   The receptacles might not be grounded, the Consumer Product
Safety Commission said Thursday. So far, no injuries have been
reported.
   About 6,700 strips were sold by Rose's Stores of Henderson,
N.C., Colonial Pottery of Morehead City, N.C., and Trak Auto
Stores, in the Washington area.
   The importer, Collins Company Ltd. of Mount Olive, N.J., said
owners could return the strips to Trak, Rose's or Colonial for a
refund, according to the commission. Owners also may write Collins
at 450 Clark Drive, Mount Olive, N.J. 07828 or call 1-800-645-7212
extension 207 for instructions on returning the strips.
