<FIRST>r i PM-Japan-Scandal     04-14 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Scandal,0557</SECOND>
<HEAD>Top Politician Admits Accepting Funds From Scandal-Ridden Firm</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The major bribery scandal shaking the Japanese
government widened further today as the country's second most
powerful leader admitted his wife was paid about $60,000 by Recruit
Co.
   Shintaro Abe, secretary general of the governing Liberal
Democratic Party, acknowledged earlier news reports that Recruit
Co. paid his wife, Yoko, about $2,300 monthly as a consulting fee
from February 1986 to August 1988.
   ``I put my secretary entirely in charge of my fund-raising
affairs and neither my wife nor myself knew anything about it,''
said Abe in a news conference this morning. ``But I have found such
a deal took place and I admit it was a result of my ignorance.''
   Abe refused to give any further details. He said the fees
totaling about $60,000 were deposited into a bank account of his
secretary, who has been sick and hospitalized.
   Abe, the second most powerful Liberal Democrat after Takeshita,
was foreign minister and secretary general of the party when his
wife was paid the money. His disclosure followed statements by
Takeshita in Parliament Tuesday that he received about $1 million
from Recruit, an information services conglomerate.
   Both Abe and Takeshita are among 17 politicians and about 150
other influential people known to have bought at discount prices
hundreds of thousands of unlisted shares in a subsidiary of Recruit
_ transactions that generated substantial profits when the share
price soared after over-the-counter trading began.
   The stock transactions were not considered illegal, but Recruit
also paid hundreds of millions of yen to dozens of influential
politicians as political contributions, raising suspicions that it
was seeking favors in return.
   So far, 14 people, including two former vice ministers and an
ex-chairman of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp., Hisashi
Shinto, have been arrested on charges of bribery and securities law
violations in connection with the affair, and three Cabinet
ministers, including former Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa, have
been forced to resign due to their links to the scandal.
   Today's disclosure showed Abe continued to receive funds from
Recruit even after the scandal surfaced last summer and
contradicted a declaration by the Liberal Democratic Party earlier
this year that no members of the current Takeshita administration
received donations from Recruit after last summer.
   Opposition parties, which are stalemating parliamentary debate
on the national budget for the fiscal year that began April 1,
quickly stepped up their criticism of Takeshita and his
administration.
   ``How can he not know about the deposits?'' said Yukihisa
Yoshida, a official of the Democratic Socialist Party, a major
opposition group. ``It is extremely serious that he was receiving
money even after the Recruit scandal surfaced.''
   Shun Ohide, a official of the Japan Socialist Party, the largest
opposition group, said: ``Abe has been reported to be closely
linked to Recruit and I think it (today's revelation) was only part
of it. After all these revelations, the Liberal Democratic Party
should resign.''
   Despite media surveys showing his public support rate has
dropped below 10 percent _ to 7.8 percent in a poll by the
nationwide television network TV-Asahi _ Takeshita has refused
calls for his resignation, vowing to carry out political reforms
and restore public trust in his administration.
</TEXT>
