<FIRST>r i PM-Cambodia-Sihanouk 1stLd-Writethru   04-14 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia-Sihanouk, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0477,0513</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prince Criticizes Governments For `Embracing' Phnom Penh</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with five grafs to ADD details of Vietnamese occupation.
Picks up graf 4 pvs, `The prince ...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some countries now support the
Vietnamese-backed government in Cambodia, a change that poses ``the
greatest danger to our nation,'' Cambodian resistance leader Prince
Norodom Sihanouk said.
   A text of the prince's statement, seen today in Bangkok, was
made Wednesday during a Cambodian New Year's Day message over
resistance radio.
   Sihanouk leads a three-party guerrilla coalition fighting
Vietnamese forces that invaded Cambodia in 1978 and installed an
allied government in Phnom Penh. Vietnam announced last week it
will withdraw its remaining 50,000 troops by Sept. 30 and asked
other countries to abide by pledges to stop aiding the guerrillas.
   The occupation of Cambodia by Vietnam has been, along with the
Soviet presence in Afghanistan, one of the major East-West issues.
   China had vowed not to improve relations with Moscow until the
Vietnamese left Cambodia. And Vietnam's own efforts to obtain aid
and recognition from the United States in the aftermath of the
Vietnam War were frustrated by Washington's insistence that Hanoi
withdraw its troops from Cambodia first.
   The prince previously has criticized Thailand, which gives
sanctuary to his guerrillas, for hosting Cambodian Prime Minister
Hun Sen for an unprecedented visit to Thailand in January.
   Sihanouk's son, Prince Norodom Ranariddh, said recently that he
was saddened because Thailand and its allies in the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations have lessened their once-firm support for
key resistance proposals on ending the war.
   In the broadcast, Sihanouk said, ``Some foreigners, governments,
and some major newspapers of the Western world have currently
changed their attitude to wanting to embrace Vietnam's colonialism
and (the Heng Samrin government in Phnom Penh). This poses the
greatest danger to our nation.''
   These groups, the prince said, ``are doing what they can to make
us remain Vietnam's slaves all our lives.''
   Some governments and groups have been kept a distance from the
resistance because of Sihanouk's alliance in the guerrilla
coalition with the fanatical communist Khmer Rouge. The Khmer Rouge
killed hundreds of thousands of people in Cambodia before Vietnam's
invasion toppled it. With 30,000-40,000 troops, it is the mightiest
of the guerrilla groups.
   Apparently in response to this, Sihanouk said, ``We do not need
to love the Khmer Rouge. However, if we do not fight within this
tripartite framework, it is impossible because we need to have
strength and unity among the three parties to fight the Vietnamese
enemies.''
   Sihanouk is to meet with Hun Sen, prime minister of the Phnom
Penh government, next month in Indonesia for their fourth round of
bilateral peace talks.
   In the broadcast, Sihanouk said he agreed to the meeting because
otherwise he would be accused of blocking the peace process and
because French government emissaries told him on March 26 that Hun
Sen had two concessions to make. The prince said he did not yet
know what these concessions were.
</TEXT>
