<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0559EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-SocialSecurity     04-14 0400</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Social Security,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agency Quits Verifying Social Security Numbers for Businesses</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT GREENE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Social Security Administration will stop
verifying citizens' Social Security numbers for credit bureaus and
financial institutions because of a recent Supreme Court ruling on
the privacy of government records.
   Commissioner Dorcas R. Hardy announced the decision late
Thursday, days after a senator called the verification practice for
private businesses ``the largest breach of privacy in the history
of the program.''
   ``The Social Security Administration takes very seriously its
important responsibility of protecting the privacy of the records
it maintains on over 200 million Americans,'' Hardy said in
announcing the change.
   She said a Supreme Court decision March 22 ``significantly
narrowed the circumstances under which information on individuals
can be released.'' Under that 9-0 decision, the court said the FBI
may withhold its ``rap sheets'' on 24 million Americans from public
disclosure.
   The move will stop the SSA from verifying 140 million names and
Social Security submitted by TRW Credit Data, Hardy said. The firm
made the huge request last year, prompting Hardy to order a review
of the legal status of the release of such information.
   Sen. David H. Pryor, D-Ark., who raised the issue Monday at a
hearing of the Senate Committee on Aging, hailed the decision. But
he told The Washington Post, ``This action comes too late to
protect some 150,000 people whose files were violated during a test
run conducted for TRW and for more than 3 million people on whom
verifications were conducted for Citibank and other firms in past
years.''
   Pryor this week wrote Secretary of Health and Human Services
Secretary Louis W. Sullivan to investigate verifications by TRW and
Citicorp. Pryor had called them ``the largest breach of privacy in
the history of the program.''
   Since the late 1970s, Social Security has routinely performed
``negative verifications'' by telling businesses upon request
whether a name and Social Security do not match. It would not say
whether a name and number match.
   No other information, such as wages and benefits, was given
without the individual person's permission. And the agency would
not grant requests for a person's Social Security number.
   The verifications were made under an interpretation of the
Freedom of Information Act.
   The agency will continue to verify Social Security numbers for
employers who must have the correct numbers for workers, Hardy said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890414-0057 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0559EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Cyprus-Maronites     04-14 0769</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cyprus-Maronites,0797</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lebanon's Maronites Fight Moslems, But Live In Peace In Cyprus</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HASAN MROUE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KORMAKITI, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maronite Catholics are locked in a
civil war with their Moslem countrymen in Lebanon but they live in
peace with Moslem neighbors on this Mediterranean island, itself
divided by another war.
   Yet both Maronite communities are struggling for survival _
those in Lebanon against political domination by Syrian-backed
forces, and their brethren in Cyprus against shrinking numbers.
   Cyprus lies only 100 miles northwest of Lebanon, where a civil
war between Christians and Moslems has raged for 14 years.
   Some 5,000 Maronites live in Cyprus, divided since 1974 when the
Turkish Army invaded in the wake of a short-lived coup by
supporters of union with Greece.
   Only 350 Maronites still live in northern Cyprus, controlled by
Turkey and largely populated by Moslem Turkish Cypriots.
   Clustered in four villages on the northwestern tip of the
island, the community is dwindling as young people move to the more
prosperous Greek Cypriot sector in the south, which is mainly
Christian.
   As the community in Kormakiti, Asomados, Karpacha and Ayia
Marina dwindles, so does the culture their ancestors first brought
to Cyprus 900 years ago when they fled Moslem persecution in Syria
and parts of Lebanon.
   The main Maronite sect, named after the 5th Century monk St.
Maroun, whose monastery in Syria was destroyed in 938 A.D. by
Moslem invaders, lived in the mountains.
   ``The new generation is going to Greek Cypriot schools and they
don't speak Arabic. Only the old people speak Arabic now,'' said
Archbishop Butros Gemayel, a relative of former Lebanese President
Amin Gemayel.
   He was elected last June in Lebanon and is the first
Cyprus-based Maronite archbishop in 300 years.
   The Maronites have remained neutral in the conflict between the
island's Turks and Greeks and are the only people outside the
United Nations peacekeeping force allowed to cross the island's
dividing Green Line unhindered once a month.
   ``We have nothing against the Turks. We saved many Turkish lives
during the war,'' said John Mavrides, the Parliamentary
representative of the Maronite community.
   ``Special sentiments link us to Lebanon, but the people of
Kormakiti are the only ones who still speak some Arabic,'' said
Mavrides.
   Kormakati, population 230, is the main Maronite village, 22
miles northwest of the capital, Nicosia.
   It has a school with 18 pupils under age 10, a church run by
94-year-old Father Antonios Terzi and the ``Lebanon'' cafe but no
hospital.
   ``The sick have to go to Kyrenia or Nicosia, but if it's very
serious, we call the doctor from a nearby Turkish Cypriot
village,'' said Amida Hannarusso, who runs Kormakiti's only cafe.
   In the 16th century 80,000 Maronites lived in 70 villages in
Cyprus. But, like other groups on the island, they suffered
persecution and massacres by the various invaders, including the
Moslem Turks.
   They survived. But when the Turks invaded in 1974, many of the
young people moved south with 200,000 Greek Cypriots who either
fled or were expelled by the invaders. Some 70,000 Turkish Cypriots
fled north.
   Most of the Maronites remaining in the north are old people who
mainly work the land.
   The Greek Cypriot authorities send food supplies twice a month
to the Maronite villages and provide free education for Maronite
children whose parents live in the north. Maronites in the Greek
Cyriot sector also provide financial assistance.
   Those who moved south have largely integrated, scattered over
the Greek sector, rather than living in exclusively Maronite
neighborhoods.
   Valentino Piribitsi, a Maronite born in Cyprus three years
before the Turkish invasion, said: ``We're all Cypriots.''
   Piribitsi has lived in Nicosia since his parents left Kormakiti
in 1980 so he and his sister could attend a Christian secondary
school.
   However, another young Maronite, Kyriakos, who declined to give
his family name, said he feels his brethren are discriminated
against by the Greek Cypriots, who are mainly Greek Orthodox.
   ``If a Maronite and a Greek Cypriot with the same qualifications
apply for a job, the Greek Cypriot would be chosen in most cases,''
said Kyriakos, 22.
   Gemayel acknowledged his community now faces ``an identity
crisis'' in Cyprus.
   The Maronite link with Lebanon is still strong because ``that's
where their roots are, that's the religious center,'' he said.
   But if the island was reunited and the Cypriot national identity
becomes stronger than loyalty to the community, ``the Maronites'
longing for Lebanon will only be religious, rather than ethnic,''
he lamented.
   Kyriakos noted: ``I don't care much about Lebanon, like the
older generation does. I don't identify with the Lebanese. I'm
Cypriot.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
