<HEAD>Judge Rejects 540-Pound Coke Dealer's Plea for Sympathy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANFORD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted cocaine dealer seeking a light
sentence cited his 540-pound build, but the judge said the argument
carried little weight.
   James Edward Roath said he felt ``less than a human being''
because of his obesity. Dealing drugs made him feel needed, argued
Roath's attorney, Donald Lykkebak.
   ``Where was his conscience?'' Circuit Judge Robert McGregor
responded. ``That is a matter of the mind, not of the body.''
   The judge sentenced Roath, 32, to 3{ years in prison and a
$50,000 fine.
   Holding onto a table and podium for support, Roath apologized to
the judge Wednesday and tried to get him to agree to a shorter
sentence than that allowed by state guidelines.
   The judge was not moved, however. He said Roath should learn to
cope with his handicap and not use it as an excuse for
``contributing to a national epidemic of cocaine.''
