<FIRST>u i PM-India-Afghanistan     04-14 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India-Afghanistan,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Afghan Ambassador Accuses U.S. Of Violating Geneva Accord</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARLEEN FISHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghanistan's ambassador to India,
speaking on the first anniversary of the Geneva Accord that led to
the withdrawal of Soviet troops from his country, accused the
United States today of ignoring ``the spirit and the letter'' of
the U.N.-sponsored agreement.
   ``The Geneva Accord is fully implemented by Afghanistan and the
Soviet Union, but unfortunately the other parties concerned have
not implemented it and the situation has gotten more tense than
ever before,'' Abdul Samad Azhar told reporters.
   He repeated his government's accusations that the United States
and Pakistan were continuing to arm Moslem guerrillas who have
trying the past decade to overthrow the Soviet-style party that
took power by coup and assassination in 1978.
   Afghanistan and Pakistan pledged in the Geneva Accord not to
interfere in each other's internal affairs. The Soviet Union, whose
troops fought alongside Afghan government troops against the
guerrillas for nine years, and the United States, one of the
guerrillas' staunchest backers, signed as guarantors.
   Under the accord, Moscow withdrew its 115,000 soldiers from
Afghanistan in phases. The last Soviet soldier left Afghanistan on
Feb. 15.
   The Soviets continue to supply President Najib's army with
weapons, including long-range Scud-B missiles now used by
government troops against the guerrillas besieging the strategic
eastern city of Jalalabad.
   ``The Soviet Union fully implemented the accord. They withdrew
their troops,'' Azhar said. ``But the other side, the United States
of America, did not respect the letter and spirit. They are
continuing supplying weapons to the rebels. Every day more
sophisticated weapons are being supplied.''
   Asked what these weapons were, the ambassador listed
anti-aircraft Stinger missiles and surface-to-surface missiles that
he said had ranges of 18 to 50 miles.
   Azhar also criticized the slowness with which foreign aid is
arriving for the reconstruction of his country. A year ago, he
said, there had been talk of an international program similar to
the Marshall Plan for Europe after the devastation of World War II.
   ``Unfortunately, in practice we see a Marshall Plan for the
destruction of Afghanistan, not the reconstruction,'' the
ambassador said.
   Western nations have been reluctant to send aid that could help
prolong the longevity of the Najib government. In addition, with
civil war raging throughout much of Afghanistan, relief agencies of
the United Nations and other international groups say they are
hamstrung in operating outside Kabul.
   The ambassador reiterated his government's position that it was
willing to call new elections under U.N. supervision. The
mujahedeen guerrillas, whose name means Islamic holy warriors, have
refused to participate in any election while Najib and his People's
Democratic Party of Afghanistan remains in power.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
