<FIRST>r a PM-PalmBeachCameras     04-14 0285</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Palm Beach Cameras,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Surveillance Cameras at Entrances to Palm Beach Proposed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PALM BEACH, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A proposal to place video surveillance
cameras on bridges leading to their ritzy island is winning support
from residents despite warnings it would focus a spotlight on the
town's elitist image.
   More than 40 residents turned out in support of the plan to
record every car, truck, bicycle and pedestrian heading to the
island when it was discussed Wednesday by the Public Safety
Committee.
   But others recalled negative national publicity the town
received about a law requiring blue-collar workers to carry
identification cards, declared unconstitutional by a federal judge
in 1985.
   ``This type of situation might work against us in our public
image,'' Phillip Radlauer said. ``We've been taking a terrible
beating as an elitist community.''
   Robert Oreck, a landlord, proposed the plan to increase security.
   ``Let's put the criminals on notice _ Palm Beach, Florida, is
not the place to ply their trade,'' Oreck said.
   Town Attorney John Randolph said the plan does not appear to be
unconstitutional.
   ``There is no expectation of privacy in one's use of a public
street,'' he said.
   Security concerns have been heightened after a woman from nearby
Lake Worth was killed Feb. 6 and her body was dumped in the road
next to the Bath &amp; Tennis Club.
   Proponents of the plan also cited the case of Mark Baltes, who
was run over and killed in 1986 by a car driven by a man who lived
in West Palm Beach.
   Under the plan, police officers would review tapes made during a
specified period before and after a crime.
   The committee sent the proposal to the Town Council, which meets
Monday.
</TEXT>
