<DOCNO> AP890414-0062 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0614EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Firefighter'sJoke     04-14 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Firefighter's Joke,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Firefighter's Joke About Burning Vacant House Backfires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ANNAPOLIS, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bored firefighter who jokingly told two
teen-agers calling the station to set a fire must pay for the
damage to a vacant house which the youths subsequently torched, a
judge has ruled.
   Barry Scott McDonald, 21, was found guilty of storefront burning
and ordered to pay for the $1,630 damage the blaze did to the
house's front porch.
   Under Maryland law, someone who incites such a crime can be
punished the same way as the person who commits it.
   ``Apparently they (the teen-agers) knew some of the guys at the
station and were joking back and forth. People in the background
were shouting addresses and places to set fires,'' McDonald's
attorney, Barry Diamond, said Thursday in recounting the telephone
call.
   ``But the kid who actually set the fire pointed his finger at my
client,'' he said.
   In Anne Arundel County Circuit Court on Tuesday, Diamond told
Judge Bruce C. Williams that the July 31 call to the Orchard Beach
fire station came on a night when the firefighters on duty,
including McDonald, had nothing to do.
   Soon after, the fire department was called to a fire at an
abandoned house a few blocks away.
   McDonald thought the teens could tell he was kidding, Diamond
said.
   But McDonald told colleagues after the fire was reported, ``See,
I told you he would do it,'' Assistant State's Attorney Philip
Caroom said.
   McDonald, a volunteer with the 45-member company since 1985, was
suspended from firefighting duties after the blaze, said company
Chief Walt Snyder.
   Both McDonald and the teen-agers live in Orchard Beach, a tiny
community about 10 miles south of Baltimore.
   Williams sentenced McDonald to probation before judgment, which
allows him to keep a clean criminal record if he completes his
three years of probation without incident.
   He also will have to pay court costs and perform 50 hours of
community service, although he is barred from taking part in any
firefighting work.
   The names of the teen-agers and the status of their cases were
withheld because of juvenile court confidentiality rules. However,
Caroom said they were ordered along with McDonald to pay for damage
to the house.
   Storefront burning refers to arson at an unoccupied building.
Under Maryland law, it is less serious than arson but still carries
a maximum penalty of 20 years in prison.
   ``I would say he's extremely lucky that the kids did select an
unoccupied structure and that there was minimal damage done to
it,'' Caroom said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
