<FIRST>r i PM-BRF--India-TeaTime     04-14 0138</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--India-Tea Time,0139</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indian Scam: The Cup That Doesn't Cheer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thieves operating out of a railroad
station near Bombay have come up with a new ploy: a cup of tea that
packs a powerful and costly punch, an Indian news agency reported
today.
   United News of India said the thieves mingle with licensed tea
vendors on the platform at Kalyan, 25 miles northeast of Bombay,
and sell tea spiked with intoxicants. Gang members then board the
trains as passengers, wait for their victims to nod off, and
relieve them of cash and other belongings.
   UNI said a memo warning of the scam had been received recently
by the Central Railways Authority. The news agency did not say how
long the gang had been operating or how many people might have been
victimized.
</TEXT>
