<FIRST>r a PM-People-Stassen     04-14 0147</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People-Stassen,0156</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Gov. Stassen Calls Rock Station To Win Prize</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Disc jockeys at a rock station didn't think
they'd get a response when they invited former Gov. Harold Stassen
to call in and win $99.50 on his 82nd birthday.
   The perennial presidential candidate took advantage of the
chance and said he'll use the money for his project to improve the
United Nations.
   John Hines and Bob Berglund, the morning hosts at WLOL-FM,
declared Thursday, Stassen's birthday, ``Harold Stassen Call In and
Win Day.''
   At 8:45 a.m., they got the call.
   ``Bergie,'' Hines told his partner over the air, ``say good
morning to Harold Stassen.''
   ``Well, you're kidding,'' a shocked Berglund said. ``Good
morning.''
   ``Good morning,'' Stassen replied.
   ``Somebody told him and he called in,'' said producer Mark
Bauer. ``I don't think he was listening.''
   Stassen was Minnesota governor from 1939 through 1943.
</TEXT>
