<DOCNO> AP890414-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0635EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-SriLanka     04-14 0538</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Sri Lanka,0553</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sinhalese Evacuated After 41 Die In Car Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Sinhalese in the port of
Trincomalee took refuge in a navy dockyard today after 41 people
were killed in a car bombing, military officials said.
   Indian peacekeeping troops patrolling the city reported no new
violence, but a curfew imposed after Thursday's blast remained in
effect. Indian and Sri Lankan officials blamed the bombing on Tamil
militants.
   Sri Lankan military officials in Colombo said three people died
in hospitals today of injuries suffered in the blast. Thirty-eight
others died on Thursday, and at least 54 were injured.
   Most of Trincomalee's estimated 12,000 Sinhalese residents were
evacuated to the dockyard for their safety, the Sri Lankan
officials said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Tamils account for about 60 percent of the city's 35,000 people,
while Sinhalese make up 35 percent. There also is a small Moslem
minority.
   Nalin Seneviratna, head of the provincial council in
northeastern Sri Lanka, said the car that exploded outside a hotel
and shopping arcade was packed with an estimated 110 pounds of
explosives hidden under a pile of coconuts.
   He said all but two of those killed were Sinhalese who were
shopping for gifts and sweets to mark their New Year's Day, which
was celebrated Thursday. The others were members of the Tamil
minority, which observed the New Year's Day today.
   Shortly after the explosion, angry Sinhalese attacked Tamils. At
least four Tamils were stabbed to death and seven were wounded,
said Seneviratna.
   Sri Lankan military officials blamed a group of Tamil
extremists, the Eelam People's Revolutionary Liberation Front, for
the blast. Indian officials blamed the largest Tamil rebel militia,
Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam.
   A spokesman for the Tigers in Colombo denied responsibility for
the explosion.
   The bombing was linked to the killing of six Tamil villagers on
Tuesday in remote Kurinchkerni village in Trincomalee district,
about 145 miles northeast of the capital Colombo, military
officials said.
   Indian peacekeeping troops have been in northern and eastern Sri
Lanka since July 1987 to disarm Tamil rebels and enforce a peace
accord aimed at ending the Tamil insurgency that began in 1983.
   At least 12,500 people, mostly Sinhalese, have been killed in
the Tamil insurrection and the backlash from Sinhalese extremists
opposed to the peace accord.
   Sinhalese militants claimed the accord gave too many concessions
to the Tamil minority and began a bloody campaign to dislodge the
government for signing the agreement with India.
   India became involved in the ethnic troubles of its southern
neighbor because of 60 million politically powerful Tamils in south
India.
   Tamils, mostly Hindus, comprise 18 percent of Sri Lanka's 16
million people. Militants have waged a war against the government
for an independent state in the north and east of the island
nation, where they are a majority.
   They claim they are discriminated against by the mostly Buddhist
Sinhalese, who make up 75 percent of the population.
   President Ranasinghe Premadasa had ordered a one-week truce and
offered amnesty to Sinhalese and Tamil rebels willing to surrender
arms. The explosion occurred on the second day of the cease-fire
that began to coincide with the local New Year.
</TEXT>
