<DOCNO> AP890414-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0641EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-AdoptionRights     04-14 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Adoption Rights,0457</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court: Dads Who Fail to Give Pre-Birth Support Lose Adoption Rights</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BILL KACZOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who fails to support his child's
mother emotionally and financially prior to birth loses his
standing in an adoption case, the Florida Supreme Court has ruled.
   ``Because prenatal care of the pregnant mother and unborn child
is critical to the well-being of the child and of society, the
biological father, wed or unwed, has a responsibility to provide
support during the pre-birth period,'' Justice Leander Shaw wrote
for the majority in a 6-1 opinion Thursday.
   Failure to provide that support can constitute abandonment.
Normally, a father's consent is required for adoption, but a father
who abandons his unborn child loses that right, the high court held.
   The ruling is important because it sets the precedent that the
father's level of ``prebirth support'' can be considered by a judge
to determine his standing in an adoption case.
   The ruling came in the case of an infant identified only as John
Doe to protect his identity. A judge in Orange County rejected the
request of the biological parents, dubbed Richard and Mary Roe, to
regain custody from the adoptive parents, Bob and Jane Doe.
   The Roes were unwed when the baby was born Sept. 12, 1986.
   The 5th District Court of Appeal in Daytona Beach reversed the
decision, but allowed the baby to stay with the adoptive parents
pending the Supreme Court ruling.
   In a sharply worded dissent, Justice Parker Lee McDonald wrote
that the majority has deprived the biological parents, now married,
of their child ``without a finding that the natural parents are
unfit in the slightest. I think it is a sad day.''
   When Mary Roe became pregnant, the father said he wasn't ready
to commit to marriage, in part because of financial pressure, and
urged her to have an abortion, Shaw wrote.
   She refused, lost her job and lived off public welfare and
charity. While Roe failed to provide support, they continued to see
each other and he initially voiced no objection to adoption,
although never giving formal consent.
   The Supreme Court also ruled the mother couldn't withdraw her
consent to the adoption, although she attempted to do so only a few
days after the child was given to the Does three days after the
baby was born.
   She contended her consent had been given under the duress of her
personal circumstances, but those circumstances changed when Roe
agreed to marry her.
   The high court held a mother can revoke her consent after
adoption only if another person had exerted coercion, duress or
fraud to procure that consent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
