<FIRST>r i PM-Austria-Scandal     04-14 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Austria-Scandal,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Interior Minister Resigns From Public Offices Over Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Interior Minister Karl Blecha
resigned today from his remaining government and party posts
because of a scandal over the mysterious sinking of a ship in 1977.
   Blecha, 55, once considered one of the most powerful officials
in the Socialist Party, stepped down as a parliamentary deputy and
as a deputy party chairman.
   He relinquished his ministerial post on Jan. 19.
   The Austria Press Agency quoted Blecha as saying he resigned
from his offices in order to fight allegations made against him in
connection with the so-called Lucona scandal.
   A parliamentary committee is investigating possible insurance
fraud in connection with the 1977 sinking of the vessel in the
Indian Ocean. Six sailors died.
   Blecha has denied aiding Udo Proksch, the main suspect in the
sinking who remains at large. Proksch is wanted on suspicion of
murder and insurance fraud.
   The Lucona's cargo was officially described as materials for a
uranium processing plant and was insured for $16 million. The
insurance company refused to pay, claiming the cargo was scrap
metal.
   Testifying before the investigating committee this week, Robert
Koeck, a senior security official in the Interior Ministry, said
that as interior minister Blecha had given instructions to stop
police investigations into the sinking.
   Leopold Gratz, another powerful Socialist Party official who
also is accused of aiding Proksch, resigned as president of
Parliament on Jan. 25. Both men have denied wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
