<DOCNO> AP890414-0074 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0653EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-France-Europe     04-14 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-France-Europe,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former President Heading Conservative List In European Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Valery Giscard d'Estaing said
today he will give up his seat in the National Assembly to head the
French conservative campaign in elections June 18 for the European
Parliament.
   Giscard d'Estaing, 62, also said he would be interested in
becoming speaker of the 518-member Parliament, made up of
representatives elected from the 12 countries of the European
Economic Community.
   The national council of the center-right Union for French
Democracy (UDF) voted Thursday night to join the rightist Rally for
the Republic (RPR) in backing a list of candidates headed by the
former president.
   One of the component parties of the UDF, the Union of the
Center, is expected to decide later this month to back a separate
list led by Simone Veil, a former speaker of the European
Parliament, rather than the joint UDF-RPR list.
   The UDF council rejected 49-13 a proposal, from a group calling
itself the ``Renovators,'' for calling a joint convention to try to
put together a list of younger candidates who might unite the
conservative and centrist forces.
   The Renovators, who include some of the most popular younger
leaders of both the UDF and RPR, have made a move in recent weeks
to displace a generation that has led the French center-right the
past 15 years.
   Giscard d'Estaing, president of France from 1974-81, is chairman
of the National Assembly's foreign affairs committee and president
of the UDF.
   He is not prohibited from sitting in both parliaments, but
giving up the National Assembly seat would emphasize his commitment
to working on the European political scene.
   Interviewed on French radio, Giscard d'Estaing said he would
like to be speaker of the European Parliament because he felt
``very involved in this European affair.''
   He said he would urge the centrists not to run a competing list
of candidates.
   Each member country elects members of the European Parliament in
mid-June for a five-year term using its own election laws. In
France, the system of proportional representation is used. The
Socialists have chosen former Premier Laurent Fabius, speaker of
the National Assembly, to head their list.
</TEXT>
