<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0659EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Laos-Drought     04-14 0263</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Laos-Drought,0270</SECOND>
<HEAD>United Nations Sending Emergency Food Aid To Laos</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.N. World Food Program is sending
an emergency shipment of 5,500 tons of rice to Laos to make up for
severe food shortages caused by drought, an official said today.
   The shipment is only enough food for a fraction of the more than
730,000 people affected by last year's drought, said Jane Blaxland,
director of operations of the agency's office for Thailand and Laos.
   A study by the World Food Program and the U.N. Food and
Agriculture Organization estimated the drought caused a shortage of
68,200 tons of rice, she said.
   The U.N. agency paid for the rice from emergency money and is
calling on the international community to finance further
shipments, Miss Blaxland said.
   The drought severely affected about 60 percent of the population
in Savannakhet, Champassak and Khammouane provinces, which a World
Food Program news release said normally account for 40 percent of
the country's rice.
   It said Laos is expected to face an acute food shortage
beginning this month as stocks from the 1988 growing season become
exhausted.
   ``Some people have been selling their buffalos since January to
buy rice,'' said Miss Blaxland, who visited Champassak two weeks
ago. ``We saw trucks full of buffalos leaving those districts to be
sold.
   ``We think we've seen the effects of malnutrition just about to
start among the children,'' she said.
   Laos, which has been under Communist rule since 1975, is one of
the world's poorest nations, with a per capita income estimated at
$135 in 1985.
</TEXT>
