<DOCNO> AP890414-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0706EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Lebanon     04-14 0428</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>25,000 Shells Fired In 20 Hours, French Humanitarian Effort Delayed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A fierce shelling duel between Syrian and
Christian gunners kept civilians off the streets today and delayed
a French humanitarian mission to Lebanon.
   Only a handful of people ventured out of basements and
underground bomb shelters early in the day to shop for food
supplies after the clashes subsided into sporadic mortar exchanges.
   By police count, 215 people have been killed and 727 wounded
since the current confrontation between Gen. Michel Aoun's
Christian troops and an alliance of Syrian and Druse forces started
March 8.
   A police spokesman said 25,000 shells and rockets slammed into
Beirut's Moslem and Christian sectors in the 20-hour duel that
coincided with the 14th anniversary of the outbreak of civil war in
1975.
   The exchange eased hours after an Arab League panel meeting in
Kuwait issued its third cease-fire appeal the past month.
   ``The committee repeats its calls for a cease fire ... and
continues its intensified efforts to put an end to the suffering of
the Lebanese people,'' said a statement by the six-member panel
headed by Kuwaiti Foreign Minister Sheik Sabah Ahmed Sabah.
   The statement also noted ``the failure of the warring sides in
Lebanon to abide by their pledges to consolidate the cease-fire.''
   The committee, formed in January, earlier wrapped up talks with
a delegation of right-wing Christian Lebanese politicians on ending
the current violence and solving a six-month political crisis that
threatens to cement the nation's de facto partition into sectarian
cantons.
   Two French navy vessels, the hospital ship La Rance and a
tanker, the Penhors, remained outside Lebanese territorial waters
awaiting sailing orders from French Humanitarian Assistance
Minister Bernard Kouchner, who is in Beirut.
   The hospital ship was due to drop anchor in Lebanese waters
Thursday and take Moslem and Christian wounded on board, but the
shelling forced ``postponement of the operation until further
notice,'' said a source with the Moslem Cabinet of acting prime
minister Salim Hoss.
   The tanker was to deliver fuel oil to Moslem- and
Christian-controlled ports so that power stations can continue
providing electricity.
   The main power distribution plant in Beirut's Christian Jamhour
suburb was struck in a rocket barrage Thursday, blacking out the
city and surrounding areas.
   ``The French-donated supplies of fuel oil will help us generate
power, but it cannot be distributed unless the Jamhour distribution
station is repaired,'' the electricity authority said in a
statement.
   ``Repair work cannot be launched unless a cease-fire is
reached,'' the statement added.
</TEXT>
