<FIRST>r i PM-Czech-Hijack     04-14 0229</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czech-Hijack,0235</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parents Of Teenage Hijackers Demand Extradition</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of two Czech teenagers
who hijacked a Hungarian plane last month have asked West German
authorities to extradite their children, the Communist Party daily
Rude Pravo reported today.
   Stefan Macicko and Dusan Styk, aged 16 and 17 years
respectively, shot their way onto a Malev Airlines jetliner March
29 and commandeered the plane to Frankfurt after the plane crew
told them the plane was incapable of flying all the way to the
United States.
   Czechoslovakia and West Germany have no extradition treaty and
on past occasions of airline terrorism, hijackers were always
prosecuted under West German law.
   ``The parents ... are aware of the seriousness of criminal acts
committed by their children as well as the ensuing consequences,''
the newspaper quoted Foreign Ministry spokesman Ivan Kulhanek as
saying.
   ``Although this is a very serious criminal act, the emotions of
parents cannot be overlooked,'' the daily added.
   ``The request should be judged from the point of view of good
neighhborly relations between Czechoslovakia and West Germany. Our
side has also confirmed the principle of reciprocity in case a West
German plane would be hijacked to Czechoslovakia,'' Kulhanek said.
   Letters in which the parents ask for extradition of their
children to Czechoslovak authorities were handed over to the West
German Embassy on Thursday, the paper reported.
</TEXT>
