<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0814EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NightStalker     04-14 0412</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Night Stalker,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecution Rests in `Night Stalker' Case</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecution rested its case against
defendant Richard Ramirez after a witness said Ramirez displayed
gruesome photographs of a murder victim and boasted: ``There's
blood behind the Night Stalker.''
   The close of the prosecution's case was far ahead of schedule.
   ``We had less actual testimony than we had at the preliminary
hearing, Deputy District Attorney P. Phillip Halpin said outside
court Thursday. He said he had dropped some witnesses in order to
present all of the evidence in 31 days of testimony over two months.
   Ramirez, 29, a drifter from El Paso, Texas, is charged with 13
gruesome murders and 30 related felonies in a string of nighttime
attacks that terrified Southern Californians in the summer of 1985.
   Superior Judge Michael Tynan scheduled the trial to resume May 1
with defense testimony.
   The final prosecution witness was David Laws, a sheriff's deputy
who guarded the defendant in his high-security area of the county
jail for a year and a half.
   Laws said that on Oct. 30, 1986, Ramirez summoned him and showed
him two grisly pictures of a murder victim.
   ``He said, `People come up here and call me a punk, and I show
them the pictures and say, `There's blood behind the Night
Stalker,' and they go away all pale,''' Laws testified.
   He identified one of the pictures he said Ramirez had displayed.
It showed victim Maxine Zazzara, who was stabbed and had her eyes
gouged out.
   Gerald Newbold, a sheriff's deputy who guarded Ramirez shortly
after his Aug. 30, 1985, arrest, testified he saw Ramirez drawing
``666'' and a pentagram, symbols of devil worship, in his own blood
on his cell floor.
   After six months of jury selection, testimony in the nearly
4-year-old case began Jan. 30. By the time the prosecution case
wound up Thursday, Halpin had called 137 witnesses and presented
521 pieces of evidence, including many gruesome photographs of the
Night Stalker victims.
   At one point, the trial was recessed for three weeks when
defense attorney Daniel Hernandez said he was too exhausted by
stress to continue. Another attorney, Ray Clark, was then appointed
to assist him and the trial went on.
   Clark has said the defense case will take two to four weeks. If
the estimate is correct, the trial could wrap up in far less than
the two years jurors had been told to expect.
</TEXT>
