<FIRST>r a PM-Wedtech-Moreno     04-14 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wedtech-Moreno,0371</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Wedtech Exec Gets 18-Month Prison Term</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former Wedtech Corp. executive who admitted
stealing millions of dollars from the now-defunct defense
contractor and bribing several public officials could be out of
jail by November, prosecutors say.
   Mario Moreno, a key government witness at the racketeering trial
of ex-Rep. Mario Biaggi, was sentenced at a secret court session
Thursday to 18 months in prison for conspiring to bribe public
officials and other corruption charges.
   Moreno, 47, former vice chairman of Wedtech, could have been
sentenced to 15 years in prison and $750,000 in fines. He has been
in custody since November and will be eligible for parole after
serving two-thirds of his sentence, or one year, authorities said.
   The sentencing by U.S. District Judge Charles E. Stewart was not
announced by prosecutors until after it was completed.
   In two weeks on the witness stand at the Biaggi trial, Moreno
admitted he and three other Wedtech officials paid millions of
dollars in bribes to obtain government contracts for Wedtech.
   Biaggi, 71, was sentenced to eight years in prison in November
after he was convicted of turning Wedtech into a racketeering
enterprise that paid millions in bribes and kickbacks.
   Five co-defendants also were convicted of various charges with
Biaggi, who began serving a prison sentence this week on an
unrelated bribery case.
   In a four-page letter assistant U.S. attorney Edward J.M. Little
sent to Stewart on Tuesday and made public Thursday, the prosecutor
detailed the extent of Moreno's cooperation.
   It said he supplied information that led to the conviction of
Biaggi, Biaggi's son, the former commander of the New York National
Guard, former Bronx Borough President Stanley Simon, former White
House aide Lyn Nofziger, the former head of the Small Business
Administration's New York office, two former Maryland legislators
and several others.
   Former Attorney General Edwin Meese III was investigated but
never charged with any wrongdoing in the Wedtech scandal, although
a special prosecutor criticized Meese's ethical decisions in the
case.
   Two former Meese business associates are slated to go on trial
next week on racketeering charges.
</TEXT>
