<SECOND>PM-BRF--Condor Egg,0139</SECOND>
<HEAD>Latest Condor Egg Is Fertile</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The latest California condor egg laid at the
San Diego Wild Animal Park is fertile, bringing to four the number
of live eggs produced this year in a captive breeding program
designed to save the dying species.
   Condor keepers declared the egg fertile Wednesday after holding
it up to a high-intensity lamp and detecting a developing embryo,
park spokesman Tom Hanscom said.
   The egg, laid Sunday, was the second produced this breeding
season by the condor couple who last year produced Molloko, the
first California condor to be both conceived and born in captivity.
   Hanscom said the first egg should hatch late next week. Both
eggs are being artificially incubated.
   Only 28 California condors are known to exist, and all are in
captivity.
</TEXT>
