<HEAD>Man Charged in Savage Murders Silent at Court Appearance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Note contents.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man accused in the savage murder of a
pregnant woman, her husband and their two children was placed on a
suicide watch in an isolation cell following his initial court
appearance.
   Newton Carlton Slawson, 34, remained under 24-hour watch today
in the Hillsborough County Jail after telling a staff pychologist
that he would kill himself at the first opportunity, said jail
commander Maj. Jim Cook.
   At an initial hearing Thursday, Slawson was silent as
Hillsborough County Judge Vincent Giglio read the charges against
him. Slawson is charged with four counts of murder and one count of
manslaughter.
   No arraignment date was set.
   Police said Slawson calmly confessed to the savage slayings of a
onetime coworker, Gerald Wood, 23; his wife Peggy, 21, the fetus
sliced from her womb; and their toddlers, Jennifer, 4, and Glendon,
3.
   Slawson told police he flew into a rage he couldn't control in
the Woods' Tampa apartment Tuesday night, authorities said.
   ``We just don't know why,'' said Deputy Police Chief Tom
DePolis. ``I guess the guy was a walking time bomb.''
   Police said they picked him up about 10 blocks from the Woods'
house and recovered a .357-caliber Magnum pistol and a 6-inch
folding knife from his car.
   Slawson moved to central Florida in November from Concord, N.C.,
according to his uncle William Newton.
   Single and a loner, the construction laborer and warehouseman
took a job at a compost company in eastern Hillsborough County in
February. It was there that he met Wood, a forklift driver.
