<FIRST>r i PM-Italy-Scandal     04-14 0297</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Italy-Scandal,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecutor Appeals Decision Clearing De Benedetti</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MILAN, Italy (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A prosecutor has appealed a court decision
clearing financier Carlo De Benedetti of wrongdoing in connection
with Italy's biggest banking scandal in decades, news reports said
today.
   Banco Ambrosiano, Italy's largest private bank, collapsed in
1982 after it was unable to collect $1.3 billion in loans made to
10 dummy companies in Latin America. The loans were issued after
letters of assurance were received from the Vatican bank.
   De Benedetti was notified in 1987 he was under investigation for
possible extortion in connection with his sale of Banco Ambrosiano
shares shortly before it went bankrupt. Last week, two Milan
magistrates indicted 35 people in connection with their
investigation of the scandal. They cleared De Benedetti of any
wrongdoing in connection with the bank failure.
   De Benedetti's economic empire includes the Olivetti computer
group and Mondadori, one of Italy's giant publishing houses.
   Italian news agencies and state television said prosecutor Pier
Luigi Dell'Osso disagreed with the magistrates' conclusion about De
Benedetti and had asked the Court of Appeals to indict the
financier for alleged extortion of Roberto Calvi, the Banco
Ambrosiano chairman whose body was found hanging from a London
bridge in 1982. A court ruled in January that Calvi was murdered.
   De Benedetti was vice chairman of the bank for 65 days when
Calvi was chairman.
   Last week, De Benedetti said he was satisfied because he had
always ``acted in the full respect of the law.''
   Those indicted last week included Licio Gelli, a financier who
was charged with complicity in fraudulent bankruptcy. Gelli has
been accused in other investigations of masterminding a ring of
right-wing terrorists.
   He was grandmaster of a secret lodge that investigators linked
to a plot to topple the government.
</TEXT>
