<HEAD>1,400 People Evacuated After Mystery Odor Fells 19 At Student Musical</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 1,400 people were evacuated
from an auditorium after spectators and performers at a student
musical became ill from an unidentified odor, authorities said
today.
   Officials said 19 young people were taken to four hospitals
following the incident late Thursday at Santa Monica Civic
Auditorium. No one was injured seriously.
   The stricken children _ most in their early teens or younger _
complained of dizziness, nausea, chest pains and difficulty
breathing, authorities said.
   Firefighters who searched the arena in this seaside community 20
miles southwest of downtown Los Angeles could not find any source
for the mysterious odor, said Fire Department dispatcher Mike
Shields.
   Police Lt. Roy McGinnis said school officials were to conduct a
more detailed inspection today.
   People began to feel ill about 9 p.m. as a musical titled
``Stairway of the Stars'' was under way in the sprawling arena,
authorities said.
   ``A few girls fainted during a performance. They allege it was
paint fumes, but there was no painting going on inside the
building,'' said auditorium employee Bobbie Burnett. ``Then others
got sick. It was like a chain reaction.''
   Students from several local schools were taking part in the
event.
