<SECOND>PM-South Korea, 1st-Ld Writethru, a0530,0598</SECOND>
<HEAD>Anti-Communists March; Communists Demand Dissident's Release</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 8th pvs, `Student leaders...' to UPDATE
with demand for dissident's release, sports meeting on. Pickup 9th, ``Moon
created...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of right-wing war veterans,
some scrawling anti-communist slogans with their own blood,
demonstrated today against a dissident cleric who visited North
Korea for reunification talks.
   About 2,000 radical students supporting the Rev. Moon Ik-hwan
battled riot police with firebombs and rocks at five college
campuses in the capital today for a second day. Police said there
were some injuries and arrests but had no figures.
   About 10,000 veterans and supporters staged a mostly peaceful
march to the presidential mansion to call for the punishment of
Moon, who was arrested Thursday after returning from communist
North Korea. The protesters demanded dissident groups be disbanded
and their members jailed.
   Protesters chanted ``Destroy communists!'' and ``Execute the
Moon Ik-hwan clique!'' before riot police turned them away several
blocks from the mansion. Some marchers, including a few in
wheelchairs, attempted to force their way past police but were
stopped.
   At a rally before the march, cheering veterans burned large
effigies of Moon embracing North Korean leader Kim Il Sung. Some
enraged veterans cut their fingers and drew anti-communist slogans
with their blood as the crowd cheered.
   Many of the protesters were elderly veterans of the Korean War
that ended in 1953, but younger veterans from the Vietnam War also
took part. South Korea sent troops to Vietnam to support the United
States and South Vietnam.
   Police earlier arrested about 60 members of right-wing youth
groups who briefly occupied the Seoul offices of the country's main
dissident movement, the United National Democratic Movement, to
protest Moon's visit to the north.
   Student leaders demanded the release of Moon and other jailed
dissident leaders and called for the overthrow of President Roh
Tae-woo. The student protests today were smaller than violent
clashes Thursday involving at least 10,000 students in five cities.
   North Korea today condemned Moon's arrest and said it
constituted ``a vicious challenge to human rights, democracy and
the peaceful reunification of the nation.'' The government's
statement was carried by the Korean Central News Agency and
monitored in Tokyo.
   Despite the controversy over Moon, South Korean officials said
today they will attend an inter-Korea sports meeting Tuesday in the
border town of Panmunjom. National Unification Minister Lee
Hong-koo said the meeting, the third since March 9, is aimed at
forming a single delegation to the 1990 Asian Games in Beijing,
China.
   Moon created a major political controversy in the South by
making a secret visit to North Korea last month to meet with
communist leader Kim to discuss ways to reunite the Korean
peninsula.
   Moon and a companion were arrested Thursday after landing in
Seoul. The 71-year-old dissident was charged with being a North
Korean agent _ a charge that could carry the death penalty if he is
found guilty.
   Police today arrested Im Jae-kyung, vice president of the
opposition Hankyoreh newspaper, for trying to arrange a trip to
North Korea to interview Kim, officials said. Police earlier
arrested one of the paper's editorial writers who wanted to visit
the north to meet Kim, police said.
   The two Koreas have been bitter rivals since the division of the
peninsula at the end of the Second World War. North Korea invaded
the south in 1950 at the start of the bloody Korean War, which
ended in 1953.
</TEXT>
