<FIRST>r a PM-MilitaryContractor     04-14 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Military Contractor,0336</SECOND>
<HEAD>Official For Defunct Minnesota Military Contractor Accused Of Fraud</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An official of a defunct military
contractor has been accused of defrauding the Army by providing
inferior parts for M-16 rifles and other weapons.
   Douglas W. Mordal, formerly a supervisor at J.C. Manufacturing
Inc. in surburban Spring Lake Park, is charged in a federal
complaint filed Thursday in U.S. District Court in St. Paul.
   Mordal is accused of using inferior and softer metals and
testing procedures to fill seven orders of parts for M-16s, M-60
machine guns and M-203 grenade launchers.
   Some gun experts say that rifle and gun bolts manufactured with
softer steel are subject to backfiring or jamming. They're also
subject to faster wear.
   The contracts, filled between January 1983 and March 1987, were
worth a total of more than $2.2 million.
   The complaint says Mordal is scheduled to plead guilty Wednesday
before federal Judge Robert Renner.
   Mordal's attorney, Joseph Friedberg, declined to comment. Mordal
did not immediately return a telephone message left today at his
home in surburban Elk River.
   Joseph Walbran, an assistant U.S. attorney handling the case,
said the charges against Mordal are ``an event in a continuing
investigation.'' He declined to say whether other company officials
will be charged.
   The company is alleged to have sold the weapons parts
fraudulently by using a softer alloy steel than call for in their
contracts with the U.S. Armament Munitions and Chemical Command.
   Experts on guns asked to explain the possible effect of using
softer metals said it could cause problems, the Star Tribune
reported today.
   Wade Hanson, a salesman for Burger Brothers Sporting Goods in
Bloomington, said weapons made parts of with softer metals may be
subject to a dangerous ``blowback'' effect that could send the
shell backward.
   J.C. Manufacturing, formed in 1973, filed for protection from
creditors under Chapter 11 in October 1986. It filed for Chapter 7
bankruptcy in January.
</TEXT>
