<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1032EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Hungary     04-14 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Hungary,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Body Calls For Review Of 1950s Show Trials In Hungary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government advisory body has called
for a review of the show trial of former Premier Imre Nagy, who was
executed in 1958, the state news agency MTI reported.
   Meanwhile, the government daily Magyar Hirlap reported today
that Premier Miklos Nemeth plans to reshuffle the government next
month.
   Nagy, a critic of the Soviet Union, was ousted and arrested in
1956 after Soviet soldiers and tanks crushed a revolt that demanded
Red Army forces leave Hungary. He was executed on charges of
``conspiracy and creating a secret organization aimed at forcibly
seizing power and overthrowing the Hungarian People's Democracy.''
   The decision to reassess Nagy's and other Stalinist show trials
of the 1950s is widely seen as the first step toward Nagy's
rehabilitation, which is being demanded by several independent
political groups in Hungary.
   Political rehabilitation would involve Communist Party officials
saying it was a mistake to try him and that he was an honest man.
   But Communist Party chief Karoly Grosz recently ruled out Nagy's
political rehabilitation, saying that during the 1956 revolution he
made ``too many mistakes.''
   A purely legal rehabilitation would be a different matter, Grosz
added. Under that form of rehabilitation, judicial authorities
would say that a person convicted on a given charge should not have
been convicted.
   The bodies of Nagy and four of his associates have been exhumed
from their unmarked graves in recent weeks. The government has
given permission for a funeral to bury Nagy's remains June 16, the
31st anniversary of his execution.
   Acting on information from Justice Minister Kalman Kulcsar, the
advisory body said judicial authorities should look into the Nagy
trial in line with an earlier government resolution to review the
show trials.
   ``They want the review to be thorough, but done as fast as
possible so that a satisfactory general solution can be found after
the examination of other trials conducted in the same period,'' MTI
reported Thursday.
   It said the body would welcome a decision to review the penal
code regarding anti-state offenses and would propose abolition of
capital punishment in such cases.
   The abolition of capital punishment for anti-state crimes would
pave the way for the summary rehabilitation of the revolutionary
leaders.
   Nemeth's plans to reshuffle the government follow Wednesday's
top-level changes in the Communist Party's ruling Politburo.
   ``A necessary harmony in outlook and unity of action was
missing'' in government in recent months, Nemeth was quoted as
saying in Magyar Hirlap. ``This situation cannot continue any
longer.''
   Nemeth did not mention any names with the exception of Minister
of Health and Social Care Judit Csehak, who had asked not to be
renominated for Politburo membership Wednesday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
