<FIRST>r a PM-BombThreat-Bush     04-14 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bomb Threat-Bush,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man in Courtroom Says He Has Bomb and Demands To See Bush</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ELIZABETH, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two sheriff's officers were praised for
tackling a man in a courtroom and seizing what was believed to be
an explosive device after the man said he had a bomb and demanded
to speak to President Bush.
   The incident occurred Thursday when James Cecil, 36, of
Lakewood, faced a judge on firearms charges.
   When Cecil suddenly announced he had a bomb and wanted to speak
to Bush, who was visiting a school about 7 miles away, Union County
sheriff's officer Charles Marchese tackled him and officer Ronnie
Malcolm seized his briefcase, said Union County Sheriff Ralph G.
Froelich.
   Froelich said Malcolm didn't believe the man had a bomb until he
opened the briefcase and saw what appeared to be an electronic
explosive device.
   ``Instead of panicking and dropping it, he slowly moved over and
walked into an adjoining room with solid concrete walls, risking
his own life,'' Froelich said. ``I'm very proud of the way they
conducted themselves.''
   The device in the briefcase was ``a suspicious device; they're
not classifying it as a bomb,'' said county police Sgt. Anthony
Reilly.
   Cecil also claimed he had planted other bombs in the building,
which houses the county administration and Superior Court, said Ed
Tucker, first assistant prosecutor for Elizabeth.
   Bomb-sniffing dogs and 40 police officers searched for other
explosives in the building for five hours, but none was found, said
county police officer Ellen Merino. There were no injuries, she
said.
   Cecil was being held today in the Union County Jail facing
charges of assault and terroristic threats. Froelich said
additional charges were expected.
   The incident took place in the third-floor courtroom of Superior
Judge Leonard Sachar at about 1:30 p.m. Bush gave a speech Thursday
at Union High School and left Newark International Airport at 2:32
p.m.
   Cecil ``freaked out and said `I have a bomb here,' or something
to that effect, and everybody started scrambling,'' Tucker said.
</TEXT>
