<FIRST>r w PM-NASAResignation 1stLd-Writethru a0570 04-14 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-NASA Resignation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0570,230</SECOND>
<HEAD>Acting NASA Administrator To Resign May 13</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new 4th graf, Bush announced, with Myers successor</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dale D. Myers, the acting administrator of
NASA and one of the men brought back to the agency following the
Challenger accident, is resigning on May 13, officials announced
today.
   Myers, 67, became acting administrator of the National
Aeronautics and Space Administration last week following the
resignation of administrator James C. Fletcher.
   Richard Truly, chief of NASA space flight program, is nominated
by President Bush to become administrator, but has not yet been
confirmed by the Senate.
   Bush announced Wednesday that he plans to nominate J.R.
Thompson, head of the Marshall Space Flight Center in Huntsville,
Ala., to succeed Myers as deputy administrator.
   Myers has served two tours in NASA's headquarters office. He was
associate administrator for manned space flight from 1970 to 1974,
an era that included much of the Apollo moon landing program.
   From 1977 to 1979, Myers served as under secretary of the
Department of Energy.
   President Reagan persuaded both Myers and Fletcher to return to
NASA in the wake of the Jan. 28, 1986 Challenger accident. They
reorganized the NASA management structure and directed the program
that corrected problems on the space shuttle and enabled the
spacecraft to resume flights.
   Myers was awarded distinguished service medals by both NASA and
the Department of Energy, and he is a member of the National
Academy of Engineering.
</TEXT>
