<DOCNO> AP890414-0104 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1127EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-Revised-EmployeeBenefits     04-14 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Revised-Employee Benefits,340</SECOND>
<HEAD>Simplified Health Rules Proposed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most members of the House Ways and Means
Committee are sponsoring a bill by Chairman Dan Rostenkowski,
D-Ill., to simplify rules that prohibit employer-financed health
insurance plans from discriminating against lower-paid workers.
   The rules, aimed at encouraging extension of medical insurance
to a greater number of employees, were enacted as part of the 1986
tax overhaul. They have been assailed widely on grounds they impose
a heavy burden of paperwork on employers; some businesses say the
rules are so onerous that they have threatened to drop all employee
health insurance.
   ``It is my hope that recordkeeping and data collection
requirements of employers, particularly small employers, will be
significantly reduced,'' Rostenkowski said in introducing his
modification bill Thursday.
   Although he remains firmly committed to seeing that higher-paid
employees do not get a disproportionate share of benefits,
Rostenkowski said, those requirements ``should not be so
administratively burdensome on small or late employers that they
discourage the establishment and maintenance of fringe-benefit
programs for broad classes of employees.''
   The disputed rules generally require employers to conduct
detailed, complicated tests to determine whether their
fringe-benefit plans, principally health insurance, discriminate
against those making less than $50,000 a year.
   The rules went into effect on Jan. 1 but the Internal Revenue
Service waived them until July 1 and agreed that no employer would
be penalized if a good-faith effort to follow the rules were made
the remainder of 1989.
   Rostenkowski's bill stops short of repealing the rules, which
are known by their location in the tax code, Section 89. Many
members of Congress have endorsed repeal.
   Under Rostenkowski's bill, employers that provide a health plan
would have to offer coverage costing workers $10 a week or less
($25 or less for a family plan) to 90 percent of employees.
Higher-paid workers would be taxed on the value of coverage that
was better than provided other employees.
   The bill is being sponsored by 28 members of Ways and Means,
including all Democrats on the panel.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
