<FIRST>r a PM-ArtAcademy 1stLd-Writethru a0462 04-14 0494</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Art Academy, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0462,0504</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Academy Stages First Exhibition Of Its Permanent Collection</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf with exhibition opening.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 200 paintings and sculptures, many
never before exhibited and only recently rescued from decades of
neglect, have gone on display in a show that encompasses 164 years
of American art.
   The show, which opened today in Manhattan before beginning a
seven-city national tour, is composed almost entirely of works
donated by the artists to the National Academy of Design as a
requirement for membership.
   ``It's interesting, because our artists choose differently than
curators would choose,'' said John Dobkin, director of the Academy.
``These are works I would hope that the artists feel very strongly
about.''
   The Academy was formed in 1825 by a group of artists as a
school, rather than a museum, ``to elevate the character and
condition of the arts of design in our country.''
   From the beginning, artists were required to submit a
self-portrait or other likeness upon their election as an associate
member, and an example of their work upon induction as an
academician.
   ``The artists have been remarkably generous,'' Dobkin said in an
interview Thursday before a preview showing in a Fifth Avenue
mansion donated to the academy in 1940.
   But as the collection grew over the years, the academy was
unable to keep up with it.
   Dobkin said that when he became director in 1978, ``the storage
facility was so inadequate and the conditions for the paintings
were so lamentable that scholars hadn't been able to look at the
collection for years.''
   Funds were solicited from such sources as the National Endowment
for the Arts and the New York State Council for the Arts.
   ``And now we have felt ready after being in business since 1825
to have this large exhibition,'' Dobkin said.
   About half of the more than 150 paintings and 50 sculptures
chosen from the 2,000-item collection have never before been on
public exhibition.
   Included in the show are works by such artists as Thomas Eakins,
Winslow Homer, William Merritt Chase, Philip Pearlstein and
Alexander Stirling Calder, whose son, also named Alexander, is a
famous abstract sculptor of mobiles and stabiles.
   Dobkin estimated the total collection to be worth hundreds of
millions of dollars.
   No attempts were made to organize the show chronologically or by
style, which can make for somewhat jarring juxtapositions. Muted
pastoral scenes are hung next to bold abstracts; a study of a row
of 1950s-style cars is across the room from tiny portraits and
still-lifes.
   ``They aren't all masterpieces by any means,'' Dobkin admits.
But he adds, the artists ``gave these pieces and these are the
pieces they wanted their fellow artists to judge them by.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
      The show will go on the road later this year through 1992 with
stops in Nashville, Tenn.; Raleigh, N.C.; Atlanta; Santa Clara,
Calif.; Chicago; St. Louis and Denver.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
