<DOCNO> AP890414-0108 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1157EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NavyCrash     04-14 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Navy Crash,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Navy Planes Collide, Investigation Under Way</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MACON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Navy officials have confirmed that two Navy
training jets collided before they crashed, killing two people, but
said the cause of the collision was still being investigated.
   The crash of two T-2C Buckeye jets occurred Thursday about 50
miles north of the Meridian Naval Air Station in rural east-central
Mississippi. Two pilots who ejected suffered only minor injuries.
   The jets are used to train Navy and Marine pilots. One student
and one instructor were aboard each jet.
   The dead were identified as Lt. j.g. Jerome Reese Schuchart, 28,
of Seattle, and Ensign Duane James Hofhine, 23, of Cedarburg, Wis.
Schuchart was Hofhine's flight instructor, said Navy Petty Officer
Dave McBride of the Meridian Naval Air Station.
   The survivors were identified as Lt. Terry Lynn Tuggle of
Aurora, Colo., an instructor, and Ensign Bruce Hart Szymanski of
Fredonia, N.Y., a student.
   Tuggle and Szymanski ejected from their plane as the two
aircraft collided over rural Noxubee County. The two were
hospitalized but later released, McBride said.
   Johnny Spann, who owns a garage off old U.S. Highway 45, heard
one plane crash. ``We seen parachutes and pieces falling,'' he said.
   An ejection seat landed near his garage, and a piece of a jet
hit a house nearby, Spann said. About 30 minutes later two pilots
walked out of the woods.
   ``They had their parachutes all rolled up and everything,'' he
said. ``They looked like they was fine. We offered them a ride.
They said they'd just walk on down.''
   The pilots were picked up by a helicopter after reaching a
crossroad, he said.
