<FIRST>r a PM-Spill-Lower48Reax 1stLd-Writethru a0451 04-14 0856</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Lower 48 Reax, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0451,0877</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alaska Oil Spill Spawns Boycotts, Protests, Jokes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf to recast; INSERTS 2 grafs after 8th to include
Seattle hearing Thursday; SUBS grafs 12-13 pvs bgng `In Los Angeles...'
to put in past tense.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS J. ROWE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The nation's worst oil spill is provoking boycotts of some Exxon
stations, galvanizing protests from enraged citizens and talk
jockeys, and leading to reports of bomb threats.
   It's also inspiring some slick jokes.
   But the shipload's worth of Exxon-bashing during the past three
weeks isn't funny to some gas station operators, who quickly point
out that the public shouldn't equate them with the giant oil
corporation.
   And many station operators maintain they've witnessed few, if
any, effects of organized efforts against Exxon Corp.
   A Phoenix-based group calling itself Friends of Prince William
Sound _ where the tanker Exxon Valdez ran aground on a charted reef
and spilled some 10.1 million gallons of oil _ turned out about 50
marchers on Tuesday outside a Phoenix Exxon station, carrying signs
with slogans such as:
   ``Exxon: sign of the double cross.''
   An estimated 2,000 people held a two-hour rally Wednesday at
Seattle's Alki Beach to protest the oil spill, forcing Seattle
police to close Alki Avenue, the thoroughfare that provides the
only access to the beach.
   Radio station KUBE-FM created and promoted the event. Announcers
Charlie Brown and Ty Flint spent 12 hours broadcasting calls from
the public about the oil spill. Four other radio stations joined in
a simulcast.
   On Thursday, more than 500 people jammed a National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration hearing in Seattle that became a forum
to vent anger over the spill. The public meeting was the last of
four called by the agency to identify issues pertinent to the
establishment of a national marine sanctuary along the Northwest
coast.
   ``I'm heartbroken over what happened in Alaska,'' said John
Church, who pasted up bright red ``Remember Valdez'' signs
throughout the building. ``I used to fish in Cordova, and to see
pictures of those sea otters floating dead in the water is
heartbreaking. I don't want this to happen in Washington.''
   Meantime, Michael Siegal of KING in Seattle is trying to
generate national interest in a boycott against Exxon. He has
appeared on other radio stations around the nation and said he is
receiving 200 letters a day, many with cut-up Exxon credit cards.
   At radio station KARN in Little Rock, Ark., talk show host Pat
Lynch said Thursday that he has had guests on twice this week to
discuss the Alaska spill, and he found listeners were livid.
   ``Listeners are just plain upset and there is, I think, an
unusual sense of rage,'' he said. ``I think it hinges on two
things, one of which is the out and out undisguised greed of price
increases coming at this time, and also the certain knowledge that
the consumer will bear the cost of the Valdez cleanup.''
   In Los Angeles, morning show host Peter Tilden of KLSX-FM, a
rock 'n' roll station, solicited volunteers to help in the cleanup.
   He also asked listeners to slice Exxon credits cards and boycott
the oil company.
   To others in radio and television, the issue has been a laughing
matter.
   ``Exxon sprung into action immediately, and sent in their crack
cleanup crew _ a guy named Raoul with a squeegee and a dirty rag,''
Johnny Carson joked recently on NBC-TV's ``The Tonight Show.''
   He also quipped: ``I don't think Exxon's new slogan helps at
all: `Exxon, we're not as bad as Union Carbide.'''
   But all joking aside, Wayne Konitshek, managing director of the
Colorado Service Station Dealers Association, said three bomb
threats and two protests have been reported at Exxon service
stations since last weekend.
   He said the association is attempting to make the public aware
of the difference between independently owned stations and company
owned stations.
   Independent dealers, he said, ``are as innocent as the otters in
Alaska.''
   Nonetheless, many station operators from Maine to California
said it was business as usual in the wake of the spill. Others
attributed any decline in sales to a recent increase in prices at
the pump.
   Richard Brown, manager of an Exxon station in suburban New
Orleans, said some customers have threatened to stop buying gas in
protest of the oil spill and the rising price of fuel.
   ``But there's really been no decrease in business,'' he added.
   Tom Hamilton, a mechanic at Dave's Bustleton Exxon in
Philadelphia, said some customers have asked about a recent 6 cents
per gallon increase in the price, but none has commented seriously
about the spill.
   ``They say some things about it in jest,'' he said.
   For its part, Exxon responded to two consumer groups' boycott
call earlier this week with a statement issued from its New York
headquarters, reiterating its regret about the oil spill.
   ``All of our customers are very valuable to us and we hope that
our effort in Alaska will convince them that we continue to be a
responsible company and one people like to do business with,''
Exxon said.
</TEXT>
