<FIRST>r i PM-Czechoslovakia-Devaty     04-14 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Czechoslovakia-Devaty,0243</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Charter 77 Spokesman Released</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former spokesman for the Charter
77 human rights group was released from jail today, the state-run
news agency reported.
   CTK quoted the prosecutor's office in Brno, Moravia, as saying
Stanislav Devaty was released because ``the reasons for his
detention have ceased to exist. The investigation on his activity
continues.'' It did not elaborate.
   Devaty reportedly started a hunger strike when he was arrested
March 16 in connection with a petition he organized last fall
calling for freedom for political prisoners. He was not convicted
on any charges, but activists in Prague said authorities planned to
charged him with incitement in connection with the petition.
   The International Helsinki Federation, a Vienna-based group
monitoring human rights in the East bloc, on Tuesday appealed to
the Czechoslovak government to release the activist.
   Devaty, 37, was arrested in Prague and taken to his hometown of
Gottwaldov in Moravia. Fellow Charter 77 signatories said he had
been fasting since his arrest and had been force-fed since Easter.
   An April 8 appeal to the Prague government, signed by 29
Czechoslovak activists, said Devaty ``is capable of total
self-sacrifice.''
   There was no immediate word on Devaty's whereabouts.
   Charter 77 _ the Soviet bloc's oldest, unofficial human rights
organization _ was formed in January 1977. It was named for the
document issued by founding members calling on Czechoslovakia to
respect civil liberties.
</TEXT>
