<FIRST>r w AM-US-KoreaAmbassador     04-14 0416</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Korea Ambassador,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senators Raise Doubts About Nominee for Amabassador to South Korea</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several members of the Senate Foreign
Relations Committee have privately raised doubts with the Bush
administration about the nomination of Donald Gregg to be
ambassador to South Korea because of his possible role in the
Iran-Contra affair, congressional sources Friday.
   However, Secretary of State James Baker III has reiterated his
support for Gregg's nomination to the high-profile diplomatic by
President Bush, Gregg's former boss.
   Gregg's nomination, which will be debated by the Senate
committee next month, is one of several that have run into
opposition in the light of disclosures about the Iran-Contra affair
that have surfaced in the trial of former White House aide Oliver
North.
   On Thursday, Michael Armacost, Bush's nominee for ambasasdor to
Japan, ran into questioning about documents indicating he attended
a 1985 meeting at which it was decided to release military aid to
Honduras in return for that nation's continued backing of the
Nicaraguan Contras.
   Armacost denied attending that meeting but promised to search
his records and report back to the panel. The congressional sources
said Friday that Armacost, who served in the No. 3 post at the
State Department in the Reagan administration, will tell the
committee he was invited to attend the White House meeting but did
not go.
   Also on Thursday, Sen. Alan Cranston, D-Calif., called Baker to
ask that Gregg's nomination for South Korea be withdrawn, said
congressional sources commenting only on condition they not be
named. Margaret Tutwiler, Baker's spokeswoman, confirmed that
Cranston called the secretary but declined to say why.
   Baker then talked to Gregg ``and the status of the nomination
remains the same. The president supports his nominee,'' she said
Friday.
   When Bush was vice president, Gregg was his national security
adviser. His name is mentioned in several documents that became
public during the 1987 congressional investigation of the
Iran-Contra affair.
   The final report from that investigation says that Gregg, a
former CIA official, knew that North was directing the Contra
supply effort _ at a time when official U.S. aid was banned _ but
that he contended he did not tell Bush.
   Another nomination facing some opposition is that of John
Negroponte as ambassador to Mexico. Negroponte was ambassador to
Honduras from 1981 to 1985 and some Democrats want to know whether
he was involved in the inducements promised the Honduran government
in exchange for its support of the Contras.
</TEXT>
