<HEAD>Flights Canceled, Delayed Due to Strikes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Scores of flights were canceled in Rome and Naples
on Friday when Italian pilots went on strike for two hours and
flight attendants staged a daylong walkout.
   The strike by four flight attendants' unions, which began at
midnight Thursday, grounded nearly all planes of the state carrier
Alitalia and its domestic branch, ATI. Foreign airlines were not
affected.
   The flight attendants are protesting a deadlock in negotiations
to renew their contracts, which expired 17 months ago. They are
asking for a reduction in work hours, more time off and a salary
increase.
   Alitalia pilots have called daily two-hour strikes until April
21 to protest delays in their own contract talks.
