<FIRST>u a PM-ChristianScienceTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0beforeanexpectedtrial
04-14 0579</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Christian Science Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0558,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecution Rests In Trial of Christian Science Couple</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with judge reversing himself and
disallowing testimony; prosecution resting. Picks up 5th graf pvs, `I said...'.
DELETES 11th graf, `Sarasota Circuit...', now outdated.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The prosecution rested today without
calling a key witness in the trial of a Christian Science couple
accused of murder and abuse in the death of their daughter from
untreated diabetes.
   William and Christine Hermanson are charged with third-degree
murder and felony child abuse in the Sept. 30, 1986, death of
7-year-old Amy after seeking the aid of spiritual healers but not
doctors.
   Defense attorneys were successful today in blocking the
testimony of a witness who had said with the jury out of the
courtroom that the Hermansons had gotten medical help when they
needed it but didn't seek insulin injections that could have saved
their daughter's life.
   Attorney Charles Arnold said the surprise testimony late
Thursday violated state rules of discovery requiring lawyers to
notify the other side of damaging testimony expected to be
introduced.
   After the prosecution acknowledged the defense hadn't been told
about the witness, Sarasota Circuit Judge Stephen Dakan reversed
himself and ruled today that the testimony was inadmissible.
   The witness, Mary Christman, said Thursday that she visited the
Hermansons three days after Amy's death and learned William
Hermanson previously had taken Novocain for a tooth problem.
   His wife suggested she had anesthesia during childbirth, Mrs.
Christman testified without the jury present.
   ``I said, `God, Chris, if Bill had Novocain and you had two
Caesarean sections, which I've had myself, how could you have done
that without any anesthetic?''' Mrs. Christman testified.
   Mrs. Hermanson replied, ``Well, that was a different
situation,'' she said.
   The couple is accused of third-degree murder and child abuse in
Amy's death in 1986. Prosecutors say the parents turned to
spiritual healing and prayer instead of medical attention that
could have saved Amy's life.
   The defense says the issue is religious freedom and cites a
state law exempting parents who have religious beliefs against
medical treatment from neglect charges. The Hermansons say they
were following Christian Science doctrine when they relied on
practitioners of spiritual healing for the child's recovery.
   ``I was frustrated and baffled when a simple shot of insulin
would have saved her life ... She looked like a refugee from a
death camp,'' Mrs. Christman said. ``(Mrs. Hermanson) said Amy felt
no pain, there was no illness. It was `negative transfers' that she
was picking up from other people.''
   Mrs. Hermanson contended Amy's body would have rejected insulin
because her husband's body rejected Novocain, Mrs. Christman
testified.
   Three times Thursday, Mrs. Hermanson broke down and cried
quietly at the defense table during the testimony of her daughter's
teacher, Laura Kingsley. The teacher said Amy was once bright and
creative but turned lethargic.
   Another witness, Helen Falb, an employee at the Hermansons'
academy, said that Amy looked ``skeletal'' a few weeks before her
death and said she had been vomiting and unable to sleep. Ms. Falb
said she did not tell the parents about the conversation.
   ``I knew about their religion and I know they wrote my paycheck
and I didn't want to create a stir,'' she testified.
   A 1975 Florida law states that parents who withhold medical
treatment for religious reasons cannot be considered ``abusive or
neglectful'' to their children.
   Five similar cases are pending nationwide.
</TEXT>
