<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1301EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Fashion     04-14 0645</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Fashion,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>YSL Chairman Says Company Reorganizing, Dismisses Health Rumors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUZY PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Fashion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The house of Yves Saint Laurent is undergoing a
major managerial restructuring, but company officials say the
``king of couture'' will remain in control of creation, if not in
top form.
   Company chairman Pierre Berge said the reorganization will give
him absolute management authority, while Saint Laurent himself
stays on as the couturier.
   In an interview Friday, Berge brusquely dismissed rumors about
the health of the 52-year-old Saint Laurent.
   ``I give you my word of honor that he has neither cancer nor
AIDS, for which he is not even seropositive,'' Berge said. ``He is
working at home in Paris right now.''
   Berge said the company is being restructured to avoid any
possibility of an unfriendly takeover well into the next century.
   Overall, with couture, ready-to-wear, perfume and accessories
sales, the YSL empire is estimated to be worth nearly $2 billion.
   ``We have an eye on the future, hoping to go public on the
French stock market by 1990,'' Berge added.
   For several seasons, the reclusive Saint Laurent has been
refusing interviews and looking less-than-healthy as he walks, or
sometimes staggers, on runways after shows.
   Saint Laurent's swollen appearance, facial tics and difficulty
walking have given rise to speculation about his health.
   ``There's nothing new about Saint Laurent's illness,'' Berge
said. ``It's been talked about for 15 years. Everyone knows he has
had psychological problems, that he takes too many tranquilizers,
and that he sometimes looks somewhat confused.
   ``The company has a big insurance policy for him, and four times
a year he must have a complete physical checkup. Basically, he is
OK.''
   Berge, confirming a report in the Wall Street Journal, said that
when the Saint Laurent company goes public on the French stock
market, it will in effect create a new company.
   Management will be headed by four men: Saint Laurent; Berge;
Alain Minc, head of Italian financier Carlo de Benedetti's French
holding company; and Jean-Francis Bretelle, managing director of
Yves Saint Laurent SA.
   ``I have a special role,'' said Berge, 58. ``In France we will
have a legal status that does not exist in America, I believe. It
will be a `Societe en commandite par actions.' That basically means
that no matter what stockholders vote, I alone will have the last
word.''
   When asked if that means he will he become the absolute dictator
of the YSL operation in France, Berge replied: ``That's right. At
last, at last.''
   At the moment, Saint Laurent and Berge are majority
shareholders, which they became when they bought back the Saint
Laurent perfume business two years ago from the Squibb Corp.,
backed by De Benedetti and his associates.
   Berge and Saint Laurent have been associated since they started
their fledgling fashion house in 1961.
   They first met and became friends after Saint Laurent's
sensational 1958 ``trapeze'' line collection for Christian Dior, as
Saint Laurent, age 21, took over designing for the Dior empire
following the couturier's death in 1957.
   Saint Laurent came to Paris in 1954 from his birthplace in Oran,
Algeria, and was soon introduced by Michel de Brunhoff, the editor
of Vogue, to Christian Dior. He was so impressed by Saint Laurent's
sketches he hired him on the spot as an assistant.
   Since the beginning, Saint Laurent has had a powerful impact on
fashion. He was the first couturier to make elegant trousers for
women, starting with the tuxedo suits of 1966, still a Saint
Laurent trademark.
   Since then he has put women into sophisticated versions of
Russian fete clothes, Chinese, Arab or Indian-inspired styles,
ruffled babydoll dresses, outfits based on works by modern painters
like Mondrian and Picasso, and more.
   From his youthful days, he became a classic designer with an
unerring contemporary fashion sense, a feeling for what chic women
want to wear.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
