<FIRST>u a PM-OfficialsIndicted     04-14 0352</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Officials Indicted,0363</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Grand Jury Names Pa Officials And Illinois Company</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID MORRIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARRISBURG, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury today indicted the
head of Pennsylvania's student loan agency and his former top aide,
charging that they were involved in a scheme to extort money from a
contractor.
   The indictment names Kenneth Reeher, executive director of the
Pennsylvania Higher Education Assistance Agency, who is the state's
highest-paid employee; and Harry Casoni, a former deputy who
retired in 1986.
   Also charged was Gabler Educational Management Services Inc., of
Libertyville, Ill., according to an announcement by U.S. Attorney
James West. He said the company is expected to plead guilty to a
bribery charge later today.
   The investigation, which has spanned more than a year,
continues, he said.
   Reeher, the only state employee to make more than $100,000 a
year, counting bonuses, has denied any wrongdoing.
   John Ebersole, a spokesman for the student loan agency, said
Reeher ``told us he would have no comment today. He expects to meet
with the officers of the board early next week, and he may have
something to say at that time.''
   The agency operates a financial-assistance program for college
students and holds contracts with lenders and agencies in other
states to service student loans.
   Last week, officials said an internal review of the case found
no evidence of wrongdoing by any current loan agency employee or
official.
   Casoni retired in 1986, the same year the agency entered into a
$1.7 million no-bid contract with the Illinois company.
   According to the indictment, Reeher, 66, and Casoni, 55, told
Gabler Educational Management Services it would receive a lucrative
no-bid contract if the two men were given money and property.
   The indictment charges Reeher and Casoni with one count each of
extortion and bribery, three counts each of interstate travel in
aid of racketeering and one count each of conspiracy.
   The charges carry a maximum 80 years in jail and $3.47 million
in fines.
   The bribery count against the company carries a maximum $500,000
fine. West said the company also faces other financial sanctions.
</TEXT>
