<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1337EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Pope-US     04-14 0483</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Pope-US,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Council of Churches Ends Vatican Talks with Papal Audience</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEPHEN R. WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A National Council of Churches delegation
met with Pope John Paul II on Friday, capping five days of talks
aimed at strengthening relations between the Roman Catholic Church
and other Christian denominations in the United States.
   The 11-member delegation, representing various Anglican,
Protestant and Orthodox churches, included four ordained women.
   The Roman Catholic Church bars women priests, and the pope on
several occasions has warned that ordination of women in the
Anglican Communion, which includes the U.S. Episcopal Church, poses
serious obstacles to Christian unity.
   Delegation leaders said ordination of women was not raised in
the meetings, noting there are divisions among the non-Catholic
U.S. churches themselves on the issue. They said, however, that the
women delegates were treated with respect by the pope and other
Vatican officials.
   ``We have been treated very well,'' said the president of the
council, the Rev. Patricia A. McClurg, an ordained Presbyterian
minister. ``We found that we all share the same faith.''
   Noting that the pope cited the angel's message to the women at
Christ's tomb, McClurg said, ``I found that as a sign of respect
for women.''
   The pope recalled his meeting with Christian leaders in
Columbia, S.C., during his 1987 visit to the United States and said
all Christians ``must walk the path of reconciliation.''
   ``I am confident that, as we seek to remain ever faithful to the
Lord, the cause of ecumenism in the United States will steadily
progress,'' he added.
   Delegation leaders said the visit, the first by the council to
the Vatican since 1969, was intended primarily to strengthen
relations between the group and the U.S. Catholic bishops'
conference and to learn how the Vatican Curia, the church's central
administration, works.
   The Rev. Arie Brouwer, a minister of the Reformed Church in
America and the general secretary of the council, described the
visit as a ``spiritual retreat together.''
   ``In the United States we are supposedly the melting pot, and
sometimes it's good to come and see how the other pots melt,' said
Bishop Philip R. Cousin of the African Methodist Episcopal Church.
``Positive steps toward unity can only begin when people begin to
understand each other.''
   Three Catholics were in the delegation, including Archbishop
James Francis Stafford of Denver, chairman of the U.S. bishops'
committee for ecumenical and interreligious affairs.
   ``It has been an enriching exchange for members of the Curia to
see the richness of Christian life in the United States,'' he said.
   The delegation met with officials of the Vatican Secretariat of
State, Secretariat for Christian Unity, Congregation of the
Doctrine of the Faith and the Justice and Peace Commission.
   Topics included relations with churches in the Soviet Union, the
role of the church toward apartheid in South Africa and the
church's adapation of various cultures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890414-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1323EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a PM-EastStLouisWoes     04-14 0402</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-East St Louis Woes,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>East St. Louis Mayor Found In Contempt and Ordered To Jail</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A county judge today ordered East St.
Louis Mayor Carl Officer and the city attorney to jail after
finding them in contempt of court for failing to appear at an
earlier hearing.
   ``Your Honor, I was suffering from the effects of the flu,''
Officer said, attempting to explain to St. Clair County Judge
Sheila O'Brien why he did not appear before her March 31 to discuss
his city's leaking sewer system.
   The jailing order was the latest in a series of confrontations
and financial problems for the poverty-stricken city of 55,000
across the river from St. Louis.
   ``This is the most bizarre and outrageous situation I have ever
seen in a court of law,'' city attorney Eric Vickers said, shouting
as he challenged the judge's order. ``It is obvious this court has
no sense of fairness and decency.''
   ``Don't fight with me, Mr. Vickers,'' the judge responded.
``You're picking a fight you will not win.'' She set bond at $3,500
for each of the two men on the six-month jail sentence.
   Accusing East St. Louis officials of ``callous disregard'' for
the court's orders, Ms. O'Brien also reinstated an order of March 3
that the city post a $500,000 bond to guarantee that its sewers
will be fixed in 90 days.
   The order also requires the city to pay the costs of the lawyers
who took the sewage system complaints to court. Earlier, she had
dropped those requirements at Vickers' request.
   At the heart of the controversy is a two-acre pond at the Villa
Green housing project, which has filled with raw sewage, and was
ordered drained by the judge by early March.
   At the March 31 hearing, however, East St. Louis Public Works
Director Jesse Walker told Ms. O'Brien that his employees were
pumping sewage around the clock to keep it from backing into the
Villa Griffin pond, but a shortage of machines and manpower was
hindering progress.
   Sheila Shunick, a lawyer for tenants at the Villa Griffin
housing project, requested that the city show cause why it should
not be held in contempt. Ms. O'Brien granted her request.
   Ms. O'Brien has been holding hearings at two-week intervals on
the city's progress in stemming the flow of sewage from leaking or
blocked pipes.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
