<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Somalia     04-14 0273</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Somalia,0285</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.N. Preparing $40 Million in Aid to 70,000 Displaced Somalis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.N. agencies are preparing a $40 million
program to assist 70,000 Somalis displaced from their homes by war,
officials said Friday.
   U.N. agencies have been asked to submit a report on the program
to the office of Undersecretary-General Abdulrahim Farah by April
24, said agency officials, speaking on condition of anonymity.
   Somalia has a population of 5.3 million and is one of the
poorest nations in the world.
   The government of President Mohammed Siad Barre has been
battling a rebellion by the Somali National Movement for seven
years in the north of the country.
   In addition, a war broke out between Ethiopia and Somalia in
1977 for control of the Ogaden region.
   About 70,000 Somalis are displaced in their own nation.
   Because they have not crossed any borders, they have not been
assisted by the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees.
   That Geneva-based U.N. agency has spent $60 million to $70
million in each of the last 10 years to assist Ethiopians in
Somalia and Somalis who sought refuge in Ethiopia.
   Somalia says there are 840,000 refugees in Ethiopia. Some
refugee officials believe the true number is closer to 400,000.
   Somalia also receives much U.S. aid, expected to reach $55
million in fiscal year 1989, because the United States has signed
agreements under which the U.S. military may use Somali bases in
the event of conflict in the Middle East.
   The United States already has a large naval base at the Somali
port of Berbera on the Gulf of Aden.
</TEXT>
