<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1434EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ASNE-Cavazos     04-14 0369</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ASNE-Cavazos,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cavazos Says Newspapers Must Help Improve Schools</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Education Secretary Lauro Cavazos on Friday
urged newspaper editors to support public school improvement
efforts, saying such help is vital.
   ``I'm really here to enlist your help,'' Cavazos told the
American Society of Newspaper Editors. ``We must have your support
in these endeavors if they are to be successful.''
   Cavazos said high dropout rates, low test scores, drug abuse and
a high degree of adult illiteracy mean the nation is beyond the
``at risk'' description in a 1983 report and already in trouble.
   Newspapers should urge more parental involvement in school
management and educational decisions, more teacher responsibility
and more focus on early childhood education, he said. They should
also insist on curricular reform and should promote university
efforts to help primary and secondary schools, he added.
   Cavazos also urged the editors to support some of the education
priorities of the Bush administration, among them ``educational
deregulation'' that would allow the waiving of federal regulations
in some districts with innovative reform plans, and public school
choice programs that let parents decide which school their children
will attend.
   The secretary said open choice and competition have helped
higher education in the United States and could do the same at
lower levels.
   But he cautioned that any public school choice program must be
``very, very sensitive to equity in the system'' _ particularly
concerning minorities and the disadvantaged who may live near
sub-standard schools _ by improving ghetto schools and making
transportation available to students who opt to go elsewhere.
   Where schools are clearly unacceptable, Cavazos said during
questioning, ``the state ought to take them over, get them in
better shape or close them down. This country should not tolerate
third-rate schools.''
   In response to a question from ASNE President John Seigenthaler,
editor and publisher of the Nashville Tennessean, Cavazos stressed
that the school-choice plans favored by the administration involve
competition only among public schools.
   ``We are not prepared to move ahead ... in the federal
government'' into giving parents vouchers which they could use at
private schools, he said. ``At this time we have not moved into the
private school area.''
</TEXT>
