<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Tanks 1stLd-Writethru a0612 04-14 0870</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Tanks, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0612,0888</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tanks Rattle Residents in Restive Baltics</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 7-8 pvs, ``Several tanks ...'' with 5 grafs with
more on Tartu and Estonian action. Picks up 9th graf ``An editor ...''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANN IMSE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tanks and armored vehicles rumbled through three
restive cities in the Baltics this week, frightening residents
already shaken by a fatal clash between the military and
demonstrators in Soviet Georgia, activists and journalists said
Friday.
   Military officials said it was only a training exercise, and the
heavy armor did nothing more threatening than drive around. But the
timing frightened and infuriated residents of Riga, Tallinn and
Tartu, journalists said.
   In addition, ``a monstrous number of troops'' appeared Monday
and Tuesday in Tashkent, the capital of Uzbekistan in Soviet
Central Asia, following a nationalist meeting Sunday, according to
Moscow activist Viktor Rezunkov. There were no tanks and no curfew,
he added.
   Residents of downtown Riga, the capital of Latvia, woke up
Monday to the thunder of tank treads on the cobblestones, said Alex
Grigoriev, editor of the Popular Front newspaper Atmoda, or
Awakening. They looked out their windows to find 10-20 tanks and
other armored vehicles rolling down the street at full speed, with
guns aimed both forward and sideways _ at them, Grigoriev said.
   ``There was panic and indignation,'' he said. ``It was seen as a
provocation and an effort to exert pressure.''
   Ivar Kezbers, a secretary of the Latvian Communist Party,
appeared on television in Riga on Thursday to join the public
complaints and deny military claims that local officials had been
warned about the maneuvers, said Mikhail Bonden, correspondent for
unofficial journal Express-Khronika.
   Five tanks were seen Thursday on the streets of Tartu, Estonia's
university city, shortly before a large student demonstration
against military service, said Tartu resident Petr Vikhalem.
   Friday's Tartu newspapers said the tanks had lagged behind their
unit, which passed through the city during the night, Vikhalem
said. But people assumed the tanks' appearance was related to the
demonstration, he said.
   Armored personnel carriers were seen in the Estonian capital of
Tallinn on Friday, about three miles from downtown, said Tarmu
Tammerk of the newspaper Kodumaa, or Homeland.
   Estonian Radio journalist Sulev Hallik said he had seen no
unusual military activities even though his office is located near
Tallinn's tank regiment. ``It's warm here, but without tanks,'' he
said.
   No explanation was given immediately for the vehicles Tammerk
reported, but Hallik said military vehicles sometimes pass through
the city's outskirts.
   An editor at Estonian TV said Friday he had heard nothing of any
tanks. Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady I. Gerasimov said he knew
nothing about it.
   All three cities have had demonstrations drawing tens of
thousands of people demanding greater autonomy. Estonia's
parliament last fall declared the republic sovereign and gave
itself the right to overturn Soviet laws.
   But activists in the Baltics have taken great pains to prevent
violence that could be used to justify the imposition of martial
law. There have been tense moments between Baltic natives and
Russians, but no violence for at least six months.
   The tanks in Riga were the most obvious, taking up stations at
major downtown intersections for two days, Grigoriev said. Lt. Gen.
Fyodor Kuzmin, commander of the Baltic military district, said on
Latvian TV the tanks ``were on maneuvers,'' Grigoriev reported.
   ``The general said they were training. But for what would they
be training in downtown Riga?'' asked Grigoriev. People feared the
troops might be preparing to put down demonstrations in Riga as
they did in Georgia, he said.
   On Sunday, troops charged Georgian pro-independence
demonstrators rallying in the capital of Tbilisi, and at least 19
people were killed.
   ``It's rather strange that right after Georgia there would be
tanks on the streets of Riga for the first time since the 1940s,''
said Bonden.
   The tanks' appearance coincided with a discussion by the Latvian
government of a proposed law requiring public sector workers to
speak Latvian. That bill is opposed by the ``Interfront'' movement,
a group of Russian nationalists who successfully backed Kuzmin's
election to the new Soviet parliament, Bonden said.
   Kuzmin said the tank exercises had been planned for some time
and local authorities had been forewarned, Grigoriev said. But
Kezbers, the party official, denied that on Latvian TV Thursday and
called the action ``a mistake by the soldiers,'' Grigoriev said.
   Kezbers called the presence of troops in Riga the day after the
tragedy in Georgia and parliamentary run-off elections
``unhealthy,'' Bonden said.
   The dozen armored personnel carriers appeared briefly in Tartu
shortly after noon Thursday, hours before a long-planned student
demonstration demanding the right to do their military service in
Estonia. Tammerk said such protests have been held almost daily in
Estonia recently, due to growing maltreatment of Estonian
conscripts in the army.
   ``They are being labeled fascists, even by officers,'' he said.
Letters in newspapers have offered ``horrific accounts'' of
torture, sexual abuse and beatings, he said.
   Estonian President Arnold Ruutel and Premier Indrek Toome wrote
Thursday to the Soviet Presidium and Defense Minister Dmitri T.
Yazov proposing that Estonians be permitted to perform their
military service in one of the Baltic republics, Tammerk said.
</TEXT>
