<FIRST>u w PM-NorthTrial 4thLd-Writethru a0639 04-14 0739</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-North Trial, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0639,700</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trial Testimony Ends, Jury to Be Sequestered</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDs: CORRECTS word in 2nd graf to feel sted fell; inserts new 7th
graf, The prosecution, with contention North became money-hungry; CORRECTS
word to max sted limit in pvs 12th graf, ``He said''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Testimony in Oliver North's Iran-Contra trial
ended today and the judge said the jury will be isolated when it
starts considering North's fate toward the end of next week.
   ``It seems to us, both sides feel, it's appropriate to sequester
during the ... deliberations,'' said U.S. District Judge Gerhard A.
Gesell.
   Opening statements in the trial took place Feb. 21 and 48 people
have testified since then. Gesell said final arguments will begin
Tuesday, with the jury to be sequestered starting Wednesday night
at the earliest.
   One of the prosecution's final witnesses today was a former
National Security Council official who said North, then an NSC
aide, was so pinched for money that he complained about not having
enough to buy lunch and gasoline.
   But North's complaints suddenly stopped in mid-1985, said Mary
Dix, who was the NSC's director of administration. By that time,
North was controlling a secret cash fund run out of his office safe
intended to provide covert aid to the Contra rebels in Nicaragua.
   The fund was financed by Contra leader Adolfo Calero and former
Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard Secord.
   The prosecution is seeking to portray North as a career military
officer who became money-hungry while working at the NSC.
   North is accused of illegally accepting a $13,800 home security
system from Secord in 1986 and of converting to his own use $4,300
in travelers checks out of the secret stash he kept in the office
safe.
   Ms. Dix testified that North, then a Marine lieutenant colonel,
complained on five occasions through mid-1985 that he was strapped
for cash.
   On a few occasions in the hallway as she was going home, North
would run after her ``yelling Mary, Mary,'' she recalled. She said
that ``he would need cash to go home,'' complaining that he didn't
have enough to buy gasoline.
   In other instances, ``Colonel North would get very upset'' if
the petty cash box for paying cab fare was empty, Ms. Dix said.
   When North wasn't reimbursed rapidly enough for office expenses,
``He would be pretty frantic'' in trying to get NSC staffers to
process his expense accounts, ``to turn them around as soon as
possible.''
   ``He said his credit cards were charged to the max,'' she said.
   On a few other occasions while she was in her office, ``he would
run by. ... His face was red. ... He was very upset with my
staff,'' about not being reimbursed fast enough.
   ``I would herd him from my area,'' she recalled.
   North said at one point that there was ``not enough for cash to
go home'' and ``not enough for lunch money,'' she testified.
   Prosecutor David Zornow asked if North's complaining stopped.
   ``It stopped to the best of my recollection in mid-1985,'' Ms.
Dix replied.
   North testified Monday that the $3,000 balance on a used GMC
Suburban vehicle he bought in October 1985 was paid from money he
kept in a metal box in a closet at his home.
   But the salesman who sold the vehicle, William Howell, testified
today that North said he was going to get the money from the White
House credit union.
   ``It was my understanding that the money was to come from the
White House credit union ... the balance,'' Howell said.
   From February to May 1985, Secord, who had been enlisted by
North to run weapons to the Nicaraguan rebels, arranged four
private sales of arms for the Contras.
   Some $90,000 to $100,000 from Calero was funneled through
North's office safe, as well as $150,000 to $200,000 in cash from
Secord. North said he destroyed the ledger detailing how the money
was spent on orders from CIA Director William Casey.
   In testimony Monday, North said he paid off the $3,038 balance
on the $8,038 vehicle four days after making the down payment.
Prosecutor John Keker asked North whether he got $3,000 in cash
that day from Secord, whose office is a mile or two from the car
lot in Virginia.
   North said he got ``a lot of money from General Secord on a lot
of occasions'' and didn't remember that particular day.
</TEXT>
