<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1444EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Spill-PublicRadio 1stLd-Writethru a0450 04-14 0514</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Public Radio, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0450,0523</SECOND>
<HEAD>Exxon Pays Alaska Public Radio $32,283 for Spill News Coverage</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `Susan Braine..', to CORRECT her title to acting
executive director sted acting news director.</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Spill-Alaska Opinion, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN S. AKRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JUNEAU, Alaska (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Exxon Corp. has sent the Alaska Public
Radio Network more than $32,000 for expenses the 24-station network
has incurred in news coverage of the Exxon Valdez oil spill.
   ``The check's in the mail,'' Exxon spokesman Jan Cool said
Thursday. ``APRN will decide how the money will be distributed to
the stations that covered it.''
   Susan Braine, acting executive director, said network officials
decided it was ethical to accept Exxon money for coverage of a
story in which the oil company is involved.
   ``Exxon has underwritten our programs in the past,'' she said.
``A lot of the oil companies have supported us. It doesn't mean
that we won't report anything negative about them.''
   In many of Alaska's small towns and villages, the network's
member station is the only or primary source of news. The stations
are heavily subsidized by the state through the Alaska Public
Broadcasting Commission, and also rely on underwriting and
donations.
   But unlike underwriting, in which a company or other benefactor
provides money for the network to spend as it wishes, Exxon's
contribution is being made after the fact for coverage of a
specific news event involving the company.
   ``That's an interesting ethical question that I haven't ever
heard of before,'' said Frank Wetzel, ombudsman for The Seattle
Times.
   Wetzel said in a telephone interview that the ethical dilemma is
eased somewhat by the fact that network reporters already have
covered the spill without knowing that Exxon would be paying for
the coverage.
   ``But I wonder about the future,'' he said. ``Will there be some
very subjective withholding of criticism of Exxon now that the
reporters and producers know that their work is being financed by
Exxon? It's a pretty close question, I think.''
   Cool said that while ``the situation is unique,'' Exxon
considers the money just one contribution out of many it makes
routinely. She discounted suggestions that the network's
objectivity might be compromised.
   ``They certainly haven't been pro-Exxon in their coverage,''
Cool said. ``We did this really as a public service for the people
of Alaska who wanted to know the state of the oil spill.''
   Exxon made the contribution after officials learned the network
had asked Rep. Mike Davis to submit a supplemental state budget
request for the $32,283, Cool said.
   The network has maintained round-the-clock coverage of the
spill, sending six reporters and one technician to Prince William
Sound in the three weeks since the tanker Exxon Valdez ran aground.
   Braine said the network would welcome additional money from
Exxon if it was offered.
   Wetzel, however, questioned the wisdom of accepting Exxon's
money when it's earmarked for spill coverage.
   ``If Exxon wanted to make a general contribution, that would be
one thing,'' he said. ``But it has the earmarks of financing
coverage of your own mess.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890414-0140 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1425EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-MailingTaxes Bjt   04-14 0820</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mailing Taxes, Bjt,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>Post Offices Gird for Taxpayers Unable to Put It Off Any Longer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Doughnuts and coffee, pizza and headache
tablets will be available here and there when procrastinating
Americans, unable to put it off any longer, take those dreaded
federal tax forms to post offices for mailing by midnight Monday.
   Taxpayers seeking a sporting chance will find it in Virginia and
Texas, where special postal facilities to accept tax mail will be
added attractions at some baseball fields.
   For most Americans, tax returns must be postmarked by midnight
Monday. As usual, officials expect a crush at post offices.
   In a bid to make the best of the situation, a choice of
refreshments, provided by local broadcasters, will offered to
taxpayers in Salt Lake City.
   Doughnuts will be available at the main post office there thanks
to KDAB, while KLZX will offer pizza at the downtown station and
KKAT will provide refreshments at the West Valley station,
according to postal officials.
   Radio WIBA will include headache tablets in its offer of coffee
and doughnuts for late mailers at the Madison, Wis., Main Post
Office.
   Headache powders will be provided along with coffee by KSSN at
the Little Rock, Ark., general mail facility in North Little Rock.
   A special ``Tax Dodge'' station will operate on University
Boulevard in Little Rock, where KZOU-FM is sponsoring a party and a
special postal station will be set up. There will also be a
fund-raiser for the local United Fund, for taxpayers who have
anything left to give.
   Refreshments will be served and balloons handed out at the
Alexandria, Va., main post office, while nearby Ballston Mall in
Arlington serves up a party in the food concourse, where a special
postal station is set up for the event.
   A special late tax-acceptance facility is being set up at The
Diamond, the field where the Richmond, Va., Braves baseball team
plays. A postal official will throw out the first ball in the
Braves' game against Toledo and a postal chorale will sing the
national anthem.
   Meanwhile, a special postal facility will operate at Texas
Stadium between Dallas and Fort Worth, where Internal Revenue
Service and postal workers will be on hand until midnight.
   In Boise, Idaho, KIZN Radio will provide coffee and doughnuts at
the Main Post Office.
   In Memphis, Tenn., the Peabody Hotel is sponsoring an annual IRS
party, including paying postage for tax mailers who send in their
returns from the special mail booth in the lobby.
   Volunteer IRS officials will be available to answer questions at
postal facilities across the nation including, for example, Austin,
Texas; Minneapolis; Bluefield, W. Va.; Anchorage, Alaska;
Philadelphia; and St. Louis.
   In addition, many post offices will be offering curbside pickup
of returns.
   Postal clerks in Seattle will fan out to four shopping centers
across town to accept returns on Monday, with local radio and
television stations planning live broadcasts at some locations.
   Special collection cans, red ones, will be set out in the
Sacramento, Calif., postal area for April 17 postmarks.
   The mobile post office in Van Nuys, Calif., will be parked in
the parking lot at the main post office to handle last-minute
returns. A special window will be set up for people who need just
two stamps for their taxes, and workers will be stationed along the
curb to pick up returns from motorists.
   In Wichita, Kan., Postmaster Mary A. Brown expects her office to
handle 80,000 extra pieces of mail on Monday and is posting
collectors outside the main post office and a second facility to
collect returns until midnight.
   Even more traffic problems than normal are expected in San Diego
this year. Three collection lanes will be open at the main post
office on Midway Drive, but a sold-out Neil Diamond concert at the
San Diego Sports Arena will be bringing in added traffic and likely
will slow things down.
   Residents of one region get an extra day to file this year,
having until midnight Tuesday. That's because Massachusetts
celebrates a state holiday, Patriot's Day, on Monday.
   As a result, taxpayers whose returns and handled by the IRS
Center in Andover, Mass., have until Tuesday midnight to file,
according to IRS officials in Boston. That region includes all of
New England and part of upstate New York.
   Even though one day later than most of the rest of the country,
the Springfield, Mass., post office will hold its traditional
tax-night party, complete with coffee and a postal-workers band
singing such songs as ``Return to Sender.''
   An estimated 10,000 people attended last year, in attire ranging
from tuxedos to bathrobes.
   Students from Springfield Technical Community College and
representatives of the Massachusetts Department of Revenue will be
on hand to help last-minute filers, many of whom show up each year
with boxes of documents and do their tax calculations on the spot.
</TEXT>
