<FIRST>r a AM-Spill-Exxon     04-14 0656</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Spill-Exxon,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radio Stations, Comedians Take on Exxon</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Tanker Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   In the three weeks since the Alaskan oil spill, irate consumers
have been cutting up their Exxon cards, comedians have been
savaging the petroleum giant, and environmental groups have used
the disaster to galvanize protest.
   Many gas station operators say, however, that they've witnessed
few effects of an organized boycott against Exxon Corp. They are
quick to add that the public should not hold them responsible.
   Radio announcers have been particularly vocal about the spill
and encouraging listeners to take action.
   Station KUBE-FM, for example, organized and promoted a two-hour
rally Wednesday at Seattle's Alki Beach to protest the spill.
Announcers Charlie Brown and Ty Flint spent 12 hours broadcasting
calls from the public about the oil spill. Four other radio
stations joined in a simulcast.
   An estimated 2,000 people attended the rally, forcing Seattle
police to close the only access to the beach.
   Meantime, Michael Siegal of KING in Seattle is trying to
generate national interest in a boycott. He has appeared on other
radio stations around the nation and said he is receiving 200
letters a day, many with cut-up Exxon credit cards.
   Elsewhere in Seattle, more than 500 people jammed a National
Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration hearing Thursday that became
a forum to vent anger over the spill. The meeting was the last of
four called by the agency to identify issues pertinent to the
establishment of a national marine sanctuary along the Northwest
coast.
   ``I'm heartbroken over what happened in Alaska,'' said John
Church, who pasted up bright red ``Remember Valdez'' signs
throughout the building. Valdez is the Exxon tanker that ran
aground on a charted reef March 24 in Prince William Sound,
spilling more than 10 million gallons of oil.
   At radio station KARN in Little Rock, Ark., talk show host Pat
Lynch said Thursday that he has had guests on twice this week to
discuss the Alaska spill.
   ``Listeners are just plain upset and there is, I think, an
unusual sense of rage,'' he said. ``I think it hinges on two
things, one of which is the out and out undisguised greed of price
increases coming at this time, and also the certain knowledge that
the consumer will bear the cost of the Valdez cleanup.''
   In Los Angeles, morning show host Peter Tilden of rock station
KLSX-FM solicited volunteers to help in the cleanup. He also asked
listeners to slice Exxon credits cards and boycott the oil company.
   To others in radio and television, the issue has generated slick
jokes.
   On NBC-TV's ``The Tonight Show,'' host Johnny Carson said, ``I
don't think Exxon's new slogan helps at all: `Exxon, we're not as
bad as Union Carbide.'''
   But joking aside, Wayne Konitshek, managing director of the
Colorado Service Station Dealers Association, said three bomb
threats and two protests have been reported at Exxon service
stations since last weekend.
   He said the association is trying to make the public aware of
the difference between independently owned stations and company
owned stations.
   Independent dealers, he said, ``are as innocent as the otters in
Alaska.''
   Nonetheless, many station operators from Maine to California
said it was business as usual in the wake of the spill. Others
attributed any decline in sales to a recent increase in prices at
the pump.
   Richard Brown, manager of an Exxon station in suburban New
Orleans, said some customers have threatened to stop buying gas in
protest but said there has been no decrease in business.
   For its part, Exxon responded to two consumer groups' boycott
call earlier this week with a statement issued from its New York
headquarters, reiterating its regret about the spill.
   ``All of our customers are very valuable to us and we hope that
our effort in Alaska will convince them that we continue to be a
responsible company and one people like to do business with,''
Exxon said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
