<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1535EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BusinessInventories     04-14 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business Inventories,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inventories Up, Sales Down in February</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government reported Friday that business
inventories rose 0.5 percent in February while sales fell 0.9
percent, a combination that analysts said could point toward
production cutbacks if it continues.
   Inventories held on shelves and backlots climbed to a seasonally
adjusted $763.6 billion in February following a 0.8 percent
increase in January, the Commerce Department reported.
   Sales, meanwhile, dropped to a seasonally adjusted $507.3
billion in February after rising 1.1 percent in the previous month.
The decline was the first since sales fell 0.2 percent in November
1987, the month after the stock market crash, and marked the
steepest drop in more than two years.
   February's report was consistent with a host of other
indications that economic growth is slowing as the record peacetime
expansion extends into its seventh year.
   If increases in inventories are not accompanied by rising sales,
analysts say the result could be production cutbacks that hold down
economic growth.
   Robert G. Dederick, chief economist for Northern Trust Co. in
Chicago, said the inventory buildup isn't alarming yet, ``but
unless we can get some sales they are quickly going to be at a
disturbing level.''
   ``The accumulation rate really has been heavy enough that we
could develop excesses rather quickly if sales did soften,''
Dederick said. ``I view this as a danger area.''
   February's business activity produced an increase in the ratio
of inventories to sales to 1.51 to 1, meaning it would take 1.51
months to exhaust inventories at February's sales pace. The ratio
had been 1.48 to 1 in January.
   February's increase in inventories was led by a 0.8 percent rise
in stocks held by retailers, followed by a 0.5 percent gain in
manufacturer inventories and a 0.2 percent gain at the wholesale
level.
   In the retail category, stockpiles of unsold cars were up 0.4
percent as sales declined 2.4 percent. Auto sales have been weak
this year, and carmakers are offering new incentive programs in
hopes of luring more people to dealerships.
   February's decline in business sales included a 1.7 percent drop
in manufacturer sales, a 0.6 percent drop in retail sales and a
virtually unchanged level of sales activity for wholesalers.
   Analysts have blamed February's poor sales figures on harsh
weather that followed a warm-weather surge in January. March's
advance report on retail sales showed purchases edged up 0.1
percent.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890414-0145 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1500EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u w AM-Trade Bjt   04-14 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Trade, Bjt,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Trade Deficit Widens Sharply as Improvement Fizzles</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserGraphic NY40</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. merchandise trade deficit widened
sharply in February, the government said Friday, bolstering
economists' belief that improvement in the nation's trade
performance is fizzling.
   The Commerce Department said the monthly, seasonally adjusted
deficit swelled 20.9 percent to $10.5 billion, up from a revised
$8.68 billion in January. The deterioration reflected a 5.3 percent
increase in imports, which swamped a slight 0.6 percent improvement
in sales of U.S. goods abroad.
   The trade gap for the first two months of the year is running at
an annual rate of $115 billion, scarcely below the $119.76 billion
deficit for all 1988.
   Commerce Secretary Robert Mosbacher said, ``I continue to be
encouraged that the annual deficit will show further improvement in
1989,'' but most private economists disagree.
   The rise in oil prices to the $20-a-barrel level will inflate
imports, while the strength of the dollar will make the price of
American goods more expensive, discouraging export sales, they say.
   ``Trade fizzled some time ago and this fits in with the theme
that we're still on an unacceptably high plateau,'' said Robert
Dederick, chief economist at Northern Trust Co. in Chicago.
   ``The good news is that after worsening in the fourth quarter,
the trade deficit seems to have narrowed a bit, but the bad news is
that still leaves us no better off than last spring,'' he said.
   A dramatic 21 percent decline in the trade gap last year, from a
peak of $152.1 billion in 1987, accounted for nearly half of
overall economic growth as measured by the gross national product.
The Bush administration is counting on further trade improvement to
bolster the economy and help it meet its pledges to reduce the
federal budget deficit without new taxes.
   The February performance reflected a 5.3 percent jump in
imports, which rose to a seasonally adjusted $39.4 billion. The
higher figure included increases of $1.0 billion in sales of
foreign capital goods to businesses and $800 million in purchases
of foreign cars.
   ``It's clear that major improvement in trade continues to be
held captive by our addiction to imports,'' said economist Jerry
Jasinowski of the National Association of Manufacturers. ``The U.S.
continues to suck in ... industrial materials, parts and
equipment.''
   U.S. oil imports managed to decline 7.2 percent in February to
$3.24 billion despite the third consecutive increase in the price
of a barrel of oil, $15.08, up from $14.46 a month earlier.
   ``We know that has to go up because oil prices are now about $20
a barrel. That's going to add $1 billion a month to the deficit,''
said economist Michael K. Evans, who owns a Washington consulting
firm. ``We're going to have a lot more increases in the trade
deficit. It's going to go to $12 billion a month pretty soon and
it's going to stay there.''
   U.S. exports were up a lackluster 0.6 percent as drops in
agricultural and manufactured products nearly offset gains in sales
of industrial products and autos.
   As usual, the United States posted its largest trade deficit
with Japan in February, $4.65 billion, up 31.7 percent from a
three-year low of $3.53 billion a month earlier.
   The deficit with Western Europe was $624 million, a
deterioration from January's rare $46 million surplus.
   Willard A. Workman, director of international policy for the
U.S. Chamber of Commerce, said the February report indicates that
the drop in the deficit with Japan in January was ``only a blip on
the trade radar scope.''
   The stall in trade fits in with other evidence of slower growth
in reports released Friday, including two consecutive flat months
of industrial production in February and March, a moderation in
wholesale price inflation and the sharpest drop in business sales
in February in more than two years.
</TEXT>
