<FIRST>r i AM-Israel-Shamir     04-14 0479</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Israel-Shamir,0495</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shamir Rejects Trading Land for Peace</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Israel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KARIN LAUB</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEL AVIV, Israel (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said
Friday he rejects trading land for Middle East peace despite an
earlier government statement that Israel is willing to discuss any
option with the Palestinians.
   ``I don't accept it. It is not necessary. It is not relevant,''
he told a news conference on his return to Israel from a 10-day
visit to the United States.
   Shamir, 73, described his visit as a success and added: ``There
is an understanding between the U.S. and Israel about our
four-point peace initiative.''
   Shamir met last week with President Bush, who supported Shamir's
idea for elections in the occupied territories but said the United
States could not accept permanent Israeli occupation of the West
Bank and Gaza Strip, which Israel seized in the 1967 Middle East
war.
   Earlier Friday, Israeli sources confirmed a Jerusalem Post
report that a cable with Shamir's proposal was sent to Israeli
embassies abroad.
   Shamir's plan offers elections to choose representatives from
the occupied territories to negotiate an interim settlement with
Israel.
   In later negotiations on a final status for the territorities,
``Israel will be prepared to discuss any option which will be
presented,'' a source quoted the cable as saying. The source spoke
on condition of anonymity.
   The government statement appeared to leave open the possibility
that Israel would be willing to consider PLO demands for a
Palestinian state despite Israel's stated opposition to such
proposals.
   Several West Bank Palestinians have offered a counterproposal
that says residents should elect members of the PLO's Palestine
National Council instead of representatives for talks with Israel,
Israel radio and Palestinian sources said.
   At a later stage, three of those elected would be nominated to
negotiate a two-year interim agreement with Israel, according to
the reports.
   ``Palestinians see Shamir's plan as an attempt to bypass the
PLO,'' said Palestinian journalist Daoud Kuttab. ``But we are ready
to consider elections to the (council.) This would neutralize the
problem we have with Shamir's idea.''
   The Palestinian plan also calls for partial Israeli army
withdrawal before elections are held under international
supervision.
   In the last stage, the PLO and Israel would negotiate the final
status of the occupied lands in the framework of an international
peace conference.
   Shamir has rejected international supervision of elections,
talks with the PLO and an international conference.
   Shamir's peace plan essentially repeats the 1978 U.S.-sponsored
Camp David Accords, which led to peace with Egypt but have been
rejected by the Palestinians because they promise only limited
self-rule. But it adds the elections for Palestinian negotiating
representatives.
   Like the Camp David Accords, the new plan would leave
negotiations on the final status of the territories until the third
year of a five-year period of autonomy.
   The territories are home to 1.7 million Palestinians.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
