<FIRST>u a PM-WinerySlayings 2ndLd-Writethru a0652 04-14 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Winery Slayings, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0652,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>String Of Shootings Leaves At Least Five Dead, One Injured</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Rewrites throughout to recast, add detail, quote from neighbor.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto, LaserGraphic Staffing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GLEN ELLEN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A series of shootings at a ranch, a
winery and two homes today left at least five people dead, and
authorities say they are looking for a missing winery worker and
his three young daughters.
   A statewide alert was issued for Ramon Salcedo, about 50, after
three persons were found dead at the home of his mother-in-law and
another woman was found dead at his home. The fifth victim was shot
to death at the Grand Cru Winery, where Salcedo worked.
   Authorities did not identify the victims.
   Sonoma County Sheriff Richard Michaelson said it appeared that
Salcedo, went to the ranch of a prominent local man, Bob Kunde, and
wounded ranch worker Kenneth Butti in the shoulder.
   Then, said Michaelson, the gunman went to the Grand Cru Winery
and shot a male co-worker to death before fleeing in an aging
maroon Ford sedan. The body was found in a car near the winery.
   A woman answering the phone at the winery said officials there
would have no comment.
   Michaelson said the gunman then went to his home in nearby Boyes
Hot Springs. The body of a woman was found there, and Salcedo's
three girls, ages 2, 3 and 4, were reported missing.
   Later, Lt. Gary Zanolini said, the bodies of two adults and a
child were found at the home of Salcedo's mother-in-law in Cotati,
about 5 miles west of here.
   ``I've never spoken to him,'' said Carol Settles, who lives near
the Salcedo home.
   ``They are pretty quiet ... except for him yelling,'' said
Settles. ``I never heard what he was saying. I heard them arguing,
but not the words.''
   Butti was listed in fair condition at Santa Rosa Memorial
Hospital.
   Glen Ellen is a town of 1,500 in the wine-making region of
Sonoma County, north of San Francisco.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
