<FIRST>r a AM-OklaCentennial     04-14 0531</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Okla Centennial,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blue Coats Returning To Oklahoma Fort</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GIL BROYLES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EL RENO, Okla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A century after one-tenth of the United
States Army converged on a parcel of land in Indian Territory to
oversee the region's first great land run, the blue coats are
returning to Fort Reno.
   About 500 re-enactors _ including 150 military hobbyists from
five states _ will take part in a weekend encampment organizers
hope will authentically reproduce the excitement of the days before
the Run of '89, in which settlers stampeded the area to claim land
that was free for the taking.
   The goal is to ``give a good history lesson,'' said Deborah
Foreman, who with her husband Gary helped organize ``Fort Reno and
Indian Territory Days.''
   Participants representing cavalry and infantry units of the
period are coming from Illinois, Arkansas, Louisiana and Texas as
well as Oklahoma, Mrs. Foreman said.
   Spectators at the Fort Reno parade grounds Saturday and Sunday
will see cavalry competition, infantry drills, Indian dancing, a
wagon demonstration, a frontier fashion show, period music and
simulated gunfights, she said.
   About 120 Indians will show how their ancestors lived before the
land run and will participate in ceremonies during the
re-enactment, Mrs. Foreman said.
   She said organizers were careful to consider the feelings of
tribal officials, who see no reason to celebrate the centennial of
another episode in which the government took away Indian land.
   ``This event is a living history demonstration. This is not a
land run celebration,'' Mrs. Foreman said.
   The events at the historic fort west of El Reno constitute the
largest authentic re-enactment in the state. It is a prelude to
events in Guthrie, where the centennial of the land rush will be
observed the following weekend.
   A century ago, thousands of settlers gathered in camps around
the Unassigned Lands in the days before the run, collecting
supplies and girding for a mad dash for land.
   About 2,500 soldiers were stationed in and around the 2 million
acres of the Unassigned Lands in what is now central Oklahoma.
Their job was to help federal marshals keep the peace and to keep
out the ``Sooners'' who tried to sneak in early.
   ``Most of the trouble encountered was evicting squatters,
rounding up cattle rustlers, timber thieves, hunters and notifying
ranch owners to vacate their cattle prior to April 20,'' Sgt. John
Brandt, trumpeter of Troop L, 5th Cavalry, wrote.
   At noon on April 22, 1889, the boom of cannon from Fort Reno and
gunshots and bugles elsewhere signaled the beginning of the run for
more than 40,000 settlers.
   ``There were sounds of a mighty roar and cheer, whips cracking
and men shouting to their horses,'' said Brandt, who was stationed
near Purcell, one of eight major starting points for the run.
   ``The saddle horses plunged and raced by at top speed, the
lighter vehicles and faster horses stretched out towards the river.
Then the slower horses and heavier wagons thundered by.''
   While there were more than a dozen other land openings through
lotteries and runs before statehood in 1907, historians say it was
the first land run that started the inevitable movement toward
statehood.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890414-0154 </DOCNO>
