<FIRST>r w AM-US-Nicaragua     04-14 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Nicaragua,540</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Department Praises Contra Aid Pact, Warns Sandinistas of Deadline</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Friday praised
congressional approval of new aid for the Contra rebels and warned
the Nicaraguan government that the deadline for fulfilling its
commitment to political reforms was only 11 days away.
   The State Department's statement appears designed to use the
leverage it was granted by Congress to prod the Soviet-backed
Nicaraguan government into giving the Contras a share in the
political process.
   Vice President Dan Quayle, meantime, told the American Society
of Newspaper Editors convention he hopes the American press will
watch Nicaraguan President Daniel Ortega closely to see if he keeps
his commitments to democratic reforms.
   ``Are the Sandinistas finally willing to take the course that
all the Central American governments committed themselves to ...?
Are they prepared to negotiate with the internal opposition and the
Nicaraguan resistance in order to promote national reconciliation
among all Nicaraguans?'' he asked. ``We will know the answers to
these questions, and we will know them relatively soon.''
   Congress on Thursday approved a $49.7 million package of food
and medical aid for the Contras to last them for 10 months until
they can return to their homes in Nicaragua and be assured
participation in a democratic political system.
   The compromise package was worked out by Secretary of State
James A. Baker III to avoid the kind of divisiveness with the
Democratic-controlled Congress which derailed past administration
attempts to aid the Contras.
   ``We welcome passage of the legislation,'' said spokeswoman
Margaret Tutwiler. ``Approval of this assistance is a tangible
manifestation of bipartisanship.''
   At the same time, the Sandinista government must now comply with
an agreement by the Central American countries which calls for
Nicaragua ``to create the conditions which will allow for the
reintegration of the resistance into a safe, democratic
Nicaragua,'' she said.
   ``We are deeply concerned by the refusal thus far by the
Sandinistas to negotiate with the internal opposition on the reform
of electoral laws,'' Ms. Tutwiler said.
   On Thursday, the ruling Sandinista party condemned the Contra
aid package, saying it threatens the Nicaraguan government and
``makes fun of the will of the Central American presidents.''
   The presidents of El Salvador, Honduras, Guatemala and Costa
Rica signed a pact on Feb. 14 in El Salvador, agreeing to draft a
plan by mid-May to dismantle the Contras, most of whom are in
jungle camps in Honduras near the Nicaraguan border.
   In the pact, Ortega promised legal reforms to guarantee fair
general elections, which he moved up by 10 months, to Feb. 25,
1990. The first stage of the reforms is supposed to be in place by
April 25.
   ``Only 11 days remain before the deadline established'' at the
El Salvador meeting, the State Department said in a statement.
   ``We hope the government of Nicaragua will engage in a genuine
dialogue to achieve a national consensus on necessary reforms,''
the statement said.
   ``It is increasingly clear that the Sandinistas' conduct must be
closely scrutinized by all who care about the future of democracy
in Nicaragua,'' it said.
   Such scrutiny was one of the main motives cited by supporters of
the compromise Contra aid package in Congress, who hope it will put
the Sandinista leadership under intense international pressure to
keep its promises.
</TEXT>
