<FIRST>r i AM-Korea     04-14 0461</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0478</SECOND>
<HEAD>War Veterans Scrawl Anti-Communist Slogans in Blood</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos SEL1,8</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of war veterans, some
scrawling anti-communist slogans with their blood, on Friday
denounced a dissident clergyman who visited communist North Korea
for reunification talks.
   At a rival protest, about 5,000 radical students hurled
firebombs and rocks as they battled police for a second day in
support of the Rev. Moon Ik-hwan.
   He was arrested Thursday on his return from an illegal 10-day
trip to North Korea that included meetings with communist leader
Kim Il Sung.
   The war veterans, numbering about 10,000, rallied in Seoul,
where they burned large effigies of Moon giving a bear hug to the
North Korean leader. TV broadcasts showing the embrace angered many
South Koreans who blame Kim for the 1950-53 Korean War that took
more than 1 million lives.
   Enraged veterans at the rally bit their fingers until they drew
blood, then scrawled slogans on posters that said: ``Crush leftist
leanings!'' and ``Protect democracy!''
   They began a mainly peaceful march on the presidential mansion,
demanding the government disband dissident groups and jail their
members.
   ``Destroy communists!'' they shouted. ``Execute the Moon Ik-hwan
clique!'' Riot police turned them away several blocks from the
mansion.
   Several veterans later delievered a letter to the prime
minister's office calling for stronger action to stamp out what
they called spreading left-wing sentiment.
   Preliminary charges filed against Moon, 71, carry the death
sentence under the tough national security law, which requires
South Koreans to get government permission to visit the north.
   Police earlier arrested 60 members of right-wing youth groups
who briefly occupied the Seoul offices of the country's biggest
dissident organization, the United National Democratic Movement,
which Moon advises.
   In Seoul and two provincial cities, Taegu and Kwangju, radical
students clashed with police firing tear gas. They demanded Moon's
release and the overthrow of President Roh Tae-woo.
   Police said some people were injured and others were arrested
during the demonstrations, but they gave no figures.
   Also Friday, state TV reported that dozens of students attacked
two police substations with firebombs and sticks, one in Seoul and
on in southern Taegu city. They smashed windows of the buildings,
it said. Few South Koreans share the views of the radical students.
   In a related development, police Friday said they arrested
newspaper executive Im Jae-kyung, accusing him of planning a trip
to North Korea to interview Kim. Police earlier arrested an
editorial writer for Im's opposition Hankyoreh newspaper. They say
he too wanted to visit Pyongyang without government approval.
   The two nations have been bitter rivals since the division of
the peninsula at the end of World War II. That enmity deepened when
North Korea invaded the south in 1950.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
