<FIRST>r a AM-Hoffman'sMother 1stLd-Writethru a0664 04-14 0497</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hoffman's Mother, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0664,0510</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Remembers Abbie As Loving Son, Funny Child</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 8th, `My son...' to UPDATE with memorial
service planned.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHELLE LOCKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florence and John Hoffman wanted their son to be a
doctor. Instead, he became the wisecracking founder of the radical
Yippie movement, horrifying his father as he ducked underground in
skirmishes with the establishment.
   Having Abbie Hoffman as a son could be difficult, but it was a
relationship spiced with adventure and an indomitable humor, his
mother recalled Friday.
   ``He had a wonderful sense of humor. He loved every funny book
he could put his hands on,'' she said.
   ``I never thought he was going to become famous. I never had
that in mind,'' Mrs. Hoffman, 83, said in a telephone interview
from her home in Worcester.
   Hoffman, 52, was found dead Wednesday in his bed at his
apartment in New Hope, Pa.
   An autopsy on Hoffman was inconclusive and officials said they
would not know the results of toxicology tests until next week at
the earliest.
   Mrs. Hoffman said her son had been troubled, but she didn't
believe he had killed himself.
   ``My son knew that he had problems,'' Mrs. Hoffman said. ``They
found no drugs around him. I think suicide may be ruled out.''
   A memorial service was planned for Wednesday at Temple Emanuel
in Worcester, the synagogue Hoffman attended as a child.
   Hoffman became famous with the Chicago Seven, a group of
radicals who stood trial on charges of conspiring to disrupt the
1968 Democratic National Convention in Chicago. He was acquitted of
conspiracy and a conviction of crossing state lines with intent to
riot was overturned.
   He also founded the loosely organized Yippie movement, or Youth
International Party, in 1968 to bring together radicals to protest
the government and the Vietnam War.
   John Hoffman, a pharmacist who worked long hours running a
medical supply company, could never accept his son's outlaw status,
Mrs. Hoffman said.
   ``My husband took it really hard,'' she said. ``When he was
underground, my husband just couldn't take the news when this
happened.'' He died while his son was in hiding to avoid trial on
cocaine charges.
   ``Of course everyone has ambitions. I wanted him to be a good
student and be able to make it in life. Maybe I was over ambitious.
Maybe we both were,'' Mrs. Hoffman said.
   The Hoffmans drove Abbie to Brandeis University for an interview
at the medical school, but instructors advised that he was better
at mathematics than medicine. At Brandeis, Hoffman's interests
turned to psychology.
   Mrs. Hoffman credited Brandeis, a cradle of 1960s activism, with
Hoffman's emergence as a radical leader.
   Hoffman never followed the conventional path his parents had
envisioned, but Mrs. Hoffman said she was always sure of his
affection.
   ``Yes he did love me and I loved him too,'' she said. ``But what
can you do? Things happen in your life.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890414-0163 </DOCNO>
