<FIRST>r w AM-Governors-Trade     04-14 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Governors-Trade,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Virginia's Governor Saw Gold Mine in Chicken Feet</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM M. WELCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Virginia Gov. Gerald Baliles was struck, he
recalled Friday, by the chicken feet he saw frequently at meals
during a trade mission to the Far East.
   When he got home, he said, he asked Virginia chicken producers
what they did with the feet of chickens they process.
   ``They laughed,'' Baliles recounted, ``and said they're cut off
and thrown away. I said, `I think we've found a new market.'''
   As a result, Baliles told fellow governors Friday, Virginia now
exports 40 tons of chicken feet and related products every month to
foreign markets where they are more valued.
   Baliles, a Democrat and chairman of the National Governors'
Association, cited the chicken-feet example as he and several
colleagues released a report saying governors should do more to
encourage international exports by businesses within their states.
   The report by the association's task force on foreign markets
said states must develop new links with foreign countries if their
citizens are to succeed in a future economy that will be
increasingly dependent on international trade.
   It suggested states and governors:
   _ Come up with their own targeted plan for finding new markets
for producers and service-providing companies within their own
states, and encouraging development of products in demand by
foreign nations.
   _ Elevate foreign trade to a top priority and increase public
awareness of the connections between their own economy and
international markets.
   _ Appoint ``trade czars,'' an official in each state with
cabinet-level rank who would direct and coordinate its plan for
encouraging international trade.
   _ Help firms obtain financing for export deals, either through
direct state loans and loan-guarantee programs, or by serving as
brokers and clearinghouses to match commercial lenders with
businesses. Some states are already serving as loan brokers.
   _ Consider pooling resources for trade and tourism promotion in
groups of states, as Mississippi, Louisiana and Arkansas have done
to promote their products jointly.
   ``We can do something about international competition,'' Baliles
said. ``We can develop an export culture. We can develop programs
that identify markets.
   The governors released their report as part of a day-long
conference on increasing business dealings between states and
developing nations. It came on a day when the Commerce Department
announced a worsening trade deficit for the United States, with the
gap between merchandise imports and exports swelling by 20.9
percent, to $10.5 billion, in February.
   ``While the federal government sets the rules on trade, success
in developing and expanding foreign markets depends on the
decisions of thousands of corporations and business people,''
Baliles said. ``State governments are positioned to help.''
   Mississippi Gov. Ray Mabus, who headed the task force, said his
state has just begun pushing exports and has had success in selling
Mississippi catfish to the Soviet Union.
   Mabus, a Democrat, said Baliles told him his chicken story
earlier.
   ``I went back and talked to my chicken producers,'' Mabus said.
``Now we sell as much chicken feet as Virginia does.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890414-0165 </DOCNO>
