<FIRST>u w PM-ASNE-SmallPapers 1stLd-Writethru a0593 04-14 0251</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-ASNE-Small Papers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0593,240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fourteen Small Papers Honored</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Subs 3rd graf to CORRECT spelling of Waterville paper.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A committee of the American Society of
Newspaper editors has selected 14 small newspapers for recognition
as the best in the United States.
   James Herman, editor of the Traverse City, Mich., Record-Eagle,
announced the results at a program on excellence in small
newspapers at the society's convention here Thursday.
   The papers selected are the Ann Arbor, Mich., News; the
Alexandria, La., Town Talk; the Biloxi, Miss., Sun-Herald; the
Central Maine Morning Sentinel of Waterville, Maine; the Cape Cod
Times of Hyannis, Mass.; the Concord Monitor of Concord, N.H.; The
Express of Easton, Pa.; the Gloucester County Times of Woodbury,
N.J.; the Gwinnett Daily News, Lawrenceville, Ga.; the Jackson,
Tenn., Sun; the Leesburg, Fla., Daily Commercial; the Middlesex
News of Framingham, Mass.; the Owensboro, Ky., Messenger-Inquirer;
and the St. Cloud, Minn., Times.
   The newspapers were selected in a two-stage process from among
1,357 papers of under 50,000 circulation in the country.
   Last year, Jean Abbott of the University of Missouri School of
Journalism conducted a survey in which editors of all of the
newspapers were asked to name the three outstanding ones in their
states.
   Herman said he then asked the editors of the 150 papers selected
by this process to submit copies of their papers, which they did in
February.
   A panel of judges named by Herman selected what they considered
outstanding examples from among these submissions.
