<DOCNO> AP890414-0167 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1705EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-SovietSub     04-14 0411</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Sub,0424</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Sub Was Conducting Experiments When Disaster Broke Out</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet nuclear-powered submarine was testing
deep sea dives and conducting scientific experiments when it caught
fire and sank off Norway, Tass said Friday.
   The official news agency said investigators have come up with
four probable causes of April 7 disaster, which killed 42 of the 69
sailors aboard, but it did not list them. It also said a decision
on whether to salvage the submarine could take months.
   In Oslo, Norwegian experts said the sub's nuclear reactors and
weapons are apparently intact in the vessel on the ocean floor.
   Eight water samples collected near the sunken vessel, 5,000 feet
beneath the ocean surface, detected no radiation leakage, said
Norway's National Institute of Radiation Protection.
   Tass said the submarine was an experimental vessel that was
testing deep dives and unusual materials when the accident happened.
   ``The test program covered a total of 12 scientific and
technological problems and even in the short time during which the
submarine was put through its paces, it produced exceptional
research results,'' it said without elaboration.
   The Soviet nuclear-powered vessel is thought to be one of that
country's most advanced submarines.
   A decision on whether to attempt to raise the submarine will not
be made for several months, Tass said, quoting Deputy Prime
Minister Igor Belovsov.
   Several officials at a news conference Thursday for Soviet
journalists blamed the severity of the fire on the flow of
high-pressure air into the burning compartment, Tass said, but the
cause of the fire is unknown.
   ``Experts have identified four most probable causes of the sub's
loss, but won't yet make the final conclusion,'' Tass said. It
quoted Belovsov as saying the government commission investigating
the accident agreed on the need to develop new sea rescue
techniques and lifesaving equipment.
   The Norweigan institute said the vessel apparently withstood
tremendous water pressure and explosions that sank the ship.
   The Soviets have said the submarine's two reactors were shut
down before the crew evacuated and that neither of the two
nuclear-tipped torpedoes was armed for combat. They said there was
no danger of radioactivity being released from the sunken vessel.
   But the institute said it may collect more water samples.
Deepwater currents may have prevented accurate detection of
radioactivity, said Johan Baarli, director of the government
institute.
   Earlier tests taken near the sub, 310 miles off Norway's
northern coast, showed no atmospheric contamination from the
sinking.
</TEXT>
