<FIRST>r a AM-NukeProtest     04-14 0212</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nuke Protest,0218</SECOND>
<HEAD>105 New Arrests at Nevada Site</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Anti-nuclear protesters tried to block traffic
in and out of the Nevada Test Site on Friday, and 65 people were
arrested on misdemeanor nuisance charges when they failed to move
from the site's main road.
   Forty others were arrested on trespass charges during the night.
   Friday's arrests bring to 452 the number of citations issued
since the annual ``Reclaim the Test Site'' protest began April 7
and ending Sunday.
   Energy Department spokesman Jim Boyer said 400 protesters showed
up near the gates to the site Thursday night and 200 of them sat
down on the main road and blocked buses and cars carrying workers
to and from the secret desert site.
   The traffic was rerouted and the protesters were allowed to
remain until dawn, when they were told they would be arrested if
they did not move.
   Boyer said no major traffic delays were reported Friday.
   Chris Brown of the sponsoring American Peace Test said the
protesters hoped to block workers from the test site.
   Nye County officials say they will no longer prosecute
protesters who are cited for misdemeanor violations at the remote
desert because of the growing number of protests against the
nation's nuclear testing program.
