<FIRST>u w AM-US-Soviet Bjt   04-14 0481</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Soviet, Bjt,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Says Gorbachev Running Risks With Economic Reform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III said
Friday that Mikhail S. Gorbachev's critics may try to stifle his
economic reform program unless he succeeds in getting ``consumer
goods on the table and in the markets.''
   Baker said that the political reforms Gorbachev has pushed as
part of ``perestroika,'' or resturcturing, are progressing faster
than his economic reforms.
   ``That might trigger something,'' he said. ``These things
generally have to proceed apace.''
   Addressing the American Society of Newspaper Editors, the
secretary commented:
   ``If they are unable to get the economic part of this going and
going well so there are consumer goods on the table and in the
markets, that's going to give rise, I suppose, to some feelings on
the part of some that this idea of perestroika doesn't mean much to
the common man or woman in the Soviet Union.''
   Baker said Gorbachev's program entails risks to him from
opponents of change, entrenched elements of the Soviet bureaucracy
and ``sources of nationalistic discontent.''
   The secretary, who will meet with Gorbachev and Soviet Foreign
Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze next month in Moscow, said that a
reversal of perestroika ``would be unfortunate.''
   Unless the West adopts an ``obstructionist approach'' to the
Soviet Union, he said, ``it's our view that whether or not
perestroika succeeds will depend on what happens in the Soviet
Union and not on what we in the West might do or might not do.''
   Answering a subsequent question, Baker said:
   ``We very much want perestroika to succeed and we very much want
the general secretary to succeed. We think that's in the best
interest of the United States and the best interest of the world.
...''
   Just this week, a Moscow newspaper said sugar rationing would
begin in the Soviet capital for the first time since World War II.
   And the daily Socialist Industry said earlier this month that
many Soviet citizens ``can expect that the year 1989 will be the
most unsuccessful of all those we have lived through. ... The bony
hand of hunger for products is quite capable of strangling
perestroika.''
   Addressing the editors, Baker mixed praise of Gorbachev and
perestroika with a complaint that ``there remain too many areas
where the slogans of new thinking lack content.''
   For instance, Baker said he intended to confront the Soviet
leaders with their recent sale of high-performance bombers to Libya.
   Repeating U.S. charges that the North African country supports
terrorism, Baker asked, ``How does this sale assist in the
worldwide efforts, supposedly supported by Moscow, to control
chemical weapons that Libya is developing at its Rabta plant?''
   He also renewed U.S. demands that the Berlin Wall be torn down
and that the Soviets repudiate the Brezhnev Doctrine, which asserts
a right to intervene in East European countries.
</TEXT>
