<FIRST>r i AM-Salvador     04-14 0304</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Salvador,0313</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bombs Damage House of Vice President-Elect</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto SAL1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three bombs exploded Friday in
the master bedroom and dining room of Vice President-elect
Francisco Merino's home, slightly injuring a child and causing
extensive damage, police said.
   Merino and his wife, Maria Antonieta, were visiting the United
States, but the couple's four young children and three friends were
sleeping in the house in affluent Maquilishuat suburb when it was
bombed at dawn. The injured child, who was cut by a piece of
debris, was a friend of Merino's children.
   Seven or eight men raced up in two cars, lobbed 2{-pound blocks
of TNT over a wall surrounding the garden, and sped away, a
policeman quoted witnesses as saying. Three bombs exploded and the
other was deactivated later, he said on condition of anonymity.
   President-elect Alfredo Cristiani blamed the leftist Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front when he visited the house afer the
attack. An anonymous caller told a radio station the rebels were
not responsible.
   The caller said they had nothing to do with the attack ``even
though Merino is one of those who is promoting terror, repression
and slaughter of our people, and we consider that he deserves this
and much more.''
   The Marxist-led insurgents have fought nine years against the
U.S.-backed government.
   Cristiani said the bombing ``demonstrates that they are savages
who are not interested in peace, but only interested in terrorizing
the civilian population. I think very little can be achieved, as
far as pacifying the country, through dialogue with these kind of
people.''
   Cristiani and Merino, of the rightist Republican Nationalist
Alliance, were elected March 19. They take office June 1 from
Christian Democratic President Jose Napoleon Duarte.
   Merino was to return to El Salvador later Friday.
</TEXT>
