<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1709EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Quayle     04-14 0414</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Quayle,410</SECOND>
<HEAD>Quayle Says Bush Is Accessible</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Write</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just as George Bush refused to discuss his
private chats with President Reagan, Vice President Dan Quayle
wouldn't say Friday what he and Bush talk about in the White House
inner sanctum.
   But during a question-and-answer session with members of the
audience at the American Society of Newspaper Editors convention,
Quayle did provide some insights into how Bush conducts himself
during these high-level meetings.
   ``He enjoys the give and take,'' Quayle said. ``He enjoys having
ideas put forward, whether it be by me or by others. He enjoys the
competition of ideas and discussion of policy and where we ought to
be going.''
   Quayle, however, declined to respond when asked to cite what
differences he may have had with the president in the nearly three
months they've been in office.
   ``I'm not going to get into private conversations that I have
with the president and what kind of influence and how I think I can
influence his decisions,'' Quayle said. ``It wouldn't be
appropriate. I've decided not to do it _ and if I did engage, and
do it, I would lose my effectiveness.''
   When he was campaigning for the presidency, Bush steadfastly
refused, in debate and in exchanges with reporters, to discuss
whatever he might have said to Reagan or what Reagan might have
said to him.
   This question arose frequently in the context of what Bush knew
about the Iran-Contra scandal and what role he might have played in
it.
   Quayle also said Friday he's pleased with the access he has to
the president.
   ``I have the right to go into his office anytime,'' he said,
adding that he has had several one-on-one meetings with Bush in
addition to their regular Thursday lunches.
   Asked to compare his vice presidential style with that of Bush,
Quayle told the audience that ``from the operational point of view
... it is essentially the same type of vice presidency.''
   ``Now, obviously, I'm a different individual than President
Bush, and obviously, in a period of time, you will have a Quayle
model of the vice presidency,'' he said. ``We're just starting.''
   ``I would say from a philosophical and an ideological point of
view, that there is from a practical point of view, no difference
at all,'' he said. But Quayle also said, ``Obviously in style, in
rhetoric, things of that sort, we will approach the job in a
different manner.''
</TEXT>
