<FIRST>r w AM-US-Mideast     04-14 0658</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Mideast,640</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Still Sees Jewish Settlements As Impediments to Peace</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department spokeswoman said Friday
that the United States still views Jewish settlements in the West
Bank and Gaza as impediments to peace, and urged Palestinians and
Israelis to refrain from exacerbating their tensions.
   The comments by department spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler
followed Thursday's clash in the occupied West Bank village of
Nahalin in which Israeli forces shot and killed at least five
Palestinians in one of the bloodiest incidents of the 16-month
Palestinian uprising.
   An estimated 80,000 Jews live in settlements among an estimated
1.7 million Palestinians, but settlement construction has been
scaled back in recent years by budgetary and political constraints.
   Under an agreement reached by partners in Israel's coalition
government last year, the first of eight new settlements went up
last week in the West Bank, not far from the village.
   In response to reports that the United States had changed its
policy on Jewish settlements, Ms. Tutwiler said, ``there is no
change in our policy. Our policy remains what it has been.
   ``We continue to believe that new settlements do not contribute
to a climate that can promote the peace process,'' she said.
   Ms. Tutwiler said ``the loss of life and injuries which occurred
... yesterday is tragic. We urge all sides to refrain from engaging
in confrontations that lead to the unnecessary loss of life.''
   The United States, she said, wants ``to see the violence stopped
and see steps taken that can begin to defuse the tension on the
ground.''
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III passed a similar message
to Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir during Shamir's recent
visit. Shamir proposed holding elections among the Palestinians as
one tension-reducing step.
   But the Palestine Liberation Organization has rejected any
slowing of the Palestinian uprising until Israel withdraws from the
lands it captured in the 1967 war.
   Meantime, the State Department registered opposition to any
effort to grant the PLO membership in the United Nations.
   ``In our view, the self-declared Palestinian state, which we do
not recognize, does not meet the generally accepted international
law criteria for statehood,'' a department statement said. It added
that the PLO ``does not qualify for membership in U.N. agencies.''
   The statement responded to a letter by 38 senators urging Baker
to oppose U.N. recognition of the PLO as a member state, an
upgrading of its current observer status.
   In New York, the PLO's permanent observer Zuhdi Labib Terzi told
The Associated Press that his organization was not considering
applying to the U.N. for membership now. ``That would be
premature,'' he said.
   ``We have not yet gone to the Security Council to apply,'' he
said. ``We are not that stupid when the U.S. holds a veto'' over
the council's decisions.
   The State Department also addressed the latest violence in
Lebanon.
   In a departure from previous statements, the State Department
named Syria as one of the parties being urged to cease fire in
Beirut. Until now, repeated U.S. urgings for calm in Lebanon have
failed to name Syria, referring to it only as a warring party.
   ``We condemn the savage shelling in Beirut on Thursday. It was a
reprehensible reminder that 14 years of armed conflict have failed
to solve Lebanon's problems,'' said a department statement.
   ``We reprove all participants in yesterday's fighting, both
Lebanese and non-Lebanese. We call on all combatants, including the
Lebanese armed forces, the different militias and the Syrian army
to cease fire,'' it said.
   The statement also called on Christian leader Gen. Michel Aoun
to pursue his recent proposal for power-sharing talks with
Lebanon's Moslem majority, saying Moslem Prime Minister Salim
al-Hoss should take Aoun up on his offer.
   In an apparent reference to Aoun's stated intention of expelling
the 40,000 Syrian troops from Lebanon, the statement said that
``force will not unite the Lebanese, neither will it cause foreign
troops to withdraw.''
</TEXT>
