<FIRST>r i AM-Soviet-Armenians     04-14 0208</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Armenians,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Armenians Seek Permission For Moscow Memorial March</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of Armenians is seeking permission from
Moscow authorities to stage a march in memory of Armenians who were
killed by the Turks between 1915 and 1920, a group member said
Friday.
   Karen Saakian said he submitted an application to the Moscow
City Council to stage the march April 24 to commemorate ``the first
mass genocide of the 20th Century.'' The group vowed to stage the
march even if it is denied permission.
   Memorial services generally are held each year in Armenia to
honor the dead.
   The Ottomans accused the Armenians living in eastern Turkey of
helping the invading Russians during World War I and ordered the
Armenian population deported to Syria.
   Armenians were rounded up, their homes destroyed and their
property seized. Hundreds of thousands died from beatings,
starvation and exposure during the trip.
   Armenians have said 1.5 million died, but Turkish officials have
disputed that figure, saying there were only 1.4 million Armenians
living in Turkey at the turn of the century. They claim about
300,000 Armenians were killed. Historians have estimated 600,000
dead.
   Saakian said the group put in its application for the march
Thursday but had not received an answer.
</TEXT>
