<HEAD>Pope Receives African Leader Who Wants to Offer Cathedral</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VATICAN CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pope John Paul II met Friday with the
president of the Ivory Coast, who said he came to Rome to offer the
Roman Catholic leader a basilica he is building in his West African
nation.
   Other than describing the meeting as ``very cordial,'' the
Vatican released no details of the private half-hour audience with
President Felix Houphouet-Boigny.
   No one from the African delegation could be reached to see if
the president had indeed made his offer about the basilica, which
will be Africa's biggest center for Christian worship and only
slightly smaller than St. Peter's in Rome, Christendom's largest
basilica.
   After Friday's audience, the pope gave the president an icon of
the Black Madonna, revered throughout Poland, the pontiff's native
country. The African leader gave the pontiff two blocks of marble
from the Ivory Coast basilica.
   The $130 million Notre Dame Peace basilica in Yamoussoukro is
expected to be inaugurated later this year.
   Vatican officials say the pope has no intention of attending the
ceremony, an attitude some have taken as a sign of disapproval for
such opulence during the Ivory's Coast worst economic crisis in 28
years of independence.
   While visiting Paris in March, Houphouet-Boigny said that when
he met the pope he would ask him to accept the basilica in the name
of the Vatican.
