<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1725EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Greece-US     04-14 0239</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-US,0249</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Progress Made in Talks on U.S. Bases</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 16th round of talks on the future of
U.S. military bases in Greece ended Friday without making any
progress, a government spokesman said.
   The talks on a new defense and economic cooperation agreement,
which began Monday, stumbled on Greece's insistence the United
States help Athens solve differences with neighboring Turkey,
spokesman Sotiris Kostopoulos said.
   U.S. negotiators said they don't want regional disputes wound
into the bilateral talks.
   Greece and Turkey have longstanding quarrels over seabed mineral
rights, military control of the Aegean sea and the war-divided
Mediterranean island of Cyprus.
   Another issue clouding the talks is Greece's reluctance to
extradite a suspected Palestinian terrorist, Mohammed Rashid,
wanted by the United States for the 1982 bombing of a Pan Am jumbo
jet, Kostopoulos said. The blast killed a Japanese teen-ager and
injured 15 other passengers.
   Rashid is in Athens' top-security prison awaiting a decision on
the extradition from Greece's Supreme Court. The decision has been
delayed three times since the 34-year-old Palestinian was arrested
at the Athens Airport.
   The United States may cut its military aid to Greece if Rashid
is not extradited, U.S. diplomats have said.
   The five-year base agreement expired Dec. 20. Under the accord,
the United States has 17 months to leavrsal from the Reagan
administration, raised environmental concerns about the sale of oil
and gas leases in the three offshore areas _ off the southern and
northern California coastlines and off southern Florida in the Gulf
of Mexico.
   In each case, environmentalists have vigorously fought oil
exploration, arguing the lease sites are too close to
environmentally fragile and important ecosystems.
   The president directed that the lease sales, which were
scheduled to begin this year and next, be put on hold until a
further environmental impact study by the task force can be
completed. The group plans to report to the president by the end of
the year.
   Lujan rejected suggestions by some environmental groups that the
task force is biased toward oil development. Environentalists had
wanted environmental groups, fishermen and the Florida and
California state governments represented, but were rebuffed.
   ``We think it' very well balanced'' said Lujan. The task force
includes representatives from the interior and energy departments
as well as the Environmental Protection Agency and National Oceanic
and Atmospheric Administration. The National Academy of Sciences
serves as a consultant.
   Lujan said that the Alaska spill has made it imperative to take
a close look at transportation and emergency response issues in
considering the environmental questions surrounding oil drilling in
the three lease areas.
   Robert Kallman, executive director of the task force, said in
some cases the government might require pipelines to be built
instead of using supertankers such as the one that ran aground in
Alaska.
   Kallman said that while the southern California area is most
suited for transporting oil through pipelines, the industry likely
would want to opt for tanker transportation in the northern
California and Florida fields.
   Kallman recently resigned as director of the Minerals Management
Service at the Interior Department where he was responsible for
managing the federal offshore oil and gas leasing program. He
described himself Friday as a supporter of offshore drilling ``as
long as it's environmentally possible and feasible.''
   The three lease areas were to be put up for sale this year or
early next year until Bush called for additional environmental
studies. Officials acknowledge that opposition is likely to become
more intense after the Alaska spill.
   In the lease area under review off the Florida coast, oil
companies already have purchased 73 leases for more than $100
million, but have been prevented from drilling by a moratorium
imposed by Congress. The task force study covers only leases that
have not yet been sold, so oil companies would be free to drill on
the 73 leases they already own when the congressional moratorium
expires in October.
   But Lujan said Friday he would be strongly opposed to any such
drilling prior to completion of the task force report. He suggested
that ``anybody with an ounce of brains'' would think twice before
going ahead with drilling before the task force report is completed
and a decision is made by the president on whether to go ahead with
selling additional leases.
</TEXT>
