<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1739EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Austria-Scandal     04-14 0282</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Austria-Scandal,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Interior Minister Resigns Over Fraud Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROLAND PRINZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Interior Minister Karl Blecha
resigned from public office Friday amid mounting criticism of his
role in a $16 million scandal involving the mysterious sinking of a
ship.
   Socialist Chancellor Franz Vranitzky hinted he had wanted the
resignations from Blecha, 55, who once was one of the most powerful
figures in the Socialist Party.
   Blecha should have resigned all his offices when he quit as
interior minister on Jan. 19, Vranitzky told reporters.
   On Friday, the beleaguered politician stepped down as a
parliamentary deputy and deputy party chairman.
   His loss of parliamentary immunity means Blecha can be
prosecuted in connection with the so-called Lucona scandal. Austria
Press Agency quoted Blecha as saying he resigned so he can fight
the allegations.
   ``The decision had to be made,'' said Vranitzky, who in the past
year has forced the resignations of at least two senior party men
over financial irregularities.
   Blecha is accused of ordering police to stop investigating the
scandal, and of influencing witnesses to a parliamentary commission
looking into possible insurance fraud connected to the 1977 sinking
of the Lucona in the Indian Ocean. Six sailors died.
   Blecha denies aiding Udo Proksch, a fugitive who is the main
suspect in the sinking. Proksch is wanted on murder and fraud
charges.
   The Lucona's cargo was listed as materials for a uranium
processing plant and was insured for $16 million. The insurance
company claims the cargo was scrap metal. It refuses to pay.
   Leopold Gratz, another powerful Socialist Party official accused
of aiding Proksch, resigned as president of parliament Jan. 25.
Both men deny wrongdoing.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
