<DOCNO> AP890414-0180 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1741EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Zimbabwe     04-14 0424</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Zimbabwe,0438</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four More Top Politicians Quit in Corruption Scandal</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANGUS SHAW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Robert Mugabe announced Friday
the resignations of four more senior politicians linked to a
corruption scandal.
   ``I feel let down. But when we condemn them let us not forget
that everyone has a balance sheet, good and bad,'' Mugabe told a
news conference.
   ``I am still proud of them. All these men are good men, by and
large,'' he said of Higher Education Minister Dzingai Mutumbuka;
Industry and Technology Minister Callistus Ndlovu; Matabeleland
North Gov. Jacob Mudenda; and Charles Ndlovu, the deputy minister
of sport and culture.
   Their resignations brought to seven the number of politicians
who have quit over their involvement in purchasing cars and trucks
from the black market. Their involvement was exposed by police, the
press and a special judicial commission that Mugabe ordered to
investigate graft.
   The ministers and governor are accused of lying to Judge
President Wilson Sandura's commission, which on Thursday published
its report.
   Ndlovu recently was convicted of fraud and given a suspended
jail term of eight months.
   Mugabe said they had erred by overextending themselves
financially on homes, overdrafts and a ``high style of life.''
   ``It was abuse of privilege,'' said Mugabe, an avowed socialist.
``It amounted to conducting a racket in a process of speculation
and profiteering _ the evils of the capitalist system we still have.
   ``When revolutionaries go wrong they must be punished, perhaps
more so because they are revolutionaries,'' said the 65-year-old
leader who promised to transform this country into a socialist
state when it became independent from Britain nine years ago.
   Instead, critics say, most of his politicians have amassed vast
wealth in homes, farms and businesses while the bulk of the 9.2
million people remain largely impoverished.
   Those who resigned earlier are Defense Minister Enos Nkala;
Political Affairs Minister Frederick Shava; and Maurice Nyagumbo,
the most senior of the ministers and a stanch ally of Mugabe.
   Sandura's three-man commission accuses them of abusing their
power to avoid waiting lists lasting up to 10 years to buy cars and
trucks at low fixed prices and sell them on the black market for up
to five times more. Zimbabwe suffers a severe shortage of vehicles
because of a lack of hard currency.
   Police are considering prosecuting 15 senior officials,
including the ministers, for price control violations and perjury.
The black marketeering charges carry fines, and people convicted of
lying to a judge can be jailed for up to five years.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
