<FIRST>r w AM-US-India-Nepal     04-14 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-India-Nepal</SECOND>
<HEAD>With India-Nepal</HEAD>
<HEAD>State Department Urges Talks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States on Friday urged India and
Nepal to resolve their differences at the negotiating table and not
to endanger stability in the volatile region.
   ``We are urging both countries to begin meaningful talks and to
recognize that a quick and amicable resolution is in their own
interests and that of regional harmony and stability,'' said a
statement issued by the State Department.
   ``We have no comments on the relative merits of this bilateral
issue,'' said spokeswoman Margaret Tutwiler, reading the statement.
   India on Friday accused Nepal of violating a 39-year-old
friendship treaty and said it might have to review its relations
with its tiny, landlocked neighbor.
   Relations between the two countries soured earlier this year
after Nepal bought arms from China, which India views as an enemy.
In the latest development, India stopped trade with Nepal March 19
after the two countries' treaties on trade and transit expired.
   ``What is important is that Nepal and India decide what kind of
relationship these two sovereign and independent countries want
with one another and to make arrangements to facilitate talks in a
way which is least disruptive to those concerned,'' the department
said.
</TEXT>
