<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 2033EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Sweden-Disarmament     04-14 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sweden-Disarmament,0408</SECOND>
<HEAD>Palme Commission Disbands, Sees Expanded U.N. Role</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LARRY GERBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>STOCKHOLM, Sweden (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 14-nation commission Friday wrapped
up eight years of work on international disarmament, suggesting
expanded U.N. operations against terrorism, environmental disaster
and civil conflict.
   The Palme Commission, which included former U.S. Secretary of
State Cyrus Vance, Soviet Communist Party Central Committee member
Georgi Arbatov and Norwegian Prime Minister Gro Harlem Brundtland,
suggested the United Nations establish a peace fund to pay for its
new duties.
   The commission praised disarmament progress since the
organization's founding in 1980 and said international emphasis was
shifting from confrontation to cooperation.
   ``Up to the nuclear age, people thought you have to be strong to
survive. In the best possibility, you could beat your enemy,'' said
Egon Bahr, a member of West Germany's parliament.
   ``This is finished,'' said Bahr. ``We have not completely
succeeded, but we have gone along the way.''
   The independent Vienna-based commission, founded by the late
Swedish Prime Minister Olof Palme and others, in 1982 proposed the
idea of common security. It was one of the early proponents of a
European zone free of tactical nuclear weapons and a stronger
United Nations.
   It decided two years ago to disband, but to continue disarmament
work in smaller groups.
   A final statement blamed inadequate funding for hampering U.N.
operations in Namibia and threatening peace in the territory, which
gained independence from South Africa on April 1.
   It suggested a special $2 billion reserve fund be set up for
expanded peacekeeping work, paid by mandatory contributions from
all members.
   ``A world that spends the equivalent of nearly $1 trillion each
year to prepare for war should be able to afford the comparatively
small sums required for peacekeeping,'' the document said.
   It suggested U.N. forces be given roles in:
   _ Maritime peacekeeping, in situations such as the dangers to
shipping in the Persian Gulf stemming from the Iran-Iraq war.
   _ Anti-terrorist actions. David Owen, a former British foreign
secretary, said storming a hijacked aircraft or diverting a nuclear
terrorist threat were examples of how such a force could work,
especially in countries too small to have anti-terror units of
their own.
   _ Environmental cleanups in countries that do not have the
expertise to cope with disasters.
   _ Prolonged conflicts within a state, especially when
international relief efforts are threatened.
</TEXT>
