<DOCNO> AP890414-0183 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 2034EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Japan-China     04-14 0409</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-China,0421</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chinese Premier Says `Open-Door' Policy Firmly Rooted</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JANICE FUHRMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chinese Premier Li Peng wound up three days of
talks in Japan on Friday, saying China's open-door diplomatic and
economic policy is firmly in place and urging aggressive Japanese
investment in his country.
   Li denied rumors of serious disagreements between him and
Communist Party general secretary Zhao Ziyang about the pace of
economic and political reform in China.
   ``In terms of the general policy of promoting reform and an
`open-door policy,' we agree,'' he said at the Japan National Press
Club. ``The political situation today in China is stable.''
   During his visit, the first to Japan by a Chinese head of
government in seven years, Li met Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita,
Emperor Akihito and other political and business leaders.
   Earlier Friday, Li told businessmen not to let a recent economic
slowdown in China deter them from investing in his country, which
is experiencing severe inflation and cutbacks in public spending.
   Japanese capital and technology would complement China's vast
labor pool, land and natural resources, Li told about 300 business
leaders.
   Japan provides 80 percent of China's credit and is its second
largest trading partner after Hong Kong, but accounts for only 8
percent of total foreign investment there.
   In the diplomatic arena, Li said the Chino-Soviet summit next
month in Beijing will center on normalizing relations between the
two countries and should result in ``positive effects for peace in
China, Asia and the world as a whole.''
   During his meeting with the emperor on Thursday, Li said Akihito
expressed regret for the ``unfortunate history'' between the two
countries. More than 10 million Chinese died during Japan's 1937-45
invasion of the Chinese mainland.
   ``I responded that to recall history is to open up better
prospects for the future,'' Li said.
   China and Japan have been at odds about recent Japanese efforts
to evade responsibility for the war. After criticism by China and
other nations, Takeshita in February retracted a remark that only
future historians can judge whether Japan was an aggressor in the
war.
   During Li's visit, Japan announced it will lend China up to $734
million this fiscal year to help fund 11 projects including
expanding two ports and building a subway in Beijing.
   Li was accompanied by high-ranking government officials
including Foreign Minister Qian Qichen. He is to spend Saturday
sightseeing in western Japan and return Sunday to Beijing.
</TEXT>
