<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 2035EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Chad     04-14 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chad,0441</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chad Says Coup Foiled, Plotters Flee to Sudan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Chad reported a failed coup against President
Hissene Habre's government, and Sudan said the leaders, two
generals and the interior minister, escaped to the neighboring
country.
   A government statement releaased Thursday night through Chad's
embassy in France, the former colonial power in the North African
nation, said the plotters ``entered into rebellion against the
institutions of the republic'' on the night of April 1-2.
   It identified them as Hassan Djamous, armed forces commander;
Idriss Debi, his predecessor in the post, and Ibrahim Mahamat Itno,
the interior minister, characterizing all three as ``individuals
motivated and manipulated by overwhelming ambition.''
   The armed forces were ``ordered to destroy'' the plotters and
``put an end to the rebellion by annihilation,'' the statement said.
   When asked what happened to the three men, the Chadian Embassy
in Paris would say only that the plot was discovered and the
authors and their accomplices rendered harmless.
   A statement released Thursday night in Khartoum, capital of
Sudan, said Itno, Djamous and Debi crossed into Darfur province a
week ago. It was issued in the name of Tigani Sysi, governor of the
border province.
   Sudan's military command issued a statement saying Chadian
soldiers had intruded into Darfur and Sudanese soldiers were sent
to expel them. It did not give the number of intruders, but the
magazine Al-Adwaa said 2,000 Chadian soldiers crossed the border.
   Diplomatic sources in N'Djamena, capital of Chad, said April 5
that Itno was arrested and Djamous and Debi had disappeared. They
reported military movements in N'Djamena the weekend of April 1-3
and roadblocks around the city.
   In a report from N'Djamena, the French news agency Agence
France-Presse quoted sources it did not identify as saying Djamous
and Debi were wounded Tuesday in fighting with soldiers who pursued
them into Darfur province. It said Djamous was taken prisoner but
Debi escaped.
   Itno took a leading role in negotiations leading to Habre's
reconciliation with political oppponents who had fought a long
civil war. He also joined negotations that led to a 1987 agreement
with rebel leader Acheik ibn Omar, who was named foreign minister
earlier year.
   Chad became independent of France in 1960. Habre has been
president since 1982, when he ousted a Libyan-backed government led
by Goukouni Oueddei.
   Libya kept military forces in northern Chad and supported
factions opposed to Habre until a successful Chadian military
offensive in 1987.
   Col. Moammar Gadhafi, the Libyan leader, then recognized Habre's
government and agreed to a cease-fire, but there has not been a
permanent settlement.
</TEXT>
