<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 2036EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-Editors-Castro-Ortega     04-14 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Editors-Castro-Ortega,370</SECOND>
<HEAD>Editors Blocked From Hearing Castro, Ortega</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III defended
on Friday a decision to keep presidents Fidel Castro of Cuba and
Daniel Ortega of Nicaragua from speaking to the American Society of
Newspaper Editors.
   Baker said the government was exercising ``a certain amount of
discretion'' when it informed an invitation commitee that visas
would not be issued for the two Marxist leaders.
   ``I hope it's not the use of censorship,'' Baker said in
response to a question from James Squires, editor of the Chicago
Tribune who had sought clearance for Castro and Ortega to appear
before the convention in Washington.
   Baker said the United States could not have normal relations
with the two nations until U.S. leaders are convinced they observe
basic standards of human rights, have democratic procedures and do
not interfere in the affairs of neighboring countries.
   ``Once you start making exceptions you are on a very slippery
slope,'' he said.
   Vice President Dan Quayle, also appearing before the editors,
was asked to explain why Ortega was not allowed to come.
   ``You are not going to learn very much from (Ortega) coming up
here and responding to your questions and making promises,'' Quayle
said. ``What we will learn by, is going down and monitoring in
Nicaragua and seeing if you're going to have an electoral process
established that will allow fair, free elections.''
   ``You have the opportunity, clearly, to ask him questions in
Managua,'' Quayle said. ``But as far as coming up here, I really
don't think that it would be that beneficial.''
   The United States has strained relations with Nicaragua and no
relations with Cuba.
   Squires and other members of the editors group decided not to
invite Castro and Ortega to speak to the convention after they were
told by State Department officials the two leaders would not be
permitted to enter the country.
   After Baker's comments Friday, Margaret Tutwiler, the department
spokeswoman, cited a presidental proclamation and U.S. policy as
grounds ``to deny visas to senior officials of the Cuban
government, given ongoing Cuban support for external subversion and
internal repression.''
   She said she did not know why Ortega would not be eligible for a
U.S. visa.
</TEXT>
