<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 2036EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Peru     04-14 0357</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Peru,0369</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six Slain In Attacks; Villagers Chase off Rebels</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AYACUCHO, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peasants wielding pitchforks and clubs
chased off a band of Shining Path guerrillas, and violence across
the central highlands claimed six more lives, police said Friday.
   The killings pushed the insurgency death toll this week to 65.
Officials said nearly 800 people have died this year, making 1989
the bloodiest period in Peru's nine-year insurgency.
   Police said Shining Path guerrillas on Thursday killed Mayor
Hipolito Arancibia of Carhuamayo, a town in Junin state 190 miles
north of Ayacucho.
   Arrancibia, 48, was walking from the town council building to
his home nearby when three rebels, two women and a man, shot him to
death and fled, police said.
   Also Thursday, 40 guerrillas in Carhuapata, in Huancavelica
state 33 miles west of Ayacucho, executed the village's treasurer
and his wife after accusing them of mismanaging community funds,
police said.
   The attackers, who were led by a woman, dragged the couple to
the main plaza and forced villagers to witness the shootings,
police said.
   On Wednesday in the nearby hamlet of Paucarbamba, about 200
peasant farmers grabbed farm tools, clubs and knives and confronted
a dozen Shining Path insurgents who had ordered residents to listen
to a guerrilla lecture.
   Police said the rebels ran away and fired a few shots at their
pursuers, killing one man and wounding another.
   Twenty guerrillas leading 80 peasants attacked a police post
Wednesday in Cora Cora, a town in Ayacucho state about 120 miles
south of Ayacucho city, police said.
   Post defenders repelled the attack after five hours of fighting.
Police said two attackers were killed and two wounded.
   The Shining Path has been fighting since 1980 to topple Peru's
elected government and impose a worker-peasant state similar to the
China of Mao-Tse Tung.
   Analysts say the Shining Path draws its major strength from
highland Indian peasants, who see themselves as victims of
discrimination.
   In fighting reported earlier this week, military troops killed
34 Shining Path guerrillas in jungle clashes. Rebels killed 23
peasant farmers, one police officer and a political leader in
attacks throughout the central Andean highlands.
</TEXT>
