<FIRST>r a AM-Mayor-Contempt     04-14 0562</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Mayor-Contempt,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>East St. Louis Mayor Jailed for Contempt, Attorney Promises Quick
Release</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL DE LA GARZA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BELLEVILLE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An angry judge jailed the mayor and the
city attorney of East St. Louis for contempt Friday for failing to
appear at a court hearing on their city's leaking sewer system.
   Mayor Carl Officer and city attorney Eric Vickers were released
on $3,500 bond apiece after spending 1{ hours in the St. Clair
County Jail in Belleville, the county seat.
   Officer called the contempt order by St. Clair County Judge
Sheila O'Brien ``ridiculous.''
   ``What can I say, other than that she has confirmed her
incompetence?'' added Vickers after he was released.
   Earlier, the judge told Vickers she would file a complaint about
his conduct with state agencies in Illinois and Missouri, where
Vickers is licensed to practice law.
   After a bitter courtroom exchange with Vickers, the judge
ordered the city officials jailed for failure to appear at a March
31 hearing. The hearing had been called to discuss sewer problems
in their financially troubled city of 55,000 across the river from
St. Louis, Mo.
   Residents of East St. Louis' Villa Green housing project
complained after raw sewage leaked from a two-acre pond outside the
housing project. The judge ordered the city to drain the pond early
in March.
   Officer told the judge he was absent at the March 31 hearing on
the city's progress because he was ``suffering from the effects of
the flu.'' But he answered, ``I don't know,'' when asked where he
was over the next two days following the hearing.
   O'Brien then sentenced the two officials to six months in jail
for contempt.
   ``This is the most bizarre and outrageous situation I have ever
seen in a court of law,'' Vickers told O'Brien. ``It is obvious
this court has no sense of fairness and decency.''
   The judge responded sharply.
   ``Don't fight with me, Mr. Vickers,'' she said. ``You're picking
a fight you will not win.''
   Court bailiffs handcuffed Officer and Vickers together and led
them from the courtroom. As they walked out, the men lifted their
hands in a salute.
   Earlier, venting her anger over what she called East St. Louis'
``callous disregard'' for the court's orders, Ms. O'Brien
reinstated an order of March 3 that the city post a $500,000 bond
to guarantee its sewers be fixed in 90 days.
   The order also requires the city to pay the costs of the lawyers
who took the sewage system complaints to court.
   At the March 31 hearing, East St. Louis Public Works Director
Jesse Walker told O'Brien his employees were pumping sewage around
the clock to keep it from backing into the Villa Griffin pond, but
a shortage of machines and manpower was hindering progress.
   An that time, Sheila Shunick, a lawyer for tenants at the Villa
Griffin housing project, requested that the city show cause why it
should not be held in contempt and O'Brien granted her request.
   The judge has been holding hearings at two-week intervals on the
city's progress in stemming the free flow of sewage from leaking or
blocked pipes. The next hearing is set for June 9.
   Shunick acknowledged Friday that the city had made some progress
in repairing the sewers. Officer told the judge the city has spent
$15 million since 1979 on its the sewer system.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
