<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia-Vietnam     04-14 0187</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia-Vietnam,0195</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnam Asks Britain To Co-Chair Withdrawal Commission</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vietnam has asked Britain to be
co-chairman of an international commission to monitor the
withdrawal of Vietnamese troops from Cambodia, a British official
said Friday.
   Lord Glenarthur, minister for foreign and commonwealth affairs,
said the request was made during his visit to Hanoi on April 9-14.
   Glenarthur, the first British minister to visit Vietnam since
the communists won the war in April 1975, said he told Foreign
Minister Nguyen Co Thach his government would study the request.
   He added, however, that he felt the United Nations should head
the commission. U.N. peacekeepers usually are used to monitor
cease-fires and troop withdrawals.
   ``There are pitfalls in our taking part,'' he said without
elaboration at a news conference in Bangkok.
   Vietnam has occupied Cambodia since an invasion in December 1978.
   On April 5, the Vietnamese said they would withdraw by Sept. 30
and welcomed international monitoring.
   Hanoi recommended revival of a commission establioshed in 1954
Geneva agreements to supervise the pullout of French and communist
Vietnamese forces from Cambodia. Britain was co-chairman of the
commission.
</TEXT>
