<FIRST>r i AM-Iraq-Chaldeans     04-14 0161</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iraq-Chaldeans,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands of Chaldeans Mourn Mourn Patriarch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of Chaldean Catholics paid last
respects Friday to patriarch Mar Paul II Cheikho.
   Church officials said Mar Paul, 83, died Thursday while
conducting a service in the Mother of Sorrows, where his body lay
in state before burial beside his predecessors in the 400-year-old
church, Baghdad's oldest.
   In stifling hot weather, the Chaldean faithful filed past the
black-draped open coffin, many stooping to kiss the dead
patriarch's hand. Others bowed and made the sign of the cross.
   Mar Paul was spiritual leader of the Chaldean Catholics for 30
years.
   The Uniate Chaldean Church, affiliated with Rome but
semi-autonomous, has about 300,000 adherents and 18 archbishoprics
in Iraq, Iran, Syria, Lebanon, Turkey and the United States. About
half Iraq's Christians are Chaldeans.
   Chaldean archbishops elect their primate and a synod is expected
within 40 days to choose a new Patriarch of Babylon of the
Chaldeans, the full title.
