<FIRST>r w AM-ScientificFraud     04-14 0459</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Scientific Fraud,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gvt Urged to Probe Fraud</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARTON REPPERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government should get involved in
investigating suspected scientific fraud by university researchers
only after institutional procedures have been exhausted, the head
of an association representing 56 major U.S. research universities
said Friday.
   ``To hold open the threat of an office of government that can
march in at any time and take over an ongoing investigation is both
unnecessary and harmful,'' said Robert M. Rozensweig, president of
the Washington-based Association of American Universities.
   He said that as with government regulations on testing of human
subjects and animal research, ``the government can help to
encourage and buttress institutional responsibility.''
   ``It is essential that there be clear statements that reinforce
the primacy of the institution's role, and that there be equally
clear statements specifying the conditions under which the
government's authority will be invoked.
   ``In general, that ought to be only after the institution has
completed its work, or if the institutional processes are found to
be defective, or if the institution itself asks for help,''
Rozensweig told a conference sponsored by the American Association
for the Advancement of Science.
   Rep. John D. Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House Energy and
Commerce Committee, is planning to introduce legislation that would
set up a special federal office to oversee the integrity of
research activities.
   In addition, an Institute of Medicine panel recently proposed a
series of recommendations to the National Institutes of Health to
help deal with the problem of fraud and misconduct in biomedical
research.
   Paul J. Friedman, a member of the medical panel, told the
conference that the group urged ``lessening of the competitive
pressures that encourage abuses of good research and authorship
practices.''
   ``Institutions were asked to give serious consideration to
proposals to limit the number of publications reviewed for
advancement; instead of stressing productivity, institutions would
really concentrate on determining the quality of a small number of
papers,'' he said.
   Friedman, associate dean of the School of Medicine of the
University of California at San Diego, said the panel recommended
that by 1992 institutions receiving federal research funds be
required to develop ``appropriate scientific and ethical
standards.''
   He noted there have been proposals by congressional committees
and the inspector general of the Department of Health and Human
Services to conduct data audits on randomly selected scientific
research experiments.
   But Friedman said the Institute of Medicine panel ``came out
squarely against this idea, regarding it as not likely to catch any
determined cheaters, but very likely to lead to interminable
arguments about the selection and interpretation of research data.''
   ``It would inevitably be extremely costly in professional time
and would pit a new investigative bureaucracy against the
scientific community,'' he said.
</TEXT>
