<DOCNO> AP890414-0196 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 2049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-FactoryUse     04-14 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Factory Use,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>Factory Operating Rate Slips for Second Month as Economy Slows</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The operating rate at the nation's factories,
mines and utilities declined in March for the second consecutive
month, the government said Friday in a report read as a sign that
inflationary pressures are easing.
   The Federal Reserve Board said U.S. industry used 84 percent of
its capacity last month, down from 84.2 percent in February and
84.4 percent in January.
   It was the first back-to-back decline in the operating rate
since August-September 1986.
   ``I think this is unambiguous confirmation that the economy is
slowing due to high interest rates, a slowdown in trade improvement
and some tapering off of the capital (investment) boom,'' said
economist Jerry Jasinowski of the National Association of
Manufacturers.
   The closer factories get to full capacity, the greater the fear
they will have trouble producing enough goods to meet demand,
leading to shortages and price increases. Economists consider an
operating rate of 85 percent as a clear sign that inflation will
accelerate.
   This report ``will help to alleviate the inflationary pressures
that come from bottlenecks and shortages and excess demand. It will
certainly take some pressure off,'' said economist Cynthia Latta of
Data Resources Inc., a Lexington, Mass., forecasting firm.
   Stock and bond prices rose sharply in early trading after the
release of the report and another by the Labor Department which
said wholesale prices in March had risen at a moderate 0.4 percent
rate.
   In a related report indicating sluggishness, the Federal Reserve
said the pace of industrial production was flat for the second
month in a row in March, leaving its industrial production index at
141 percent of its 1977 base, 4.6 percent higher than a year ago.
   Jasinowski said that although the central bank's reports showed
the economy slowing, they did not yet presage a recession.
   Production dipped 0.1 percent at manufacturing plants after an
identical rise a month earlier. Output at mines and oil wells rose
0.5 percent after a sharp 1.5 percent decline a month earlier.
Production at utilities dropped 0.5 percent after a large 2.3
percent jump in February.
   The output of automobiles and light trucks fell in March to an
annual rate of 7.1 million units, down from 7.2 million a month
earlier. However, output of business equipment and construction
supplies rose.
   The operating rate at manufacturing plants dipped to 84.4
percent last month, from 84.7 percent in February and 84.9 percent
in January.
   The rate at factories producing durable goods, ``big ticket''
items expected to last three or more years, fell to 83 percent,
from 83.3 percent, reflecting declines in fabricated metal products
and automobiles and parts. It was the third consecutive decline at
auto plants, to 82.4 percent in March. The auto industry has been
hit with slow sales this year.
   At plants manufacturing non-durable goods, the rate slipped from
86.6 percent to 86.3 percent last month.
   In the mining sector, which includes oil and gas drilling, the
operating rate rose from 81.2 percent to 81.6 percent. At
utilities, the rate fell from 82.3 percent to 81.8 percent.
</TEXT>
