<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Scandal 1stLd-Writethru   04-14 0485</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Scandal, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0751,0497</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politician Admits Wife Received Funds From from Recruit Co.</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: CORRECTS day in lead.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TETSUO JIMBO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The secretary-general of Japan's governing party
acknowledged Friday that his wife was paid about $60,000 in
consulting fees from Recruit Co., the firm at the center of a
bribery scandal shaking the government.
   Shintaro Abe also told a news conference: ``I put my secretary
entirely in charge of my fund-raising affairs, and neither my wife
nor myself knew anything about it. But I have found such a deal
took place and I admit it was a result of my ignorance.''
   He confirmed news reports that Recruit Co., a publishing
conglomerate, paid his wife Yoko about $2,300 monthly as a
consulting fee from February 1986 to August 1988. He said the money
was deposited into a bank account of his secretary, who has been
sick and hospitalized.
   Abe, secretary-general of the Liberal Democratic Party, is
considered Japan's most powerful poltician after Prime Minister
Noboru Takeshita.
   Abe was foreign minister at the time the consulting fee was paid
by Recruit.
   On Tuesday, Takeshita told Parliament that from 1985 to 1987 his
political support groups had received $1 million from Recruit and
its subsidiaries, with the money coming in the form of donations
and purchases of party fund-raising tickets.
   Takeshita was at that time the Liberal Democrats'
secretary-general.
   About 17 politicians and 150 other influential people are known
to have bought at discount prices hundreds of thousands of unlisted
shares in a subsidiary of Recruit and then received substantial
profits when the share price soared after trading began. Takeshita
has denied any personal involvement. Such stock transactions are
not considered illegal.
   But opposition leaders say Recuit also paid millions to
influential people as political contributions and expected favors
in return.
   Fourteen people, including two former vice ministers and an
ex-chairman of Nippon Telegraph and Telephone Corp. have been
arrested on charges of bribery and securities law violations in
connection with the affair. Former Finance Minister Kiichi Miyazawa
and and two other Cabinet members resigned after being linked to
the scandal.
   Abe's disclosures Friday contradicted a declaration by the
Liberal Democratic Party earlier this year that no members of the
current Takeshita administration received donations from Recruit
after last summer.
   Opposition parties increased their criticism.
   ``How can he (Abe) not know about the deposits?'' said Yukihisa
Yoshida of the Democratic Socialist Party. ``It is extremely
serious that he was receiving money even after the Recruit scandal
surfaced.''
   Shun Ohide, a leader of the Socialist Party, Japan's largest
opposition group, said: ``Abe has been reported to be closely
linked to Recruit, and I think it (Friday's revelation) was only
part of it. After all these revelations, the Liberal Democratic
Party should resign.''
   Takeshita has refused calls for his resignation, vowing to carry
out political reforms and restore public trust in his
administration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
