<FIRST>r i AM-UN-Mozambique     04-14 0261</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UN-Mozambique,0268</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mozmbique Says Rebels Receive Aid from Inside South Africa</HEAD>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mozambique's premier said Friday the
rebels fighting his Marxist government receive aid from within
South Africa, but did not accuse the South African government of
providing it.
   Mario de Graca Machungo said the Mozambique National Resistance,
known by the acronym Renamo, has killed more than 100,000 people
and caused $6 billion in damage.
   ``We know that most of their aid comes from inside South
Africa,'' he said. ``We are not sure whether South Africa serves as
a source or a transit point.''
   South Africa and Mozambique agreed in 1984 not to support rebels
fighting each other's governments. Mozambique closed African
National Congress bases on its territory and South Africa pledged
to stop supporting Renamo.
   Government officials and private agencies held a pledging
conference Friday with a goal of $382 million in money and goods
for Mozambique's emergency needs in 1989-90. U.N. spokesman Salim
Lone reported more than $350 million in pledges.
   A report prepared by the United Nations and Mozambique asked for
more than $237 million in emergency food aid as the most pressing
requirement.
   In Maputo, capital of Mozambique, the official news agency AIM
said two Renamo guerrillas who surrendered said the rebels received
weapons from South Africa last year. One was quoted as saying South
African planes delivered arms to central Mozambique.
   The AIM report did not say whether the planes and supplies were
from the South African military or private sources. It identified
the former guerrillas as Diogo Toni and Wiriam Erton.
</TEXT>
