<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 2052EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ChristianScienceTrial     04-14 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Christian Science Trial,0404</SECOND>
<HEAD>Prosecution Rests; Trial Resumes Monday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SARASOTA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A judge blocked prosecutors Friday from
presenting key testimony in the trial of a Christian Science couple
charged with murder for allowing their young daughter to die of
diabetes without treatment.
   Former banker William Hermanson, 42, and his wife Christine, 38,
are charged with third-degree murder and felony child abuse in the
Sept. 30, 1986, death of 7-year-old Amy. The couple sought the aid
of spiritual healers but not doctors.
   Defense attorneys successfully blocked the testimony of a family
friend who said out of the jury's presence that Amy's parents
obtained medical care for themselves but didn't get Amy the insulin
injections that could have saved her.
   Attorney Charles Arnold said the surprise testimony Thursday
violated state rules of discovery requiring lawyers to notify the
other side of damaging testimony expected to be introduced.
   The state acknowledged its inaction but gave no explanation, and
Circuit Judge Stephen Dakan ruled that the testimony was
inadmissible. Dakan dismissed the six-member jury until Monday when
the defense will present its case.
   The judge reserved a ruling on a defense motion for an acquittal
on grounds that the state had failed to prove anything other than
that the couple were practicing their religion.
   Christian Science doctrine relies on prayer and spiritual
practioners rather than medicine to heal illness. There are no
sanctions, however, for followers who seek medical aid.
   At issue, the defense maintained, is religious freedom.
   The Hermansons' defense rests on a 1975 Florida law that
protects parents who withhold medical treatment from their sick
children if the parents are ``legitimately practicing'' their
religious beliefs.
   Assistant State Attorney Deno Economou, however, insisted the
Hermansons knowingly let their daughter die.
   In the disputed testimony, family friend Mary Christman said she
visited the Hermansons three days after Amy's death and learned
Hermanson once had taken Novocain for a tooth problem.
   His wife suggested she had anesthesia during childbirth, Mrs.
Christman testified.
   ``I said, `God, Chris, if Bill had Novocain and you had two
Caesarean sections .. how could you have done that without any
anesthetic?''' Mrs. Christman told the judge and attorneys.
   Mrs. Hermanson replied, ``Well, that was a different
situation,'' the friend said.
   Mrs. Hermanson also contended Amy's body would have rejected
insulin because her husband's body rejected Novocain, Mrs.
Christman testified.
</TEXT>
