<FIRST>u a AM-ShootingSpreeTrial 1stLd-Writethru a0743 04-14 0507</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shooting Spree Trial, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0743,0514</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who Killed Four While Deputies Watched Is Ruled Insane, Acquitted</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to recast lead; CORRECT spelling of judge's
name to Beaty, sted Beatty; UPDATE with more family reax. Picks up 7th
graf, `Nick Nicholson...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL NOWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   WINSTON-SALEM, N.C. (AP) _ A jury ruled Friday that a
25-year-old man was insane when he shot four people to death in
their cars and wounded five others while sheriff's deputies watched
and waited for orders from superiors.
   Michael Charles Hayes, 25, a former moped shop operator from
Davidson County, was found innocent on four counts of first-degree
murder and eight counts of assault in the July 17 shooting rampage.
   The verdict from the Forsyth County jury was announced after 14
hours of deliberations over four days.
   Superior Court Judge James Beaty ordered that Hayes be taken
into custody and brought to the John Umstead Hospital in Butner,
where he will undergo psychiatric treatment before a hearing.
   ``The court finds reasonable grounds that Michael Charles Hayes
would probably be dangerous to himself and to others,'' Beaty said
before sending him to the hospital. ``There's a substantial risk
that he would commit bodily harm to others.''
   Hayes put his hand on his forehead and cried when the verdict
was read in the half-filled courtroom. Family members of victims
and some of the survivors also sobbed. Others reacted with anger.
   ``There wasn't one crazy person in there. There were 13, and you
know who the other 12 are,'' said Gary Hull, brother of Ron Hull,
who was killed in the shooting spree.
   Nick Nicholson, father of one of the dead, Thomas Nicholson,
said the families of the victims were shocked by the verdict. ``I
have no idea why they went the way they did,'' he said.
   After the shooting spree, county sheriff's deputies were
criticized for waiting for permission to shoot Hayes as he
brandished a .22-caliber rifle, ranting and flagging down cars.
Dispatchers were criticized for telling deputies to ``stand by.''
   All the victims, people making their way home on a well-traveled
road at the end of the day, were shot at close range before
deputies finally wounded Hayes in a hail of gunfire.
   On the day before the rampage, Hayes' family had tried to have
him committed to a mental hospital.
   ``This is the only verdict that should have been delivered in
this case. Any other would have required that the jury did not
follow the letter of the law,'' defense attorney Mike Grace said.
   Prosecutor Warren Sparrow said the case was difficult,
particularly because the state's lone psychiatrist supported the
defense argument that Hayes was insane at the time of the shootings.
   ``We presented our evidence in the best light. The jury has
spoken. We accept the verdict,'' Sparrow said in a statement.
   Selwyn Rose, a private psychiatrist hired by the defense,
testified earlier this week that Hayes believed he was part of
``God's army'' on a mission to destroy demons.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
