<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--Nigeria-Births     04-14 0154</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Nigeria-Births,0158</SECOND>
<HEAD>Appeals To Families To Have Only Four Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAGOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Ibrahim Babangida appealed to
Nigerians Friday to observe a government recommendation that
families have only four children, but he said no force would be
used to limit births.
   The West African nation's population is estimated at 114 million
with an annual growth rate of 3.3 percent. The present average is
six children per family.
   ``Let me stress that the policy is not a coercive measure, and
as such no special legal provisions for its enforcement have been
made,'' Babangida said.
   But he added: ``If women space their child bearing at intervals
of two or three years, or they decide not to give birth after 35,
then they would probably bear not more than four children.''
   Health Minister Olikoye Ransome-Kuti has said Nigeria seeks to
reduce the growth rate to 2.5 percent in 1995 and 2 percent in 2000.
</TEXT>
