<FIRST>r i AM-HongKong-Vietnamese     04-14 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hong Kong-Vietnamese,0229</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Delegation Arrives To Repatriate More Boat People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vietnamese delegation arrived in Hong Kong
Friday to arrange for the repatriation of 58 Vietnamese boat people
who want to return home.
   The four-member team is to interview and issue travel documents
to the returnees, government spokesman Akber Khan said.
   Last month 75 Vietnamese who fled their homeland and came to
this British colony voluntarily returned to Vietnam in the first
major repatriation of boat people in Hong Kong.
   Those and the members of the new group are among about 12,000
Vietnamese who arrived in the colony after the Hong Kong government
introduced a tough new policy last June. The policy regards those
refugees who arrived after June as illegal immigrants unless they
can prove they fled Vietnam because of persecution.
   More than 26,000 Vietnamese are now in Hong Kong, including more
than 2,000 who arrived this year. Vietnamese and Vietnamese of
Chinese descent are continuing to flee Vietnam, but the biggest
exodus occurred within months after communist forces defeated the
U.S.-backed South Vietnamese government in the spring of 1975.
   Vietnam and the U.N. Office of High Commissioner for Refugees
signed an agreement last year for the voluntary return of refugees,
with Vietnam promising the returnees would not be mistreated and
the United Nations to provide reintegration assistance.
</TEXT>
