<HEAD>Bush Picks Harlow for Treasury Post</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: adds 3 more appointments at end</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush announced Friday his selection
of Bryce L. Harlow, a White House aide since 1986, to be assistant
secretary of the Treasury for legislative affairs.
   Harlow, currently special assistant to the president for
legislative affairs, is a former associate director for the Office
of Management and Budget and a one-time aide to former Sen. Howard
H. Baker, R-Tenn.
   If confired by the Senate, he would succeed John K. Meagher, who
holds the post of deputy undersecretary of the Treasury for
legislative affairs. Bush said he would nominate Harlow first for
the deputy undersecretary's job, then promote him immediately to
the higher-ranking assistant secretary's post.
   In other personnel announcements, Bush said he would nominate:
   _Thomas D. Larson, a faculty member at Pennsylvania State
University and former Pennsylvania state transportation secretary,
to be administrator of the Federal Highway Administration. He would
succeed Robert Earl Farris.
   _David George Ball, an executive with Amex Inc. in Greenwich,
Conn., to be assistant secretary of Labor for pension and welfare
benefits. He would succeed David M. Walker.
   _Paul Dundes Wolfowitz, currently U.S. ambassador to Indonesia,
to be undersecretary of Defense for policy. He would succeed Fred
Charles Ikle.
   _Brian W. Clymer, currently the vice chairman of the
Southeastern Pennsylvania Transportation Authority, to be urban
mass transit administrator at the Department of Transportation. He
would succeed Alfred A. DelliBovi.
   _Joseph G. Schiff to be assistant secretary of Housing and Urban
Development for public and Indian housing, succeeding J. Michael
Dorsey. Since 1985, Schiff has been manager of the Louisville
office of HUD.
   _Jacqueline Knox Brown to be an assistant secretary of energy
for congressional and intergovernmental affairs, replacing C. Anson
Franklin. She most recently served as a senior policy analyst with
the Commission on Executive, Legislative and Judicial Salaries.
   _Frank Young to remain as head of the Food and Drug
Administration at the Department of Health and Human Services.
Young has served as commissioner of the Food and Drug
Administration since July 1984.
