<FIRST>r w AM-ASNE-NewspaperAds 1stld-writethru a0773 04-14 0664</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ASNE-Newspaper Ads, 1st ld-writethru, a0773, 640</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS spelling of Procter &amp; Gamble throughout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pulitzer prizes don't impress national
advertisers, but four-color graphics and younger readers do,
newspaper editors were told Friday by ad executives who said
editors must show that newspapers are not dinosaurs but are a
``hot, visible'' advertising medium.
   Newspapers must spruce up their images and use innovative ad
campaigns if they want take ad dollars away from television and
magazines, the executives told a session of the American Society of
Newspaper Editors convention.
   Robert Wehling, vice president marketing services at the
nation's second largest advertiser, Procter &amp; Gamble, said surveys
show that newspaper readers tend to be over 40, whereas advertisers
want to reach under-40 audiences.
   Magazines, he said, have better four-color printing capability
and magazines tend to be read more than once. Newspapers, he said,
get thrown out with the next day's trash.
   Newspapers also are cluttered and their ads don't show products
being used as well as television does, Wehling said.
   Most national advertisers ``see a significant cost
disadvantage'' in using newspapers when compared with television
and magazines, he said.
   ``There is simply no compelling reason for national advertisers
to redirect dollars to the newspaper medium,'' Wehling said.
   Newspapers could help themselves by emphasizing regional ad
campaigns, by giving advertisers better positions and by trying to
link local and national advertising campaigns, Wehling said.
   He said one bright star for national newspaper advertising has
been USA Today, where Procter &amp; Gamble's ads have increased for the
past three years and will continue to do so.
   Marianne Caponnnetto, senior vice president and media director
at Lord, Geller, Einstein, O'Neill and Partners in New York, said
USA Today sales people were ``extremely aggressive.''
   But that was the exception, she said, adding that even though
her jobs have included placing $50 million a year in ads for the
International Business Machines Corp., she could ``count on one
hand'' the number of newspaper sales executives she's ever met.
   Advertisers perceive newspaper sales personnel as ``order
takers,'' ``dull,'' not creative and ``just looking to sell
space,'' she said.
   Part of the problem is that young ad agency executives are
products of the TV age. They don't read newspapers as much, they
want exciting ad campaigns, and they don't want to expend their
energies on quarter-page newspaper ads.
   She also pointed out that a majority of Americans no longer get
most of their news from newspapers.
   Advertisers, she said, ``are indifferent to Pulitzer prizes.''
   Newspapers need to target special segments of their audiences _
geographically and demograghically, she said.
   ``Added value'' approaches such as joint promotions, research,
cross-media programs and merchandising are being used by magazines
``to protect their rate cards.''
   ``All of your major competitors are adapting to the requirement
of mixed marketing. It is time for you to do the same,'' she said.
   She said newspapers have ``the potential to launch a strong and
unified strategy that could open up significant opportunities for
sustained growth.''
   It also is time for editors to take more aggressive roles, she
said, and convince advertising craftsman ``that newspapers are a
hot, visible medium.''
   ``While you can't take the show biz away from TV, you can make
newspapers more appealing by demonstrating the inroads made in
areas like reproduction in four-color, by making newspapers more
profitable for agencies by standardizing contracts, invoices, rate
structures and by being more flexible with new positioning and
layout ideas,'' she said.
   She urged editors to ``Support your ad sales efforts to entice
new and repeat business with special incentives. Be innovative. ...
   ``The church and the state must work together to ensure the
preservation of the species. That doesn't mean that anyone's
integrity must be compromised. But in a fierce survival battle
you've got to operate as a team and understand one another's
business. The best way to protect your credibility and integrity is
to secure a sound business future.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890414-0208 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 2130EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-ASNE-NewspaperMergers     04-14 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ASNE-Newspaper Mergers,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Defend Media Consolidation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<HEAD>Associated Press Writer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Executives of three of the nation's largest
newspaper chains said consolidation in the newspaper business isn't
necessarily bad and that it may help protect the industry from
hostile takeovers by the ``apostles of greed.''
   The presidents of Knight-Ridder Inc., Times-Mirror and Gannett
Co. Inc. addressed the issue of public versus private ownership of
newspapers in a session of the American Society of Newspaper
Editors convention.
   They said that although those running publicly owned newspapers
have to pay attention to the stockholders, the financial bottom
line wasn't management's only consideration.
   ``We have a fine line to walk,'' Knight-Ridder President James
Batten said. ``We've got very solemn responsibilities to our
shareholders because, finally, it's their money.''
   Times Mirror President David Laventhol said ``There's no
question that we have to have some sense of responsibility to our
shareholders and investors.''
   But, he said, ``The idea that new owners come in and the first
thing they do is cut the editorial budget I would say is not a
realistic view of what has happened to newspapers in this country
that have been taken over by public owners. ...
   ``The biggest impact that public ownership has probably had on
newspapers ... is the ability of newspapers to invest much more
extensively than in most cases they would ever do under private
ownership,'' Laventhol said.
   He said Times Mirror ``agonized'' over the sales of the Dallas
Times-Herald and the Denver Post, but he said there have been large
increases in editorial staffs at the newspapers that have been
acquired by Times-Mirror.
   ``In many instances, despite all the rhetoric and clear pressure
on profits ... there is another part of the newspaper business,
which is news and information to make this a better world. And I
think even in our giant public companies of the people sitting up
here I think that's still a very primary motivation,'' Laventhol
said.
   Gannett President John Curley said the takeover ``threat'' was
not from ``not the major players'' in the business but from
``people who are looking toward getting in deeper in the media
business.''
   He said there also were ``apostles of greed'' who will try to
break up big companies and sell off their assets to pay the ``junk
bond'' deals that increasingly are financing large mergers.
   The entrepreneuers, however, ``overlook the fact that once you
sell some of the assets of some company ... there wouldn't be
enough left to meet their Drexel Burnham bills,'' Curley said.
   Curley said there was too much emphasis on increasing profit
margins to service debt from acquisitions.
   ``In running the paper you ought to focus on ... the advertising
side, what the market can do realistically, and then not try to
penalize the news side if it can't be done at a level that, let's
say, they can do in the Sun Belt,'' Curley said.
   ``On the other hand, I think we've got to be realistic that some
markets aren't ever going to grow and editors can't expect to add
10 to 15 percent editorial costs annually just to do nice things
when they're not ever going to see that growth,'' Curly said.
   Laventhol said the news media will be takeover targets as long
financing is available.
   ``I don't think it's going to go away, but in a way many
newspaper companies have gotten themselves in stronger position now
to fight that kind of thing than, say, they were four or five years
ago,'' Laventhol said.
   Batten noted entertainment mogul Burt Sugarman's failed attempt
to acquire Media General and rumors that the Bass brothers of Texas
were ``moving around'' Tribune stock.
   ``There are a lot of straws in the wind that are worrisome,''
Batten said.
   Laventhol noted, however, that new owners ``are keeping
newspapers alive. ... And I don't know if that's a terrible thing.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
