<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0288</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rainshowers Water the Lower Mississippi Valley</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Numerous rainshowers and isolated thunderstorms spread across
the lower Mississippi Valley on Friday, ranging from eastern Texas
to the Ohio Valley, and bringing heavy downpours to southwestern
Louisiana.
   Thunderstorms at Lake Charles, La., dumped more than 1\ inches
of rain and threatened flooding in the low-lying areas.
   Rainshowers spread from eastern Texas into the lower Ohio
Valley, with many locations reporting less than a quarter-inch of
rainfall.
   A cold front curved from the Great Lakes into the central Plains
and central Rockies. Rainshowers were widely scattered from Lower
Michigan into southern Iowa.
   A cold front off the Pacific Northwest coast spread cloudiness
across the area.
   The low in the nation this morning was 13 degrees at Gunnison,
Colo.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 37
degrees at Iron Mountain and Thief River Falls, Minn., to 90
degrees at Blythe, Calif., and Phoenix.
   The national weather forecast for Saturday, showers will be
widespread from New England through the upper Ohio Valley into the
mid-Atlantic states. Showers and thunderstorms will occur from the
eastern Tennessee Valley through the southern Atlantic states into
the central and much of Florida. The remainder of the nation will
have pleasant weather, except the Pacific Northwest where scattered
showers are expected.
   High temperatures will be in the 60s or 70s across much of the
nation; in the 50s from the Great Lakes into the northern Atlantic
states; in the 80s over much of Florida, the southern tip of Texas,
and from interior parts of California into the southern Plateau;
and in the 90s across the desert Southwest.
</TEXT>
