<FIRST>r a AM-Hoffman     04-14 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hoffman,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hoffman Autopsy Inconclusive, Toxicology Tests Awaited</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DOYLESTOWN, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Abbie Hoffman was taking prescription
drugs when he died and toxicology tests should reveal whether the
medicine killed him, the Bucks County coroner said Friday.
   Dr. Thomas Rosco refused to identify the medicine Hoffman was
taking. Asked if it was a potentially lethal drug, Rosco said,
``There are lots of drugs taken in high enough doses that can kill
you. That's what we're looking for.''
   Hoffman, 52, was found dead Wednesday in his rural New Hope
apartment. An autopsy Thursday night was inconclusive.
   ``When an autopsy is inconclusive, lots of times drugs or toxins
are a factor,'' Rosco said.
   ``What I have ruled out is homicide,'' Rosco said. ``The other
manners of death are natural causes, suicide or accidental and all
three of those are still being considered.''
   The toxicology tests won't be ready until the middle of next
week, he said.
   Rosco said he had no indication Hoffman had committed suicide,
as has been suggested by friends and family of the Yippie movement
founder.
   In an interview with The Associated Press on Friday, Florence
Hoffman, Abbie's 83-year-old mother, said she thought suicide had
been ruled out.
   Mrs. Hoffman said her son had sounded depressed in recent
conversations with his brother, Jack. But the brother told
reporters that on Monday, when they last spoke, Hoffman ``seemed
all right, he seemed good.''.
   ``He's got a lot of battlescars on him,'' said Jack Hoffman.
``He's been arrested 55 times. You somewhat do get a little
disenchanted, but I don't think he got tired out. If Abbie had one
ounce of strength left in him, he'd go out and picket.''
   Ilya Hoffman, 26, and Andrew Hoffman, 28, two of the activist's
three children, said they did not believe their father commited
suicide. Andrew Hoffman, who lives in Boston along with his sister,
said he had spoken to his father on the phone a week ago.
   ``He was very happy and he wanted us to come down and visit,''
he said.
</TEXT>
