<FIRST>r a AM-Jabril     04-14 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Jabril,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Jabril Says His Group Did Not Plant Bomb On Pan Am 103</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ahmed Jabril, leader of a group suspected of
bombing Pan Am Flight 103, denies that his organization had any
role in the attack that killed 270 people in December.
   While denying any connection with the bombing, Jabril
acknowledged that his group routinely used the same kind of bomb
investigators say was used to blow up the Pan Am jumbo jet.
   A total of 259 people on the plane and 11 people on the ground
perished when the bomb blew the aircraft out of the skies over
Lockerbie, Scotland.
   In an interview broadcast Friday, Jabril told ABC-News that his
first lieutenant, Hafez Dalkamoni, commonly built and used the type
of explosive device that downed the Pan Am flight.
   Dalkamoni is in jail in Germany after a police raid last October
that netted weapons and three bomb devices like the one used to
blow up Flight 103.
   Jabril insisted that his group, the Syrian-sponsored Popular
Front for the Liberation of Palestine-General Command, did not
plant the bomb on the airliner.
   Jabril also denied that his group receives money from Iran but
said he shared Iran's outrage at how the United States last year
shot down an Iran civilian passenger plane.
   ``I see now that the incident of the Pan Am is neither worse nor
uglier than the destruction of the Iranian air bus,'' Jabril told
ABC. ``Both of them are crimes against civilians whether by the
U.S. administration or by terrorist groups who may have blown up
the Pan Am. They are equally barbaric.''
   While denying his group's involvement, Jabril issued a warning
should the United States or Israel strike his camps in Syria. ``We
shall not remain still. Our response shall be equal if not more
violent,'' he said.
   Despite Jabril's denials, investigators suspect that his group
planted the bomb on an unwitting Pan Am passenger at the behest of
Iran.
   And although he said the barometer type bombs were used only in
the Middle East, German police found three Toshiba radio-cassette
players similar to the one used to blow up Flight 103 when they
arrested Dalkamoni last October.
</TEXT>
