<FIRST>u a AM-Court-Smoker 1stLd-Writethru a0779 04-14 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Court-Smoker, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0779,0552</SECOND>
<HEAD>Supreme Court Reinstates Part Of Smoker's Suit Against R.J. Reynolds</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 2 grafs after 4th graf, `Cigarette companies ..., with
Reynolds comment. Pick up 5th graf, `John Forster ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA WILKINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ST. PAUL, Minn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Warning labels on cigarette packs do not
give tobacco companies blanket immunity from lawsuits by victims of
lung cancer and other smoking-related ailments, the Minnesota
Supreme Court ruled Friday.
   The ruling required a lower court to reconsider a lawsuit by the
wife of a man who died of cancer four years ago after smoking
filterless Camel cigarettes for 30 years.
   Most lawsuits against tobacco companies have been dismissed
before going to trial. Michael Weiner, an attorney for plaintiff
Ann Forster, called the decision against R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co.,
maker of Camels, a major victory.
   Cigarette companies have been putting warning labels on their
products since the 1965 Cigarette Labeling and Advertising Act, but
Reynolds ``set out to do everything it could to show that that
(warning) label is not true,'' Weiner said in arguing the case Feb.
8.
   Jim Fyock, a Reynolds spokesman in Winston-Salem, N.C., said the
court had upheld the adequacy of the warnings, and said he was
confident the remaining points raised by the Forsters would be
rejected at trial.
   ``When the case is returned to the trial court, a central
element of the proceedings will be the established adequacy of
federally mandated warnings as a matter of law,'' Fyock said.
   John Forster, a businessman who died at age 46 in June 1985,
sued a few months before his death.
   He testifed that he began smoking partly because advertisements
suggested that it was a grown-up, manly thing to do. During the
1950s, cigarette companies advertised the so-called health benefits
of smoking.
   Forster said he had been able to overcome a drinking problem,
but could never quit the highly addictive leaf, despite hypnosis
and acupuncture treatment.
   Weiner said that even after warnings appeared on cigarette
packs, Forster continued relying on claims by the tobacco industry
that cigarettes were safe.
   John Strauch, a lawyer representing Reynolds, had argued that
Congress created the Federal Trade Commission to regulate cigarette
advertising, and that it had not intended individual courts and
juries to do it.
   But legal consideration of the case does not conflict with FTC
regulation ``so long as plaintiff does not claim the advertising
was deceptive because it did not adequately warn,'' Associate
Justice John Simonett wrote in the opinion.
   Weiner said Thursday that the court's ruling leaves most of his
case intact.
   Although the ruling states that Reynolds' warning is adequate,
it ``permits us to say what (Reynolds) did do is misleading, and
that's the major thrust of the case,'' Weiner said.
   The state of Minnesota, American Cancer Society, American Lung
Association, American Public Health Association and Minnesota Trial
Lawyer's Association joined his wife's case as friends-of-the-court.
   Forster's suit was dismissed in 1987 by Hennepin County District
Judge Jonathan Lebedoff, who ruled that the federal law preempted
such claims.
   Last year, the state Court of Appeals reversed Lebedoff and
ordered a trial, saying it could not ``immunize the tobacco
industry'' from lawsuits. Reynolds had appealed that ruling to the
Supreme Court.
</TEXT>
