<FIRST>u a AM-KnievelJump     04-14 0482</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Knievel Jump,0499</SECOND>
<HEAD>Daredevil Knievel Soars In His Father's Trajectory</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM DAHLBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Sports Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robbie Knievel soared easily over the Caesars
Palace fountains Friday night, safely finishing the same motorcycle
jump that nearly killed his daredevil father 22 years ago.
   Thousands of people who jammed the front of the resort cheered
as Knievel jumped his red motorcycle over the fountains and made a
perfect landing on a ramp about 180 feet from his takeoff point.
   The motorcycle landed at some 70 mph and he managed to avoid a
nearby concrete pillar and stop the bike before hitting a wall in
an underground parking garage less than the length of a football
field away.
   Knievel triumphantly rode out of the garage and back up the
landing ramp, where his father, Evel Knievel, ran out to hug him.
   ``That was for you dad, I love you,'' Knievel said to his
father, who spent 30 days in a coma after missing the same leap in
1967.
   Knievel landed just short of a huge white X on the 14-foot-wide
landing ramp and kept his hands on his handlebars as he soared over
the fountains.
   ``I thought I was going to land short like my dad and have to
deal with that,'' the daredevil said. ``I wanted to do it with no
hands but I held on because I thought I wasn't going fast enough.''
   Knievel became the first stuntman _ and possibly the last _ to
negotiate the fountains that critically injured his father and Gary
Wells, who crashed in 1980.
   ``Make it or miss it, there will be no more jumps after this,''
Rich Rose, a Caesars executive, said earlier.
   The daredevil was guaranteed $250,000 for the jump, but his take
could be much higher depending on the pay-per-view profits.
   Evel Knievel watched from only a few feet away as his son landed
easily and sped into the underground garage where a brain surgeon
and a dozen paramedics were waiting for the worst.
   ``I'm not the greatest daredevil in the world, I'm the father of
the greatest daredevil in the world,'' the 50-year-old Knievel said.
   It was the older Knievel who made the jump famous and turned
himself into a household name in the process when he crashed on
landing and flipped like a rag doll through the parking lot and
broke nearly ever bone in his body.
   But Robbie Knievel made it easily, much to the delight of the
crowd of some 20,000 people who jammed the Las Vegas Strip and
cheered as he made the leap.
   ``I'm going to have to make the perfect jump,'' he said this
week. ``I can't afford to be off even an inch.''
   And perfect it was as Knievel, after several aborted runs made
the final run.
   The jump capped a festive evening that featured Willie Nelson
singing ``America the Beautiful.''
</TEXT>
