<DOCNO> AP890414-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0049EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-SafeIUDs     04-14 0429</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Safe IUDs,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>AMA Study Panel Concludes IUDs Can Be Safe, Effective for Some Patients</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Progesterone-releasing and copper-containing
intrauterine devices can provide safe and effective contraception
for women in monogamous relationships during their middle or late
child-bearing years, a medical study panel finds.
   An estimated 60 million women worldwide use IUDs. The number in
this country is about 2 million and only two companies market them
in the United States after a series of expensive and
well-publicized product-liability trials.
   ``It's a limited endorsement, but on the other hand, there's a
large number of women who fit the criteria we set out for patient
selection,'' said Dr. William Scott, who chaired the American
Medical Association panel that reviewed medical literature on IUDs
and released its finding in Friday's Journal of the AMA.
   ``We found the IUD most useful for women in stable, monogamous
relationships who have already had their families and don't want to
take the (oral contraceptive) pill either because of inconvenience
or for fear of complications,'' he said.
   ``They (IUDs) were not recommended, however, for women with
multiple sexual partners, those with a history of pelvic
infections, bleeding disorders or previous ectopic pregnancies.''
   Progesterone-releasing IUDs secrete the hormone progesterone,
which in turn prevents a fertilized egg from attaching itself to
the uterine wall. Researchers believe copper as an IUD component
similarly inhibits implantation.
   While IUDs are ranked among the most effective means of
contraception, potential complications include perforation of the
uterus and pelvic infection, which can result in infertility.
   ``Quite frankly, the severe health risks far outweigh the
benefits gained _ especially with so many other effective methods
of birth control already available in the U.S.,'' said Guerry
Thornton Jr., an Atlanta-based attorney and products-liability
specialist.
   ``But if the medical profession is going to comment on this,
their warnings should be as explicit as possible,'' said Thornton,
who represented women in a lawsuit against Dalkon Shield
manufacturer A.H. Robins Co., which declared bankruptcy three years
ago citing IUD-related litigation.
   The panel's findings were welcomed, however, by Rod Mackenzie,
chairman and chief executive officer at GynoPharma, the Somerville,
N.J.-based firm that last May began marketing the only copper IUD
sold in the United States.
   ``We're heartened,'' Mackenzie said, ``but not at all surprised.
This has basically been the opinion of the medical profession for
some time.''
   Mackenzie declined to provide exact sales figures, but said that
``75 percent of gynecologists in this country have bought the
product from us and most have re-purchased.
   ``That fact and this report are two very encouraging comments,''
he added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890414-0218 </DOCNO>
