<FIRST>r i AM-Honduras-Strike     04-14 0320</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Honduras-Strike,0329</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Walk Out In Sympathy With Striking Social Security Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thousands of workers and government
employees nationwide walked out Thursday in sympathy with 150
striking retirement fund employees, and scores of industries were
brought to a halt.
   The massive walkout was called by the Honduran Federation of
Workers, which claims a membership of 400,000. The organization
said it would not order its members to return to work until a labor
dispute at the School Teachers' Social Security Institute is
resolved.
   The institute handles a $150 million health insurance and
retirement benefits fund. Its 150 employees struck 16 days ago
demanding a 5 percent wage increase to compensate for higher living
costs. Employees now earn $500 to $3,000 a month, depending on
seniority.
   The teachers' union, which has 40,000 members, has refused to
negotiate and threatened to strike if the social security workers
do not return to work.
   But all 80,000 government employees responded to the call by the
Honduran Federation of Workers for a walkout early Thursday.
   They were joined at midday by workers at the Texaco Refinery
owned by Exxon Corp., and truck drivers. Other federation unions
promised to join later.
   Texaco is the country's only refinery, but there was no
immediate scarcity of gasoline at service stations.
   Hundreds of sympathy strikers blocked traffic on roads and
highways in the capital of Tegucigalpa and at San Pedro Sula,
Honduras' second-largest city and 125 miles north. There were no
reports of violence.
   ``We workers are willing to fight for this to the utmost of
consequences and we will continue on strike until we reach our
goals,'' federation president Mariano de Jesus Gonzalez said.
   President Jose Azcona Hoyo's administration said it was
``totally unacceptable that actions were undertaken that could
provoke anarchy and endanger the democratic stability of the
country, which has required much sacrifice by the people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
