<FIRST>a a PM-JapaneseConnection Adv19   04-14 0799</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japanese Connection, Adv 19,0818</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv19</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Wednesday PMs, April 19, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Small Quaker College Has Nurtured Relationship with Japan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEN KUSMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A century after Earlham College started
training Quaker missionaries bound for Asia, its ties with Japan
are paying off as Indiana maneuvers to cash in on that country's
growing U.S. investments.
   ``Japan is the excuse, but international education is the
goal,'' said Jackson Bailey, founder of Earlham's Institute for
Education on Japan. ``We are very careful not to say, `Come on, get
on the Japanese bandwagon.' That's not the idea at all. Five years
from now, it could be something else.''
   Meanwhile, Earlham has trained Hoosier businesspeople in
Japanese language and customs and has helped 16 school systems
introduce Japanese curricula.
   In Gary, school officials expect 300 students _ including 100
fourth-graders _ to enroll next fall in introductory Japanese. A
survey showed 512 of the 713 high school language students would
like to study Japanese.
   ``There's an extraordinary interest,'' said Anne Thompson,
supervisor of foreign languages for the Gary Community School Corp.
``Japan is in the news. This is a steel community. The fact that
America has lost the edge in the steel world and automobile world
to Japan is recognizable in this community.''
   Subaru-Isuzu Automotive will open an assembly plant with
Japanese management this year in Lafayette. The Lafayette, West
Lafayette and Tippecanoe County school systems, which have
international students connected with Purdue University, have taken
part jointly in Earlham's program. Four high schools now offer
first-year Japanese and study Japan in art, English and social
studies.
   ``It was certainly a well-timed opportunity for us to be
involved in this project. We spend a lot of time with the people
from Japan,'' said Charlotte McGaw, assistant principal at
Lafayette Jefferson High School.
   State Superintendent of Public Instruction H. Dean Evans and
then-Gov. Robert D. Orr asked Earlham four years ago to design an
international education program. Earlham, through a grant from the
Lilly Endowment, already had a pilot program that sent
Richmond-area teachers to Japan for six weeks. It now chooses five
systems a year to send people for two weeks here and three weeks in
Japan.
   For Earlham, it's the manifestation of a century-old
relationship with what was once one of the world's most closed
cultures. From 1893, when it graduated its first Japanese student,
until World War II, Earlham-trained missionaries and educators
headed for Japan, one as tutor to the empire's crown prince.
   The ties grew after World War II when some of the
Japanese-Americans who had been interned chose to study at the
Indiana college they had learned about from the Quaker
conscientious objectors that also had been jailed.
   Bailey, a conscientious objector who served in the Army Medical
Corps, spent a year in Japan during the occupation. He later
returned for three years with his wife and children as part of the
Quakers' American Friends Service Committee doing relief work in
orphanages, schools and neighborhood centers.
   The immersion in the foreign culture ``converted me to
international education. You enrich your definition of what it is
to be human,'' said Bailey, who in December received Japan's Order
of the Sacred Treasure.
   Within four years of his 1959 return to Earlham, the college was
operating a Japanese exchange program for a group of Midwestern
colleges. Other programs were added in 1973 and 1979, and there's
now talk of adding a fourth program so the school can accommodate
all of its students who want to study in Japan. This year Earlham,
a school of 1,200 students, had 65 studying first-year Japanese.
   About 10 percent of the Earlham faculty is bilingual in Japanese
and nearly one-third have worked there, many through the
sponsorship of the college, which seeks out a Japanese background
in prospective faculty members. Japan pervades the curriculum, from
social sciences to fine arts, and the school has adopted management
methods that have proven successful in Japanese industry.
   That isn't to say, however, that Earlham excludes other
cultures. More than half its students study abroad for at least six
months, compared with 1 percent of U.S. college students who study
abroad before graduating.
   Nonetheless, school President Richard J. Wood is counting on
Earlham's friends in Japan to raise $1 million for an endowed chair
in Japanese studies. ``We think it will be a recognition of the 30
years of work we've done to raise the level of Japanese studies in
the United States.
   ``Because we were there long before there was a wave of
interest, we are trying to take advantage of that wave of interest.
   ``The importance of Japan to the American economy will not go
down ... in the next 10 to 15 years.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for PMs, April 19</NOTE>
</DOC>
