<FIRST>a i PM-Mexico-Left Adv20   04-14 0842</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mexico-Left, Adv 20,0866</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv20</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thurs PMs April 20 or Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Unity of Mexican Left Fractured after Gains in Presidential Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The left that startled the nation with its
unity and a strong second place showing in last summer's
presidential election has tumbled back into disarray.
   The fragile coalition has been unable to turn an outpouring of
support for presidential candidate Cuauhtemoc Cardenas into a solid
front and has come out of a series of state and local elections as
divided losers.
   Leaders say they're not suprised, but they're not giving up.
   ``They were four parties that had a single candidate for the
presidency but nothing more,'' said Heberto Castillo, the Mexican
Socialist Party's presidential candidate who threw his support to
Cardenas a month before the July election and has worked with him
ever since.
   ``We could unite around a candidate for president but not for
deputies and senators. That's why we lost.''
   The four parties parties, ranging from center-left to left, that
were the core of the National Democratic Front have balked at
giving up their names, platforms, claim to congressional seats,
share of government funds and privileges for the sake of a larger,
potentially more effective, opposition.
   One has effectively re-allied itself with the long-governing
Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) in March, a move leaders
say broke the alliance.
   The leftist parties engage in public and private infighting.
Regional frictions add to national ones when the parties try to
agree on joint candidates for state and local races, further
weakening their image.
   Although the front is still mentioned in connection with
possible joint candidacies for state or local elections, leaders
say it was formed to fight the PRI and likely will be replaced by
another alliance.
   ``We need a more suitable, discreet, type of conduct,'' said
Sen. Porfirio Munoz Ledo, a former head of the PRI who became a
leader and strategist of the leftist opposition. ``If we're allies
we need to overlook many differences.''
   Some members of the opposition applied March 31 to register the
Democratic Revolution Party, which is to absorb the Socialist
Party. Socialist leader Castillo said the party is having a
``painful birth;'' none of the others have agreed to join.
   The Democratic Front came about because Cardenas was a reformist
who was shut out of the PRI. After he became the presidential
candidate of a small leftist party and his popularity soared,
bringing endorsements of two similar parties and the Socialists,
the largest leftist party.
   In dealing the PRI one of its worst blows in its 60-year
history, Cardenas took 31 percent of the vote. The victor, the
PRI's Carlos Salinas de Gortari, was held to just over 50 percent,
the slimmest presidential victory ever for the PRI. The
conservative National Action Party, long the main opposition,
received 17 percent.
   On Cardenas' coattails, the left captured four of the Senate's
64 seats, the first ever won by the opposition, and expanded its
bloc in the Chamber of Deputies.
   With National Action, it held the PRI to a 10-seat margin in the
500-seat chamber. Small parties, at least one in danger of losing
its registration, gained needed votes.
   The left blames the PRI government, known for co-opting and
manipulating the opposition, for some of its troubles.
   In addition to pressuring parties, the government is using its
strong influence over the news media and changes in local election
laws to thwart the left, Castillo claimed.
   The opposition was not allowed to register joint candidates in
Veracruz state elections in October but has had trouble even when
permitted.
   In Baja California, where Cardenas won last year, only Cardenas'
party and one other could agree on a candidate for the upcoming
governor's race. Two others decided to back another, or possibly
the PRI nominee. There is even talk of an alliance with National
Action.
   At the same time, Salinas has strengthened his image with
attacks on union corruption and drug trafficking, although his
toughest tests will be foreign debt negotiations and electoral
reform, both under way.
   Lorenzo Meyer of the Colegio de Mexico, a graduate school, said
the left is going through what could be a healthy sifting-out
process but needs to offer a concrete program for the country.
   ``With a mixture of good luck, intelligence and will, the
hardships of today can be not the beginning of the end for the
center-left opposition but its difficult but necessary purgatory to
achieve internal cohesion,'' Meyer wrote recently in a front-page
column in Excelsior, one of Mexico's leading newspapers.
   Castillo said the new party wants political competition and
better distribution of wealth but would respect the private sector.
   At least 4{ million of the 6 million votes officially registered
for Cardenas came from people outside the registered parties,
Castillo said.
   ``The political culture of this country is changing
substantially,'' he said. ``Before the (July) elections people
thought it was impossible to defeat the PRI. ... Now the people
think it is possible.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Thurs PMs April 20</NOTE>
