<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0820EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a PM-Spill-OtherCoasts Adv17   04-14 1240</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Spill-Other Coasts, Adv 17,1269</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday PMs, April 17, and thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Gulf of Mexico, California Coastlines Also At Risk From Oil</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   The 10.1 million-gallon oil spill in Alaska's
Prince William Sound, where emergency teams were unprepared and
slow to respond, has drawn attention to preparedness in California
and the Gulf of Mexico, where oil rigs and tankers make similar
disasters possible. AP writers Janet McConnaughey in New Orleans
and Jeff Wilson in Los Angeles found that a spill there the size of
the one from the Exxon Valdez would be just as hard to handle.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By JANET McCONNAUGHEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>JEFF WILSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Exxon Valdez spill has focused the nation's attention on
Alaska's oilfields, but rigs are pumping crude and tankers plying
the waters off other U.S. shores that could be just as devastated _
and just as hard to clean.
   And while cleanup companies backed by the oil industry say
they're poised to respond ``on a moment's notice'' to spills along
the California and Gulf of Mexico coasts, state officials are leery
of such claims, and say the only way to prevent damage from oil
spills is to prevent the spills.
   ``The lesson of the Valdez is clear: We cannot rely on oil
company representations that they can handle a spill,'' said
California Controller Gray Davis, who wants the Coast Guard in
charge of directing cleanups ``to avoid the type of disorganization
which seriously delayed action'' in Alaska. ``We cannot afford to
sacrifice our coastline to bureaucratic bickering,'' Davis said.
   More than 10 million gallons of oil spilled on Good Friday when
the Exxon Valdez hit a reef near Valdez, Alaska. Because a response
team was disbanded in 1982, it took 11 hours before booms were
placed around the fractured tanker, and only about 8 percent of the
spilled crude has been recovered.
   ``I don't know as anybody would ever be totally prepared to deal
with that quantity of oil,'' said Coast Guard Lt. Cmdr. Bob Pond in
New Orleans.
   ``I feel very strongly that if we had a spill of that magnitude,
we would not be able to contain it,'' said Bruce Hammett, emergency
response coordinator for the Louisiana Department of Environmental
Quality. ``The thing we would have to look at is trying to minimize
damage...
   ``I just don't think we have the necessary booms, manpower,
equipment and expertise to try to contain something like that.''
   Hammett believes that planners along the Gulf have grown
complacent in the five years since the last major spill, 2.7
million gallons from the Alvenus, a tanker that ran out of a
shipping channel and cracked open on a mud bottom near Cameron, La.
Oil from the spill washed onto Galveston, Texas, beaches.
   In the Gulf of Mexico, three cleanup companies under contract to
the Coast Gaurd have a total of 4,600 feet of containment booms
along with several boats, pumps and skimmers to clean oil from
water. Clean Gulf Associates, a consortium of 166 oil and gas
companies, has 5,000 feet of booms, more than 39,300 gallons of
chemical dispersant and boats with equipment to suck up oil. Clean
Gulf's members must practice at least once a year with the cleanup
equipment.
   A spill of any size in the Gulf would be fought under a plan
developed by the states, Coast Guard, Interior Department and the
Environmental Protection Agency. In California, the Coastal
Commission is responsible under state law for containing and
cleaning spills; it admitted in 1986 that it can't.
   In the past two years, the Southern California coastline was
polluted by 67,510 gallons of oil, of which 16,035 gallons were
never recovered. More than 1,150 tankers dock in Los Angeles every
year, and dozens of drilling platforms have raised concerns over
federal plans to lease additional oil reserves. An improperly cased
well was blamed for a 1969 spill off Santa Barbara of more than
3.25 million gallons of oil that dirtied 100 miles of coastline.
   California's three industry-financed cleanup cooperatives have a
DC-4 aircraft on standby in Mesa, Ariz., equipped to spray 2,000
gallons of chemical dispersants. They also have a total of 100,000
feet of booms, 30,000 gallons of dispersants, and about two dozen
boats of various sizes equipped for cleanups.
   But that equipment is in San Francisco, Santa Barbara and Los
Angeles, so the northern part of California's 800-mile coast
remains at risk. ``That is the most vulnerable spot in terms of
equipment,'' said Cmdr. Scott Porter, chief of environmental
protection and port safety for the 11th Coast Guard District.
   Jack Mortenson of Clean Bay conceded it would take a day for
boats from his San Francisco-based cleanup company to arrive in
Eureka near the Oregon border.
   ``Whether we could arrive in Eureka in time to be effective is a
question of which direction the wind is blowing,'' said Mortenson,
adding there was some leeway because tankers travel at least 50
miles offshore.
   ``Having no response ships in the north is one indication the
oil companies aren't as prepared as their public relations
departments would have us believe,'' said California Lt. Gov. Leo
McCarthy.
   In the Gulf, Louisiana's fragile marshes are of great concern.
Planners would rather see oil wash onto a beach than onto marshes
where shrimp and fish spawn, oysters are harvested, and nutria and
otter are trapped. ``You're going to do more environmental harm by
cutting out grasses and mucking through the estuary than you are
going to help by cleaning the oil up,'' said Pond.
   Prevailing currents and winds that would steer most spills away
from the marshes are the best protection Louisiana has, he said.
   Cleanup planning is harder in the Gulf than Alaska, which
exports just a few types of oil, Hammett said. ``Here in the Gulf
we receive just about every variation on crude oil imaginable ...
and each crude oil is different from the next. You have to look at
the toxic effects of each oil ... and what is at risk at various
times of the year _ whether seabirds are nesting, mammals having
young, whether it's shrimp season, oyster season, what have you.''
   In addition, the Gulf's shipping hazards _ production platforms
and crowded shipping lanes dredged through shallow bottoms _ can
hamper cleanup. The rigs can snag and tear booms, which don't work
too well unless the water is calm.
   ``If you don't have booms there very quickly, the oil is going
to spread quickly in all directions on the surface,'' Pond said.
``You'd just need an enormous amount of boom to even think of
containing it.''
   California Coastal Commission documents show that skimmers, the
main mechanical tools for cleaning up oil, work best in absolutely
calm waters. But even then, skimmers pick up only about 50 percent
of the oil they can reach. As waves reach about 2 feet, the
recovery rate drops to between 20 percent and 30 percent. With
six-foot waves, skimmers are virtually useless.
   The other method for breaking up oil spills _ pouring
dispersants into the water _ is controversial because of the
toxicity of the chemicals.
   ``I think there is no question that a large incident such as
occurred offshore in Alaska could occur off shore in California,''
said Peter Douglas, executive director of the California Coastal
Commission.
   ``We are at risk,'' said Kim McCleneghan of California's Fish
and Game Department.
  
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for PMs April 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
