<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0855EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e PM-APArts:Collier-Horowitz Adv18   04-14 0724</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-AP Arts: Collier-Horowitz, Adv 18,0746</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 18</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues PMs, April 18 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Former Radicals Carve Out Thriving Careers as Authors</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANA KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   They are former radicals whose thriving career as
a best-selling team of authors is testament to their rebirth as
conservatives.
   And their impassioned defense of the right is not unlike their
crusade on behalf of the left two decades ago.
   But given their dramatic change in politics and lifestyles,
Peter Collier and David Horowitz may have a more highly developed
sense of irony. Witness the T-shirt Horowitz wore during a recent
publicity tour to promote their latest book, ``Destructive
Generation _ Second Thoughts About the '60s'' (Summit Books,
$19.95).
   The words in Russian, emblazoned above a red star, translated to
``God Bless America.''
   Collier, 49, and Horowitz, 50, became friends while graduate
students at the University of California at Berkeley, and later
edited the leftist magazine, Ramparts. They are the authors of
three successful books, ``The Rockefellers: An American Dynasty,''
``The Fords: An American Drama'' and ``The Kennedys: An American
Epic.''
   Collier does the majority of the writing and Horowitz does much
of the legwork. Their most successful book was ``The Kennedys,''
which was also the most controversial. Its 1984 publication
coincided with the drug overdose death of David Kennedy.
   Now comes the nagging ``Destructive Generation,'' which makes
Tom Hayden's transition from fiery radical to California
legislator, or Jerry Rubin's transformation from yippie to
corporate networker seem mild by comparison.
   Collier and Horowitz, who bill their new book as the first to
examine the 1960s in a critical light, are not unlike unruly
schoolboys who have suddenly surfaced as hall monitors.
   In their own words, they see themselves as spokesmen for ``a
generation of people who refuse to be responsible for what they've
done.''
   ``The '60s were a great party. Now it's the big hangover,'' said
Collier. ``Most of what's been written up to now have been attempts
to romanticize the '60s. We're trying to provide an antidote to
that.''
   Their thesis is stern and unyielding: the '60s was a time of
naive idealism rooted in an inherent destructiveness.
   Collier and Horowitz argue that the antiwar, antiauthority,
pro-drug culture of the '60s resulted in a breakdown of the system
and the destruction of authority. Far from offering concrete
remedies for society, '60s leftists came up with ``jerry-built''
solutions that turned out to be disastrous.
   ``There was a basic social lawlessness in the '60s,'' Collier
said. ``We romanticized crime figures. We romanticized drugs. We
attacked authority at every level. The epidemic of crime is
directly related to drugs.''
   ``When you're young, you have great optimism,'' said Horowitz,
who recalls being taken to many Soviet-made movies by his parents,
both avowed communists. ``It's naivete at one point and then it
becomes destructive.''
   ``Destructive Generation,'' much of which originally appeared in
magazines such as Playboy, Rolling Stone and California, chronicles
what are seen as the ultimately ineffectual lives and times of
Black Panther defense attorney Fay Stender and the Weather
Underground.
   The personal odyssey of Collier and Horowitz from zealous
Marxists to staunch Reagan supporters is tacked onto the end of the
book.
   When they talk politics now, they praise authority figures
rather than revile them.
   ``We saw what Reagan did,'' said Horowitz, explaining their long
evolution from left to right. ``He restored pride in this country.
Reagan helped people who were looking for freedom all over the
world.''
   As part of the publicity tour for the book, Collier and Horowitz
already have engaged in several television debates with prominent
members of the left. The exchanges have been heated.
   The two are quick to point out that they have lost many friends
since joining the conservative cause. They also are prone to
defensiveness when asked questions they perceive imply that they
sold out for the sake of writing lucrative best sellers.
   They claim they paid a high price for their journey from humble
radicals to popular authors. ``We're stigmatized as troglodytes,''
said Collier.
   ``When I lived inside the Marxist myth, it made me very
strong,'' said Horowitz. ``When I lost my faith, I lost my
confidence. I was no longer part of something which gives you
strength.''
   Next on the Collier-Horowitz agenda: a biography of the
Roosevelts.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PM Tues April 18</NOTE>
