<FIRST>a a PM-ReligionRoundup Adv14 1stLd-Writethru 04-14 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Religion Roundup, Adv 14, 1st Ld-Writethru, b0130,0675</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Fri PMs April 14, or thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: RECASTS and EXPANDS first item to include Pepsi explanation.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUPELO, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Christian protesters claim to have
increasing influence on commercial advertisers on television.
   The American Family Association, based here, called off its
boycott of the Pepsi Cola Co. after the company dropped plans to
run more ads featuring segments of pop star Madonna's video ``Like
a Prayer.''
   The Christian association had called for a Pepsi Cola boycott to
protest what it considered sacrilegious imagery in the sensual
video. Roman Catholic Bishop Rene H. Gracida of Corpus Christi,
Texas, also had urged people to boycott Pepsi products.
   ``We think Pepsi has made a very wise business and moral
decision,'' the Rev. Donald E. Wildmon, AFA executive director,
said after the ad was withdrawn.
   In announcing the move, Pepsi Cola did not acknowledge that the
Christian protests influenced its decision. The company said,
however, that many people seemed to be confusing the video and the
Pepsi ad, which did not include the video segments most objected to
by those protesting the performance.
   Wildmon also noted that some advertisers canceled ads on the
show ``Saturday Night Live'' after protests of the program's
contents by the association.
   ``More and more corporations are beginning to say no to the
exploitative and anti-Christian programming of the networks,'' he
says.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Criticizing a proposed Vatican document on
Catholic colleges and universities that would allow bishops to
intervene to protect the faith in such institutions, the lay
Catholic journal, Commonweal, says:
   ``Bishops will be caught in a vicious circle. Having declared
their prerogative to intervene, they will either have to exercise
it or be held responsible for whatever occurs when they do not.
   ``Ambiguous cases will either require painful and embarrassing
interventions, or appear to enjoy church sanction when there is no
intervention. Episcopal authority will be undermined because in
many cases it will be unenforceable.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>ANNISTON, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The election of two women as deacons at
the First Baptist Church of Williams is causing a furor, with the
Calhoun Baptist Association asking the church to reconsider its
decision.
   Association members voted 433-225 at a special meeting for a
resolution disapproving the ordination of Dean Norton and Peggy
Hamby. The small Williams church was told to reconsider and if it
doesn't take appropriate action it may be ousted.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The president of the National Conference of
Catholic Bishops has written to President Bush urging his
diplomatic efforts to stop the shelling in Lebanon.
   ``The cycle of violence must be stopped so that needed political
negotiations can begin,'' said Archbishop John L. May of St. Louis.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   More than 4,000 Jews were allowed to leave the
Soviet Union in March, the highest monthly total in l0 years,
reports the National Conference on Soviet Jewry.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Freedom From Religion Foundation is suing the
state of Colorado, demanding that it remove a monument of the Ten
Commandments from the state Capitol grounds as a ``violation of
separation of church and state.''
   Anne Gaylor, foundation president, says, ``The Ten Commandments
begin with `Thou shalt have no other gods before me,' but in our
democracy we are free to have any god or no gods.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The idea in the early days of the ecumenical
movement that doctrine divides the churches but social causes unite
them has been reversed, says a noted Protestant ecumenist.
   The Rev. J. Robert Nelson, a United Methodist scholar of
Houston, told a gathering of Protestant and Catholic scholars that
the phrase ``insurmountable obstacle'' used to be applied to
matters of faith, but added:
   ``We are now inclined to attach it to an array of nagging,
difficult problems of social ethics and personal morality.''
</TEXT>
