<FIRST>a w AM-Business-Schools Adv17-1stLd-Writethru b0398 04-14 1211</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Business-Schools, Adv 17-1st Ld-Writethru, b0398,1233</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv17</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Mon AMs, April 17, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Corporations Lobbying for Sweeping Changes in Education</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5th graf to include full name of Georgia Alliance for Public
Education, ``They include xxx''.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL LAWRENCE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Corporations from Florida to California are
plunging into the political arena to lobby for sweeping changes in
public education _ and sometimes even the tax increases to pay for
them.
   The feel-good era is over, say those leading the charge. It is
no longer enough to pledge jobs, hold career days, provide mentors
or adopt a school.
   ``We've learned to say no ... to the altruistic warm fuzzy
stuff. We're not going to do that,'' says John Cairns, a lawyer and
former director of the Minnesota Business Partnership Inc. ``It
doesn't accomplish enough. It doesn't represent enough change in
the system. It doesn't return enough on the investment we're being
asked to make.''
   The new types of activism range from Cairns' Minnesota
coalition, which helped push through the state legislature a
pioneering statewide ``choice'' program giving parents a say in
where their children attend school, to a Chicago business group
instrumental in winning state legislative approval for radical
changes in their city's school system.
   They include business campaigns for education tax increases and
bond issues in New Orleans, Cincinnati, Miami, South Carolina and
California, and a successful drive to remove school board members
in Detroit. There's also the Georgia Alliance for Public Education,
which is convening 200 CEOs from around the state in June to talk
about education and business and politics, and the Boston Compact,
which started by offering job placements in exchange for school
improvements but has evolved into a citywide restructuring plan.
   ``There certainly are more and more examples of the business
community getting involved in some of the tougher political issues
confronting schools,'' says Michael Usdan, president of the
private, non-profit Institute for Educational Leadership, which is
examining trends in the relationship between education and business.
   ``There's a tendency now to move into the political arena, away
from ... the tiny programs that collectively may not have meant
much at a time when the whole enterprise was facing such terrible,
terrible problems,'' Usdan said.
   Personalized corporate involvement in schools became highly
visible in 1981 when New York philanthropist Eugene Lang
``adopted'' a class of sixth-graders at his alma mater, promising
them counseling, support and college scholarships if they went on
to graduate.
   Another boost came in 1983 after the release of ``A Nation at
Risk,'' the gloomy report that detailed profound shortcomings in
U.S. education.
   From 1983 to 1987, the Education Department reports, the number
of education partnerships in public schools rocketed from 42,200 to
140,800 _ more than half of them sponsored by businesses.
   But the department also found that the most frequent types of
support provided by education partnerships were special awards,
scholarships or incentives for students, and guest speakers,
special demonstrations or use of the partner's facilities or
equipment. The offerings suggest some of the limitations inherent
in the approach.
   Some of those involved with adopt-a-school programs speak
bluntly about the problems.
   Some corporations may consider this ``the least expensive way to
satisfy their obligation... It's far more difficult to run a
complex jobs placement program where there are quid pro quos with
the school system,'' says Gene Cartwright, community affairs
manager for the Amoco Corp., which was heavily involved in this
year's successful drive to revamp Chicago's schools.
   Cartwright and others also noted that adopting schools, the most
popular form of partnership, often means adopting survivors _ not
those students most at risk.
   ``Basically, most of the businesses don't want to deal with the
more difficult students,'' says Sandra Hamburg of the Committee for
Economic Development, a group of business executives and educators
that has issued influential reports on the need to invest in
disadvantaged children. ``They only want the best students to come
in to their business for a career day program or they don't want to
deal with pairing a company employee with someone who's not really
motivated.''
   The National Alliance of Business, a non-profit group financed
half by the federal government and half by the private sector, has
undertaken a major effort to widen and deepen business impact by
sponsoring programs modeled on the Boston Compact in 12 cities
across the country. The premise is that local businesses pledge
jobs to high school graduates in exchange for school improvements
such as a reduction in the dropout rate.
   However, the Boston Compact achieved mixed results in its first
five years and a private evaluation of the first 18 months of the
NAB project in seven cities found the same uneven pattern.
   ``The best evidence we have points to the usefulness of these
(compacts) in the areas of targeted jobs, scholarships and
modestly-scaled collaborative programming for at-risk youth,''
wrote Gary Walker of Public-Private Ventures, the Philadelphia firm
that did the February 1989 evaluation.
   ``The elusive element of these systemwide collaborations,
however, continues to be the very thing that underlies their
origination and continuing popularity: `school improvement,'''
Walker wrote. ``School-business compacts may be no more than one
important piece of a much larger puzzle.''
   That view came through strongly at an NAB conference last week
among business officials involved in the political arena.
Cartwright called compacts ``a natural and reasonable entry point
for business to interact with the schools'' but added, ``Don't
assume that they alone will remodel the infrastructure of a failing
school system.''
   Cartwright and Cairns, participants in a panel on state action,
contended that businesses can significantly influence education
only by becoming active in the state legislative process because
most education funds come from states.
   ``If you're not a player with the state on many of these
programs, you're really not playing where most of the decisions are
made,'' Cairns said.
   Some supporters of the compact concept disagreed. ``A lot of
change in large city systems is going to happen in cities
themselves,'' said Jim Vollman, executive director of the Detroit
Compact. ``They are managed by local elected boards and if they
don't buy it, it's not going to happen. You can't expect the state
to do it.''
   But even the compacts are finding they must get involved in
politics _ school board or city council _ to win real change. In
Boston, for example, businesses were highly successful at placing
high school graduates in jobs but test scores improved only
slightly and dropout rates proved intransigent. In the compact's
second phase, business leaders are working with the mayor, elected
education officials and teacher unions to achieve specific reforms:
school-based management and a school ``choice'' program.
   The common ground among forward-thinking business leaders is
that whether their playing field is a city, a state or a district,
they must move beyond a one-school approach.
   ``Adopt-a-school served a very important historical role ...,''
says Eve Hoffman, president of the Georgia Alliance, a non-profit
group formed to educate and activate the business community on
education issues. ``There are a lot of people who have a lot
invested in adopt-a-school and what we have to do is encourage
these people to look beyond that at bigger issues.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs April 17</NOTE>
</DOC>
