<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0854</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and the Securities
and Exchange Commission settled a massive civil fraud case that
will put the junk-bond giant under close federal scrutiny for three
years and sever its relationship with indicted financier Michael
Milken.
   Drexel also announced Thursday that John Shad, a former SEC
chief instrumental in starting an intense investigation more than
two years ago that led to the fraud charges, would become its
chairman.
   The Drexel-SEC pact clears the way for Drexel's previously
announced agreement to plead guilty to criminal fraud charges and
pay $650 million in fines and restitution to settle another case
with the Justice Department.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's $90 billion plan to bail out
the savings and loan industry cleared its second major
congressional hurdle, passing a House subcommittee one day after
receiving the unanimous endorsement of the Senate Banking Committee.
   The 47-member House Banking subcommittee on financial
institutions passed the bill Thursday by voice vote after four
day-long drafting sessions wading through nearly 200 amendments.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Peter V. Ueberroth's failed bid for Eastern
Airlines has raised several new possibilities for the
strike-crippled carrier, including an auction run by the federal
bankruptcy court and new buyout offers from others.
   On Thursday, a day after his $464 million deal with Ueberroth
collapsed, Eastern boss Frank Lorenzo said he is turning attention
to his plan to reorganize Eastern as a much smaller airline.
   In Miami, meanwhile, American Airlines chief Robert Crandall
said American is interested in such Eastern assets as its Latin
American and Canadian routes. American, one of Eastern's leading
rivals, already is expanding to capitalize on the embattled
carrier's problems.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. expects to record a $1.3 billion
after-tax profit from the sale of Texaco Canada Inc., company
officials said.
   Texaco's chief financial officer, Allen J. Krowe, told a meeting
of securities analysts Thursday that the $1.3 billion would be
``slightly offset'' by minor restructuring expenses.
   Texaco sold its 78 percent in the lucrative Canadian subsidiary
to Exxon Corp. in January for $3.24 billion. The deal was one of
the final steps in a massive restructuring following the company's
emergence from bankruptcy a year earlier.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The company that publishes the National
Enquirer, the saucy supermarket tabloid, is being sold for $412.5
million in cash to a New York-based concern that publishes romance
magazines.
   Macfadden Holdings Inc., whose titles include True Story, True
Confessions and Modern Romance, said Thursday it was in a
partnership that signed a definitive agreement to buy GP Group
Inc., which publishes the Enquirer and Weekly World News from
Lantana, Fla.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government's report that retail sales rose
0.1 percent in March after dropping sharply in February is evidence
that cautious consumer spending is moderating economic growth,
analysts say.
   Sales totaled a seasonally adjusted $139.42 billion last month,
held back by sluggish business at department stores and auto
dealerships, the Commerce Department reported Thursday. Sales had
plunged 0.6 percent in February.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 28.3 percent rise in early April auto sales may
indicate that cut-rate financing and rebates are attracting buyers,
analysts say.
   But part of the huge increase reported Thursday also stems from
comparison with a slower-than-usual sales pace during April 1-10
last year.
   The eight U.S.-based car and truck makers said they sold
vehicles at an average daily rate of 36,967 during early April,
compared with a 28,811 vehicle-a-day rate during the same time last
year.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge temporarily restrained
billionaire takeover investor Marvin Davis from meddling with
unions at Northwest Airlines, which Davis is trying to buy.
   U.S. District Judge Harry MacLaughlin granted the temporary
restraining order Thursday at the request by NWA Inc., parent of
the nation's fourth-largest airline, saying Davis should avoid any
``actions and communications'' disruptive to current contracts or
contract negotiations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ConAgra Inc. said it has agreed to divest a
portion of Holly Farms Corp.'s flour milling operation if it
succeeds in a $1 billion buyout of its poultry-industry competitor.
   The agreement with the staff of the Federal Trade Commission
would require ConAgra to divest 2.4 million pounds of Holly Farms'
daily flour milling capacity if the merger is completed, ConAgra
spokesman Walt Casey said Thursday.
</TEXT>
