<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0239EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Drexel-Chronology     04-14 0725</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Drexel-Chronology,0751</SECOND>
<HEAD>Important Dates in Drexel Investigation</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drexel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a chronology of major developments in the investigation
of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and its high-yield bond trader
Michael R. Milken:
   May 12, 1986 _ The Securities and Exchange Commission charges
Dennis Levine of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. with making $12.6
million in profits from illegal trading on inside information since
1980.
   June 5 _ Levine pleads guilty to four felonies, agrees to
cooperate with the government's investigation and surrenders $11.6
million in illicit profits and restitution.
   Nov. 14 _ Stock speculator Ivan Boesky agrees to pay a $100
million penalty to settle charges of trading on insider information
supplied by Levine in 1985 and 1986. He also agrees to cooperate
with investigators in a much broader investigation of Drexel and
its chief financier, Michael Milken.
   Feb. 20 _ Levine is sentenced to two years in prison and fined
$362,000 on charges of securities fraud, tax evasion and perjury.
   March 19 _ Boyd L. Jefferies, founder of the Los Angeles
securities firm Jefferies &amp; Co., pleads guilty to two violations of
securities laws in exchange for cooperating in the government's
investigation. He quits the brokerage and agrees to stay out of the
securities business or at least five years.
   April 23 _ Boesky pleads guilty to a single charge of conspiracy
to lie to the SEC, punishable by five years imprisonment and a
$250,000 fine.
   Dec. 18 _ Boesky is sentenced to a three-year prison term and no
fine.
   March 24, 1988 _ Boesky begins serving his sentence at a
minimum-security facility in Lompoc, Calif.
   Aug. 4 _ A grand jury indicts five partners in the investment
concern Princeton-Newport Partners and a former Drexel trader over
an alleged multimillion dollar fraud and racketeering scheme, the
first-ever racketeering charge against securities professionals.
Defendants deny wrongdoing and their attorneys call the indictment
a pressure tactic to force their cooperation in a much larger
investigation of Drexel and Milken.
   Sept. 7 _ The SEC accuses Drexel, Milken and three other
employees of violating a wide range of securities laws, most in
connection with Boesky. Drexel and the others deny the accusations.
   Nov. 30 _ Intense secret negotiations are reported between
Drexel and federal prosecutors in a last-ditch attempt by the firm
to avert an indictment, particularly racketeering charges, which
carry enormous penalties.
   Dec. 7 _ Princeton-Newport Partners liquidates because of what
defense lawyers call brutal government misuse of the racketeering
laws to coerce their clients into cooperating in the Drexel
investigation.
   Dec. 21 _ Drexel agrees to plead guilty to six felonies and pay
a record $650 million in fines and restitution to settle the
biggest securities fraud probe in history. Under the settlement,
Drexel must also settle the related SEC litigation and cooperate in
the government's pursuit of other alleged wrongdoers.
   Jan. 25, 1989 _ The government files formal charges against
Drexel, publicly detailing for the first time the accusations to
which it will plead guilty. Most are related to the firm's alleged
relationship with Boesky.
   Feb. 10 _ Milken asks a federal judge to reject or modify the
plea agreement on the grounds it violates his rights by forcing
Drexel to fire him and withhold his multimillion-dollar 1988 pay.
Milken charges Drexel was coerced into signing the pact because of
the threat of racketeering charges.
   March 22 _ Drexel assistant bond trader Lisa Jones is convicted
of lying to a federal grand jury during an investigation into stock
parking allegations between Drexel and Princeton-Newport Partners.
The perjury conviction is the first in the government's
investigation of Drexel.
   March 29 _ A federal grand jury indicts Milken, his brother
Lowell Milken and former Drexel trader Bruce Newberg on 98 counts
of racketeering and fraud. Potential penalties and fines under the
counts amount to more than $12 billion plus possible prison terms.
   April 7 _ Michael and Lowell Milken plead innocent to all
charges at a federal court arraignment.
   April 13 _ Drexel and the SEC announce a settlement of the civil
fraud cause that subjects the firm to federal monitoring for three
years and forces it to sever ties with Michael Milken. Drexel also
announces that former SEC chief John Shad _ who was instrumental in
starting the investigation that led to the fraud charges _ would
become its chairman.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890414-0238 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0241EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Drexel-Terms     04-14 0735</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Drexel-Terms,0761</SECOND>
<HEAD>Terms Of Drexel Settlement With SEC</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Drexel, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are key terms of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s settlement
with the Securities and Exchange Commission announced Thursday.
   _As previously announced, Drexel agrees to plead guilty to six
felony counts of securities fraud and payment of $650 million in
civil and criminal penalties and restitution to civil claimants.
   _Drexel agrees to a permanent injunction against future
violations of securities laws. If Drexel violates the injunction,
the SEC can resume proceedings that could result in Drexel's losing
its broker-dealer status.
   _Drexel agrees to ``disassociate'' junk bond chief Michael
Milken from its business. It must fire or place on a leave of
absence any other employee who is indicted.
   _Drexel agrees to buy back Michael Milken's shares in the
company and, if his brother Lowell Milken is no longer employed by
Drexel, to purchase his shares as well.
   _Drexel agrees to appoint three independent directors to its
board, including a new chairman of Drexel's holding company. The
three directors will oversee internal controls and audit,
accounting and compliance and serve as a disciplinary committee.
   The new chairman will be John S.R. Shad, former chairman of the
Securities and Exchange Commission. The other two outside directors
will be Rod Hills, also a former chairman of SEC and the husband of
U.S. Trade Representative Carla Hills, and Ralph Saul, former head
of the American Stock Exchange.
   _Drexel also agrees to pick people approved by the SEC for four
other top posts: general counsel, director of compliance, a senior
trading official who will review trades for three years, and a
member of Drexel's executive committee who will live in the Los
Angeles area and oversee Drexel's Beverly Hills office.
   Saul Cohen has already been approved as general counsel. He
previously was a partner with the law firm of Rosenman &amp; Colin.
   _Drexel will move its stock and convertible securities trading
operations from Beverly Hills, Calif., to New York.
   _Drexel will be allowed to keep its high-yield junk bond
operations in Beverly Hills, but it will be under the oversight of
the SEC-approved executive committee member.
   _Drexel agrees to cooperate with the government's continuing
investigation retroactive to 1978 and extending for three years
after completion of the settlement.
   _Drexel agrees to pay $15 million in civil penalties,
representing three times the profits gained or losses avoided in
dealings in several stocks. The $15 million is part of the $650
million in fines and restitution that Drexel had previously agreed
to pay.
   _Drexel agrees to name at least three compliance officers in the
offices of the junk bond department. At least two must be persons
who have not previously worked in the junk bond department. The
compliance officers will have the authority to cancel or revoke
securities transactions.
   _The law firm of Morgan, Lewis &amp; Bockius, selected by the SEC,
will review and report on Drexel's policies, procedures and
practices and recommend changes.
   _Drexel agrees to pay for an accountant, Peat Marwick Main &amp;
Co., which has been picked by the U.S. attorney's office, to review
Drexel's records.
   _Drexel agrees to hire a ``special reviewer'' acceptable to the
SEC to review its investment company operations.
   _Drexel agrees to hire an outsider with SEC approval to serve as
ombudsman. The ombudsman, William Hughes Mulligan, a former federal
appeals court judge, will report to the oversight committee and
will have the authority to conduct independent investigations.
   _Drexel agrees to either terminate or place on leave anybody who
is currently named or who may be named in an indictment within the
next five years in SEC civil actions alleging security fraud
violations concerning junk bond operations.
   _To prevent conflicts of interest, Drexel agrees to create a
capital markets services department in Beverly Hills that will be
in charge of pricing and selling new junk bond securities.
   _New public issues of debt securities may not be purchased by
employees or employee-related accounts. Drexel employees would also
be prohibited from acquiring stock or warrants of an issuer for
which Drexel has written or privately placed securities within the
preceding six months.
   _The agreement is to become final after Drexel enters formal
pleas to the six felony counts to which it agreed to plead guilty
in its plea bargain with federal prosecutors.
   _Separately, the SEC announced a settlement with Cary Maultasch,
a former Drexel employee who was named in last year's complaint.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
