<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0244EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-NationalEnquirer Bjt   04-14 0652</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-National Enquirer, Bjt,0677</SECOND>
<HEAD>Agreement Reached to Sell National Enquirer For $412.5 Million</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Can a romance magazine publisher find happiness
cranking out a weekly supermarket tabloid full of celebrities and
gossip?
   National Enquirer readers may soon find out.
   Macfadden Holdings Inc., whose titles include True Story, True
Confessions and Modern Romance, said Thursday it has agreed to pay
$412.5 million for the company that publishes the National
Enquirer, the saucy scandal sheet put on the auction block nearly
four months ago.
   Macfadden said it had formed a partnership that made the winning
bid for GP Group Inc., which publishes the Enquirer from Lantana,
Fla.
   The definitive sales agreement caps an auction process launched
in mid-December after the October death of Generoso Pope Jr., who
owned GP Group.
   Macfadden officials said the deal could be completed in May.
   ``It sounds like a good solid price,'' said John Reidy, a media
industry analyst for the investment firm Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.
   But he noted there was little financial information available
publicly about either GP Group or Macfadden because they are both
privately held.
   Some of the biggest names in the media business, including
British publisher Robert Maxwell, France's Hachette SA and West
German publisher Heinrich Bauer, were reportedly among the bidders
at one time or another.
   Reidy said he suspected, however, that Macfadden felt its
properties could benefit from a link to the Enquirer's supermarket
distribution system.
   In a statement announcing the agreement late Thursday, Macfadden
said it had formed a partnership to make the bid with media
investment fund Boston Ventures Limited Partnerhip III, which is
financing the purchase.
   Macfadden will have responsibility for operating GP Group's
holdings, which include the Enquirer's sister publication, Weekly
World News.
   The National Enquirer has an average paid circulation of about
4.3 million per week while the circulation of Weekly World News is
about 1 million.
   The two publications offer considerable advertising power and an
attractive franchise in the supermarket checkout lanes.
   ``We are delighted we are the successful bidder for the GP
Group,'' said Peter Callahan, chairman of Macfadden.
   ``We have great respect for all of the employees who have helped
build the company. We are enthusiastic about the company's
management and its prospects,'' he said.
   Iain Calder, chairman and president of GP Group, said, ``The
entire GP Group family welcomes this opportunity we will have with
the new owners and are pleased with their commitment to us and
their desire to continue to build and grow the company.''
   The Blackstone Group, a private New York investment bank, was
retained last December to conduct the auction. One of Blackstone's
partners, Peter G. Peterson, was one of three trustees for Pope's
estate.
   Peterson could not be reached for comment, and the firm declined
to comment on how many bidders actually participated.
   But it was understood that the auction was conducted in two
phases, with the first cut in potential candidates coming about two
months ago. The deadline for final bids was Wednesday, and the
decision on a winner was completed Thursday.
   Michael Boylan, Macfadden's president, said he and Callahan met
with GP Group employees Thursday in Florida and told them they
considered the employees as among the most valued assets of the
company.
   He said that while there may be some changes in how the
publications are marketed, the prospective new owners don't plan to
change their operations. GP Group's headquarters will remain in
Lantana, he said.
   Macfadden was founded in 1975 when Callahan acquired several
unprofitable romance publications for an investment of $800.
   Today, Macfadden publishes a group of seven romance magazines
with a combined monthly circulation of about 2 million, led by True
Story at 1.3 million, Boylan said.
   In addition, Macfadden publishes Teen Beat magazine with a
circulation of 250,000 a month, and two special interest magazines,
The Discount Merchandiser and Chief Executive.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
