<FIRST>u f AM-Japan-Markets 1stLd-Writethru   04-14 0283</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru,f0314,0294</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Share Prices Slip</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UDPATES with morning Nikkei, comments.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar slipped against the Japanese yen
Friday, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange also were
lower in morning trading.
   The dollar, which opened at 132.00 yen, down 0.80 yen from
Thursday's close, rose slightly to 132.30 yen by late morinig. It
moved in the range of 131.92 to 132.37 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 192.51-point
loser Thursday, shed another 138.67 points, or 0.42 percent, to
finish the morning session at 32,925.27.
   The decline was precipitated by a retreat in New York linked to
the dollar's weakness in currency markets, said Yoshiro Inouye, an
analyst with Nomura Securities.
   ``But participants were inclined to remain on the sidelines
today, due to concerns over the release of U.S. economic indicators
(later Friday)'' he said.
   The United States was to announce major economic figures,
including the nation's trade figures for February and wholesale
prices for March.
   Japanese stock investors expect the U.S. trade deficit to widen
to around $9.9 billion from $9.5 billion in January, Inouye said,
   Political uncertainty over a widening stock profiteering and
bribery scandal here has chronically discouraged trading, he added.
   In the currency market, traders said the dollar fell after
slipping in New York to 132.06 yen, down 0.99 yen from its 133.05
yen close Wednesday.
   The U.S. currency weakened following a rise in Swiss interest
rates and the appointment of a new West German finance minister,
the traders said.
   Nervousness over U.S. trade figures was also discouraged trading
in the foreign exchange market, a dealer at a Japanese commercial
bank said on condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
