<FIRST>r f BC-BurlingtonResources     04-14 0350</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Burlington Resources,0361</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burlington Resources To Spin Off Plum Creek Timber Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burlington Resources Inc., which itself was spun
off from Burlington Northern Inc. last year, said Thursday it
intends to divest its timber and wood products operation, Plum
Creek Timber Co.
   Burlington Resources said Plum Creek Timber Co. L.P., a master
limited partnership, had registered with the Securities and
Exchange Commission for an initial public offering, with proceeds
to be used to acquire and run Plum Creek.
   Plum Creek has approximately 1.4 million acres of timberland and
about 9.6 billion board feet of salable softwood timber in the
Pacific Northwest. It employs about 1,800 people in Washington,
Idaho and Montana, and in 1988 had a profit of $57.4 million on
revenues of $332.8 million.
   Burlington Resources said the current management of Plum Creek
would remain in place and that no changes in employment levels
would result from the establishment of the partnership.
   In its registration statement with the SEC, the partnership
seeks an initial public offering of 12.35 million depositary units,
each with a proposed maximum offering price of $20.50. The units
represent an 88 percent interest in the limited partnership.
   Immediately before completing the public offering, the
partnership and its 95 percent-owned subsidiary, Plum Creek
Manufacturing Inc., would borrow about $325 million, which, with
the proceeds of the offering, would be used to buy Plum Creek.
   The combined aquisition price is expected to be about $575
million. Burlington Resources will keep a 12 percent interest in
the partnership, along with some of Plum Creek's assets.
   Burlington Resources said its decision to divest Plum Creek was
consistent with its plans to concentrate on its gas, oil and
natural gas pipeline businesses.
   It said it plans to distribute at least 60 cents per unit each
quarter, and if necessary, Burlington Resources would make cash
payments to the partnership to support such distributions.
   Last year, Burlington Northern spun off Burlington Resources to
encompass Burlington's oil, mineral, timber and pipeline segments.
Burlington Northern kept the Burlington Northern Railroad and moved
its headquarters from Seattle to Fort Worth, Texas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
