<FIRST>r f PM-Fusion-Westinghouse Bjt   04-14 0666</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fusion-Westinghouse, Bjt,0688</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fusion May Still Be A Generation Away, Fission Leader Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If the development of the atom-splitting
fission process is any guide, decades may pass before exciting new
fusion experiments lead to the commerical production of power by
combining atoms, Westinghouse Electric Corp. officials say.
   ``As a rule of thumb, we'd say it's probably 20 to 30 years
away,'' said J. Robert Maxwell, manager of strategic programs for
Westinghouse's energy business. ``It's virtually a test tube
experiment, a bench-top experiment.''
   From the Manhattan project in the early 1940s it took until 1957
to build the first experimental fission power plant at
Shippingport, Pa. Widespread commericial use of the process to make
electricity took another decade.
   Maxwell and another top official at the nation's leading
producer of nuclear power plants say fusion also may pose
significant radiation hazards, although probably not as severe as
those from splitting atoms in fission reactors.
   ``Fusion is not a piece of cake,'' Maxwell said. ``If this turns
out to be successful, then we'll switch to fusion. Then we'll have
to find the new demons and solve them.''
   Nonetheless, Maxwell and the company's top scientist said
reports from the University of Utah, Georgia Tech, Texas A&amp;M and
elsewhere of what appears to be a cold fusion process may bring a
tidal shift in energy production, but not anytime soon.
   The three universities have not even demonstrated a theory of
how the process works.
   ``They have developed an experiment which suggsts there is a
principle that can be demonstrated,'' Maxwell said. ``Probably it
is an advance ... but it causes us some problems of its own that we
have not explored.''
   Fusion could eliminate the problem of spent radioactive fuel
that must be sealed in storage indefinitely. But fusion may have to
take place behind heavy shielding to protect power plant employees,
and it may irradiate power plant components to the point where they
must be handled like the radioactive scrap from today's fission
plants, he said.
   Westinghouse is one of about 10 companies that signed agreements
to review the University of Utah's patent applications on condition
that the lab results remain confidential, James Brophy, university
vice president for research, said Thursday.
   Westinghouse will evaluate Utah's patent applications while
searching for commercial applications for its fusion experiment, R.
D. ``Dee'' Haun Jr., Westinghouse's chief scientist, said Wednesday
in an interview.
   ``It's very tantalizing,'' said Haun, who describes himself as
an enthusiastic skeptic about cold fusion.
   Utah's chemistry department chairman, B. Stanley Pons, and his
colleague, Martin Fleischmann of the University of Southampton,
England, announced March 23 that they had replicated at room
temperature the process that powers the sun and hydrogen bombs.
   Amid great skepticism among scientists, Georgia Tech and Texas
A&amp;M said this week that their separate experiments appear to
confirm the work of Fleischmann and Pons.
   They passed electricity through palladium while the metal was
immersed in heavy water, which differs from regular water in that
its hydrogen component has a heftier nucleus than the lone proton
at the heart of a regular hydrogen atom.
   The heavy hydrogen atoms bond in pairs to create a bigger atom
that releases energy in the form of speeding neutrons as it
deteriorates, Haun said.
   ``Unfortunately, that's as far as classical explanations will
get you,'' he said Wednesday.
   The experiments do not precisely fit existing fusion theories
because far fewer energy-bearing neutrons are being detected than
predicted, Haun said.
   ``But if this works like high-temperature fusion, it could
generate a lot of neutrons, comparable to the number of neutrons in
fission and those neutrons are going to activate the surroundings.
So you'd have a waste disposal problem, a shielding problem,'' he
said.
   However, the neutrons detected in the lab experiments appear to
be roughly 10 billion times fewer than commercial fission, Haun
said.
   A Westinghouse scientist began work March 24 trying to duplicate
the Utah experiment. Results so far are inconclusive, he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
