<FIRST>r f PM-Texaco Bjt   04-14 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Texaco, Bjt,0577</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texaco Expects $1.3 Billion Profit From Texaco Canada Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Securities analysts say Texaco Inc. is a
dramatically changed company a year after emerging from bankruptcy
and completing a major restructuring.
   At a meeting with analysts Thursday, Texaco officials said the
company is approaching the future with optimism after recording a
$1.3 billion after-tax profit from the sale of Texaco Canada Inc.
   ``There is a kind of change from big revenues and an
empire-builder to a cost-conscious company,'' said one securities
official who asked that his name not be used.
   Texaco's chief financial officer, Allen J. Krowe, told the
analyst group that the $1.3 billion first-quarter profit would be
slightly offset by restructuring expenses.
   Texaco sold its 78 percent stake in the lucrative Canadian
subsidiary to Exxon Corp. in January for $3.24 billion. The deal
was one of the final steps in a massive restructuring following the
company's emergence from bankruptcy last April.
   The company realized nearly $7 billion in total proceeds from
the asset sales, more than the company and analysts had expected.
   Krowe said Texaco revenue would decline slightly in 1989 from
$35.14 billion in 1988, reflecting divestments, although revenue
from continuing operations was expected to rise about 5 percent.
   The financial officer also said Texaco had reduced its debt to
about $7.1 billion at the end of the first quarter from $7.9
billion at the end of 1988 and expects a reduction to $6.5 billion
by year's end.
   On another matter, Texaco President James W. Kinnear said the
oil industry needed to strengthen its efforts to prevent another
spill like last month's disaster off the Alaskan coast, in which a
grounded Exxon tanker spilled about 250,000 barrels of oil into
Prince William Sound.
   ``We have to redouble our efforts to be safe and to make certain
that this in fact was only an isolated incident,'' Kinnear told
reporters.
   Kinnear said he met Thursday with the heads of several other
major oil companies, including Exxon, the largest U.S. oil company,
for the first time to begin discussions on how to prevent a similar
disaster and improve response time.
   Texaco's restructuring has helped boost the company's share
price from $38 a year ago to $53.62{ at Thursday's close on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   Despite the changes, analysts agree that Texaco still must make
a big oil discovery if it intends to compete in the future.
Although Texaco is focusing more capital expenditures on
exploration and production, about 80 percent of its efforts involve
going back into old wells using improved technology.
   ``Kinnear has delivered on many things that he said he would,''
Stephen Smith, analyst for Bear Stearns &amp; Co., said before the
meeting. ``But as far as future performance, that will take time.''
   In April 1987, Texaco filed for protection from creditors under
Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy laws to avoid having to post a
potentially ruinous multibillion-dollar security bond in its fight
with Pennzoil Co.
   Pennzoil had sued Texaco, claiming Texaco's 1984 acquisition of
Getty Oil Co. interfered with Pennzoil's prior contract to buy part
of reserve-rich Getty.
   In 1985, a Houston jury awarded Pennzoil a $10.3 billion
judgment. Texaco appealed the judgment but eventually settled with
Pennzoil for $3 billion amid heavy shareholder pressure to do so.
</TEXT>
