<FIRST>r f PM-AutoSales Bjt   04-14 0637</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Auto Sales, Bjt,0658</SECOND>
<HEAD>Are Incentives Really Working? Many Dealers Say No</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two-week-old incentives apparently drew some car
buyers into showrooms in early April, when vehicle sales soared
28.3 percent over last year, but some in the industry wondered if
car sales really are rebounding.
   Automakers who reported their April 1-10 sales figures Thursday
have been banking on strong results to put off speculation that
large-scale production cuts may be down the road.
   The eight companies that make cars and trucks in the United
States said they sold vehicles at an average daily rate of 36,967
during early April, compared with a 28,811-vehicle-a-day rate
during the same time last year.
   Car sales shot up 30.1 percent and truck sales were up 25.2
percent over last year's levels.
   Automakers and some analysts said the results were positive
signs that the industry was back on track.
   ``These sales look pretty strong,'' said analyst Scott Merlis of
Morgan Stanley &amp; Co. of New York. ``It represents a normal and
healthy response to the latest round in sales incentives.''
   ``Our dealers tell us there is strong consumer interest in and
floor traffic from our new incentive program,'' Robert Rewey, vice
president for Ford Motor Co.'s North American sales operations,
said in a statement.
   But spot checks by The Associated Press late Wednesday and
Thursday of dealers in Ohio, Louisiana, Connecticut, Washington,
Illinois and Arizona showed no consumer rush to buy new cars.
   ``I think people are washed up with incentives,'' said sales
manager Mark Baudean of Sewell Cadillac-Chevrolet in New Orleans.
   March and April typically are big months for automakers as
Americans prepare for summer vacations and weekend road trips. But
sales during March and the entire first quarter of 1989 were lower
than expected. Meantime, ambitious production schedules continued
and inventories rose, leading to speculation that without a sales
boost, summertime production cuts and layoffs are growing
possibilities.
   All that led to the latest round of buyer enticements, which
included cut-rate financing and bigger cash rebates on more cars
and trucks.
   On March 29, Ford opened the gates by offering 2.9 percent
financing for two-year loans, along with the rebates.
   General Motors Corp. matched the offer a day later, and on April
3, Chrysler Corp. undercut its competitors by offering
interest-free financing on two-year deals.
   ``While Detroit is likely to put a brave face on this sales
report, management has to be disappointed,'' said analyst Ron
Glantz of Montgomery Securities Inc. in San Francisco. ``Some sales
have been deferred from late March ... (and) sales are normally
strongest in the first two selling periods after a major increase
in incentives.''
   Tom Webb, a senior economist for the National Automobile Dealers
Association in McLain, Va., said it appeared the gain was due more
to the weak period last year than a strong period this year.
   Big incentives last year expired at the end of March. Consumers
attracted by them pushed their buying plans into March, in effect
borrowing sales from later months.
   This year, the situation was reversed. Anticipation of big
incentives began growing in March, prompting some car buyers to
delay purchase plans until they were announced.
   Despite the increase in early April numbers, car and truck sales
through April 10 this year were running 5 percent behind last year,
the second-best in the industry's history. For months, company
executives and analysts have been predicting that sales in 1989
would be lower than 1988.
   Car sales for the year so far were down 7.1 percent and truck
sales were off 1.1 percent.
   Merlis of Morgan Stanley predicted that mid- and late-April
sales figures may not be as strong as the ones reported Thursday.
   ``But it will still be a scenario that it was much better than
generally expected,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
