<FIRST>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     04-14 0272</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0286</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Down, Gold Little Changed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar firmed against European currencies
today in quiet trading while the market awaited the release of two
important economic indicators.
   Gold prices retreated after gaining nearly a dollar in Hong Kong.
   European traders reported thin activity this morning as the
market awaited release of data on the U.S. trade deficit and
producer prices.
   In Tokyo, where markets closed before London trading begins, the
dollar slipped 0.35 yen to a closing 132.45. Later, in London, the
dollar traded at 132.55 yen.
   Demand for the dollar remained strong, said Takamas Yamasaki, a
trader for the Daiwa Bank in Tokyo.
   ``Although there are uncertainties over the political and
economic situation here and abroad, investors are inclined to buy
the dollar,'' he said.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday's
prices, included: 1.8780 West German marks, up from 1.8720; 1.6525
Swiss francs, up from 1.6422; 6.3520 French francs, up from 6.3335;
2.1183 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1080; 1,377.75 Italian lire, up
from 1,374.00; and 1.1868 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1875.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.6945, compared to late
Thursday's $1.7010.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $389.50 a troy ounce, up
from $388.75 bid late Thursday. At midmorning, the city's five
major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of $388.55.
   In Zurich, the bid price at noon was $388.50, down from $389.15
bid late Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose 92 cents to close at a bid
$388.46.
   Silver was quoted in London at a bid price of $5.87 a troy
ounce, unchanged from Thursday.
</TEXT>
