<DOCNO> AP890414-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0748EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     04-14 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls Against Yen, Stocks Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell today against the Japanese
yen, while stock prices rebounded after an early setback.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average,
which shed 192.51 points Thursday, regained 86.50 points, or 0.26
percent, finishing the week at 33,150.44.
   The dollar ended trading at 132.45 yen, down 0.35 yen from
Thursday's 132.80-yen finish. The currency opened lower at 132.00
yen and ranged from 131.92 to 132.53 yen during the day.
   Participants were reluctant to make major moves although demand
for the dollar remained strong, said Takamasa Yamasaki of Daiwa
Bank.
   ``Although there are uncertainties over the political and
economic situation here and abroad, investors are inclined to buy
the dollar,'' he said.
   Higher interest rates in the United States have made the dollar
more attractive to currency investors in Tokyo.
   Today's trading was thin because there was no market-affecting
news prior to U.S. trade figures for February and producer prices
for March due to be released later in the day, Yamasaki said.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index declined 138.67 points by
the end of the morning session, but then reversed directions and
gained ground in the afternoon as institutional investors began
buying cheaper issues, said Kenji Ishizuka, a dealer for Daiwa
Securities.
   ``In the early session, participants either remained on the
sidelines, or sold issues for profit-taking,'' he said.
   With the upcoming weekend and announcement of U.S. economic
figures, market players avoided major moves, Ishizuka said.
   Reports linking Shintaro Abe, secretary-general of the ruling
Liberal Democratic Party, to the company at the center of a
widening stock-profiteering and bribery scandal also discouraged
participants during the morning session, Ishizuka said.
   Abe admitted that his wife had been paid $2,300 a month in
consulting fees by Recruit Co., the firm at the heart of the
scandal, for two years and seven months.
   Volume traded on the market's first section was estimated at 650
million shares, down from Thursday's 850 million.
</TEXT>
