<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0944EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-PlumCreek     04-14 0336</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Plum Creek,0348</SECOND>
<HEAD>Burlington Resources To Spin Off Plum Creek Timber Subsidiary</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Burlington Resources Inc., which itself was spun
off from Burlington Northern Inc. last year, says it plans to
divest its timber and wood products operation, Plum Creek Timber Co.
   Burlington Resources said Plum Creek Timber Co. L.P., a master
limited partnership, registered with the Securities and Exchange
Commission for an initial public offering, with proceeds to be used
to acquire and run Plum Creek.
   Plum Creek has approximately 1.4 million acres of timberland and
about 9.6 billion board feet of salable softwood timber in the
Pacific Northwest. It employs about 1,800 people in Washington,
Idaho and Montana, and in 1988 had profits of $57.4 million on
revenues of $332.8 million.
   In a news release Thursday, Burlington Resources said the
current management of Plum Creek would remain in place and that no
changes in employment levels would result from the establishment of
the partnership.
   In its registration statement with the SEC, the partnership
seeks an initial public offering of 12.35 million depositary units,
each with a proposed maximum offering price of $20.50. The units
represent an 88 percent interest in the limited partnership.
   The combined acquisition price is expected to be about $575
million.
   Immediately before completing the public offering, the
partnership and its 95 percent-owned subsidiary, Plum Creek
Manufacturing Inc., would borrow about $325 million, which, with
the proceeds of the offering, would be used to buy Plum Creek.
   Burlington Resources will keep a 12 percent interest in the
partnership, along with some of Plum Creek's existing assets.
   Burlington Resources said its decision to divest Plum Creek was
consistent with its plans to concentrate on its gas, oil and
natural gas pipeline businesses.
   Last year, Burlington Northern spun off Burlington Resources as
a separate company encompassing Burlington's oil, mineral, timber
and pipeline segments. Burlington Northern kept the Burlington
Northern Railroad.
   For 1988, Burlington Resources had net income of $72.1 million
or 46 cents a share on revenues of $2.17 billion.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
