<FIRST>u f PM-Earns-IBM     04-14 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Earns-IBM,0247</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Earnings Rise 1.8 Percent Excluding Accounting Change</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. said today
its profit rose 1.8 percent in the first quarter excluding the
effect of an accounting change that had swelled earnings in 1988.
   The world's biggest computer company said it earned $950 million
in the three months ended March 31. IBM earned $933 million a year
earlier from normal operations, but final net income in 1988 was
$1.25 billion after inclusion of a $315 million gain from the
accounting change.
   Including the effect of the one-time gain in 1988, net income
fell 23.9 percent. The accounting change related to the treatment
of deferred taxes.
   Earnings per share were $1.61. That was up from $1.57 in 1988
before the accounting change, but down from the $2.10 recorded
after the accounting change.
   Revenue rose 5.6 percent to $12.7 billion from $12.06 billion.
   IBM stock was up $1.50 a share to $110.75 in New York Stock
Exchange trading shortly after the announcement. The stock fell
last month after the company warned that a problem with chips had
delayed shipments of some of its big mainframe computers.
   ``IBM's product and service offerings continue to grow stronger,
and we are benefiting from our improving customer partnerships as
well as our restructuring actions,'' John F. Akers, the chairman
and chief executive, said in a statement.
   ``Our expectations for 1989 remain unchanged,'' Akers said.
</TEXT>
