<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1115EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WholesalePrices 3rdLd-Writethru   04-14 0907</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wholesale Prices, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0932</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wholesale Prices Up Moderate 0.4 Percent in March</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, The overall, with 2 grafs to update with Wall
Street trading, INSERTS 2 grafs after 7th graf pvs, Financial markets;
to UPDATE with market reaction and comment; SUBS 5 grafs for grafs 13-14,
The troubling, to UPDATE with other economic reports today; DELETES last
4 grafs to shorten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NANCY BENAC</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wholesale prices, despite a big jump in home
heating oil costs, rose a moderate 0.4 percent in March as
inflation eased somewhat after steep increases of 1 percent in each
of the previous two months, the government said today.
   The boost in the Labor Department's Producer Price Index
reflected higher costs for both food and energy, although the
increases in both categories were smaller than those registered in
the first two months of the year.
   The overall gain was close to analysts' expectations and helped
calm Wall Street's inflation fears, causing a sharp rally in early
trading today.
   The stock market staged a sharp rally, encouraged by the
apparent easing of inflationary pressures. The Dow Jones average of
30 industrials climbed 21.45 to 2,317.45 in the first half hour of
trading.
   While March's increase was much more restrained than the strong
jumps of the previous two months, wholesale prices one stop short
of retail have risen at a compound annual rate of 10.2 percent over
the past three months.
   That is the largest quarterly increase since prices rose at a
compound annual rate of 13.2 percent during the first three months
of 1981.
   Should the first quarter's rate be sustained for the rest of the
year, it would far exceed the increase registered for 1988, when
wholesale prices rose 4 percent in what was the steepest gain in
seven years. Prices had risen 2.2 percent in 1987.
   Financial markets had been fearful that further bad news on the
inflation front would prompt the Federal Reserve Board to step up
its campaign to slow economic growth and restrain inflationary
pressures by pushing up interest rates.
   Dirk Van Dongen, president of the National Association of
Wholesaler-Distributors, said the latest report was good news but
doesn't totally put to rest worries about accelerating inflation.
   ``I don't think at all that this suggests that the inflation
watch should be terminated,'' he said. ``I don't think this battle
is over.''
   Wholesale food prices rose 0.8 percent last month after jumping
1.2 percent during February. Last month's increase in food costs
was led by a 38.8 percent gain in prices for eggs while vegetable
costs dropped 11.6 percent after surging 35.3 percent during
February.
   Energy prices, meanwhile, rose 0.9 percent in March following a
2.4 percent increase during the previous month. Last month's
increase was led by a 16.8 percent rise in home heating oil prices,
while gasoline costs rose 3.5 percent and natural gas prices
declined 5.4 percent.
   Excluding the volatile food and energy categories, prices rose
0.3 percent in March, down from a 0.6 percent increase a month
earlier.
   The overall March increase left the Producer Price Index for
finished goods at 112.2, meaning that a hypothetical selection of
goods costing $100 in 1982 would have cost $112.20 last month.
   That was up 50 cents from February and 5.6 percent above March
1988.
   The troubling inflation reports at the start of 1989 had come
even as signs emerge that the economy is cooling off in response to
the Fed's anti-inflation campaign.
   Three other government reports released today added to growing
evidence that the economy is slowing down:
   _The U.S. merchandise trade deficit swelled by 20.9 percent to
$10.5 billion in February as Americans increased their appetite for
foreign goods, the Commerce Department reported.
   _The operating rate for U.S. factories declined for the second
consecutive month in March to 84 percent, the first back-to-back
declines in nearly three years, the Federal Reserve Board said.
   _Business inventories rose 0.5 percent in February while sales
plunged 0.9 percent, the steepest decline in more than two years,
Commerce reported.
   Allen Sinai, chief economist for the Boston Co., said in advance
of today's reports that while the economy does seem to be losing
steam, it may take awhile for that to translate into inflation
relief.
   ``There is a tendency to expect inflation to weaken as soon as
the economy starts to slow, but more often than not it doesn't
happen that way,'' Sinai said. ``More often than not, it takes a
weak economy for quite some time before inflation begins to peak
and then drop.''
   Despite the moderate price hikes last month for finished goods
such as bread and clothing, the index for prices at earlier stages
of production demonstrated stronger inflation.
   Prices at the intermediate level for items such as flour and
cloth rose 0.7 percent, while the cost of crude goods such as
cotton and wheat was up 2.3 percent.
   March's figures on increases in consumer prices, which so far
this year have been smaller than those at the wholesale level, will
be released on Tuesday. The Consumer Price Index rose 0.4 percent
in February and 0.6 percent in January.
   Sinai and many others are forecasting a mild recession by the
first half of 1990, but other analysts still are hopeful that the
Fed can slow the economy just enough to restrain inflation and
produce a ``soft landing'' in which growth slows but the economy
avoids an outright downturn.
</TEXT>
