<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   04-14 0305</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0318</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dry Weather Fears Boost Crop Futures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices rose modestly
this morning on the Chicago Board of Trade, boosted by perceptions
of continuing dry weather in some of the nation's major
crop-growing areas.
   Many private meteorologists are predicting another month of
dryer-than-normal conditions in the Midwest and Great Plains.
   Those forecasts contradict a National Weather Service 30-day
outlook issued Thursday afternoon, which called for normal
precipitation in most growing areas.
   But traders are paying more attention to actual precipitation
levels, which are well below normal for this time of year in
Illinois and Iowa, two major corn and soybean states hit hard by
last year's drought.
   ``People are talking dry weather for the most part,'' said
Victor Lespinasse, a trader in Chicago with Dean Witter Reynolds
Inc.
   The National Weather Service will issue a new 6-to-10-day
outlook this afternoon.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent lower to 1 cent higher with
the contract for delivery in May at $4.09 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 1{ cents higher with May at $2.69\ a bushel; oats were
1{ cents to 2{ cents higher with May at $1.85{ a bushel; soybeans
were 1 cent to 7 cents higher with May at $7.28 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mixed and pork futures were higher in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were unchanged to .20 cent higher with June at 71.15
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .30 cent lower to .33 cent higher
with May at 75.90 cents a pound; live hogs were .17 cent to .27
cent higher with June at 46.07 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .10 cent to .20 cent higher with May at 33.45 cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mixed on Thursday.
</TEXT>
