<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1248EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Bonds     04-14 0535</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bonds,0556</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bond Prices Rebound On Spate of Economic Reports</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bond prices rebounded sharply in heavy trading
today following several government reports suggesting an easing of
inflationary pressures.
   The Treasury's bellwether 30-year issue jumped 1 3-16 point, or
about $12 for every $1,000 in face amount, as its yield, which
moves inversely to price, fell to 9.03 percent from 9.15 percent
late Thursday.
   The Labor Department reported that the producer price index of
finished goods rose 0.4 percent in March _ better than the 0.5
percent many had expected. The index, which measures inflation at
the wholesale level, had increased 1 percent in each of the two
previous months.
   ``The worst fears that some market observers had expressed
regarding the possibility of a big increase in the producer price
index were soundly refuted,'' said Marshall B. Front, economist at
the Chicago investment and mutual-fund management firm of Stein Roe
&amp; Farnham.
   The government also said the U.S. merchandise trade deficit for
February widened by 20.9 percent to $10.5 billion from January's
$8.98 billion.
   And the government reported a 0.2 percent decline in the
operating rate for U.S. factories last month to 84 percent, the
second consecutive monthly decline. Business inventories rose 0.5
percent in February while sales plunged 0.9 percent in their
steepest decline in more than two years, the government said.
   The reports were consistent with expectations, analysts said,
and fit in with other evidence of slower growth, including
lackluster retail sales and a slackening of employment growth in
March.
   ``Other concerns about rising inflation and the possibility of
the Fed tightening seem to be less of a reality than before these
figures were released,'' Front said.
   Inflation and high interest rates erode the value of
fixed-income securities such as bonds.
   In the secondary market for Treasury bonds, prices of short-term
notes were up between 13-32 and 17-32 point, intermediate issues
were } point to 27-32 point higher and long-term issues rose as
much as 1 1-32 point, according to Telerate Inc., a financial
reporting service.
   The movement of a point equals a $10 change in the price of a
bond with a $1,000 face value.
   The Shearson Lehman Hutton Daily Treasury Bond Index, which
measures price movements on all outstanding Treasury issues with
maturities of a year or longer, jumped 6.94 to 1,125.23.
   In corporate trading, prices also advanced. Moody's Investment
Grade Corporate Bond Index, which measures price movements on 80
corporate bonds with maturities of five years or longer, rose 0.88
to 300.02.
   Yields on three-month Treasury bills, meanwhile, declined to
8.89, while the discount fell 17 basis points to 8.59 percent.
Yields on six-month bills declined to 9.16 percent as the discount
also dropped 17 basis points to 8.67 percent. Yields on one-year
bills fell to 9.35 percent as the discount lost 19 basis points to
8.63 percent.
   A basis point is one-hundredth of a percentage point. The yield
is the annualized return on an investment in a Treasury bill. The
discount is the percentage that bills are selling below the face
value, paid at maturity.
   The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between
banks, remained at 913-16 percent, the same as late Thursday.
</TEXT>
