<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Brokers     04-14 0270</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Brokers,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Quarter Earnings Drop At Merrill Lynch</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   First-quarter profits at Merrill Lynch &amp; Co.
plunged 46 percent despite a 25 percent jump in revenue as the
nation's largest brokerage continued to be plagued by a weak
business environment.
   For the period ended March 31, Merrill reported net earnings of
$37.2 million, or 31 cents a share, down from $68.3 million, or 62
cents a share in the year-ago period.
   Revenue during the quarter jumped to $3 billion from $2.4
billion in the first quarter of 1988, primarily due to a 60 percent
increase in interest and dividend revenue. The company noted that
exclusive of these increases, however, revenue increased just 5
percent.
   ``These results reflect the continuing weakness in the market
environment for many of our core business activities,'' said
Merrill Chairman William A. Schryer.
   But he noted that ``a strong capital base, growing client assets
... diversification of businesses and gains in institutional market
share'' will help Merrill ``prosper when market conditions
improve.''
   Merger and acquisition advisory services and corporate bond
underwritings boosted investment banking revenues by 10 percent to
$248 million, although a decline in equity underwritings partly
offset the gain.
   Asset management and custodial fee revenue rose along with
insurance revenue and real estate revenues generated by Fine Homes
International. But commission revenue declined 5 percent to $417
million because of a continued lull in stock trading volume.
Principal transaction revenue also declined, down 15 percent to
$348 million.
   At the end of the quarter, Merrill reported $290 billion in
total customer assets, up 15 percent from the year-ago period.
</TEXT>
