<FIRST>u f PM-HollyFarms 1stLd-Writethru   04-14 0420</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Holly Farms, 1st Ld-Writethru,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holly Shareholders Consider ConAgra Merger</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with vote taken, meeting adjourned till Monday.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shareholders of Holly Farms Corp. voted
today on the poultry processor's proposed $1.1 billion merger with
ConAgra Inc., but the results of the ballot were not expected to be
known until Monday.
   Shareholders met at a Memphis hotel to consider the ConAgra
proposal, which is backed by Holly Farms management. ConAgra
shareholders were scheduled to vote on the proposal later in the
day in Omaha, where that company is headquartered.
   After the Holly Farms vote was taken, officials adjourned the
meeting until Monday.
   ConAgra has threatened court action if parts of a merger
agreement reached with Holly Farms last November are not honored.
   However, Tyson Foods Inc., the rival poultry processor that has
tried since last October to take over Holly Farms, has vowed to
continue its court fight to block the proposed merger with ConAgra.
   Tyson, headquartered in Springdale, Ark., has made a cash offer
of $63.50 a share to Holly Farms stockholders for a deal worth
about $1.15 billion. Buying Holly Farms would permit Tyson to
remain the largest poultry processor in the country.
   The proposed ConAgra-Holly Farms merger calls for a stock swap
valued at $60 a share for Holly Farms stockholders. Holly Farms
shareholders would get 1.875 shares of ConAgra stock for each share
of Holly Farms stock traded.
   A major point of argument in the ConAgra-Holly Farms proposal is
a provision allowing ConAgra to purchase major Holly Farms assets
should the merger fall through.
   Tyson has filed suit in Chancery Court in Delaware attacking the
provision as an unfair attempt to block a buyout by anyone else.
The judge handling the suit has said the so-called ``asset-option
agreement'' appears to be unenforcable and has issued a temporary
injunction blocking it.
   Under the agreement, ConAgra would be allowed to buy Holly Farms
subsidiary Harker's Inc. of LeMars, Iowa, for $148.8 million, Holly
Farms of Texas Inc. for a like amount and Holly Farms facilities in
Wilkesboro, N.C., for $127.5 million.
   Those purchases would cover some 34 percent of Holly Farms'
total assets.
   Meanwhile, executives of Tyson Foods entertained shareholders of
Holly Farms Thursday night, a day before the critical vote.
   Don Tyson, president of the Arkansas firm, made a formal pitch
today to the shareholders.
   Prior to the meeting of Holly shareholders, Tyson said it had
been tendered more than 10 million, or about 55 percent, of Holly's
18.4 million shares.
</TEXT>
