<DOCNO> AP890414-0267 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1449EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Media     04-14 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Media,0389</SECOND>
<HEAD>Time's Earnings Off 26 Percent, Pulitzer Publishing Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Time Inc. said Friday its first-quarter profit tumbled 26
percent due to lower operating earnings from its magazines, heavier
interest expenses and costs related to its pending merger with
Warner Communications Inc.
   Another media company, Pulitzer Publishing Co., said its
first-quarter earnings rose 23.2 percent as its interest expenses
fell.
   New York-based Time said it earned $49 million, or 87 cents a
share, in the three months ended March 31, compared with $66
million, or $1.13 a share, a year earlier.
   First-quarter revenue rose 6.7 percent to $1.14 billion from
$1.07 billion in 1988.
   Time said operating income from its magazine segment fell to $61
million from $70 million in 1988 despite a 7 percent rise in
magazine revenue.
   The revenue increases, due mainly to strong circulation at
Sports Illustrated and People, were more than offset by higher
print order expenses, including those for the newly-launched Sports
Illustrated for Kids.
   The books segment operated at break-even for the quarter, the
same as a year earlier, while operating income from programming,
which includes the Home Box Office Inc. pay-TV services and HBO
Video, rose 5.1 percent.
   Time's operating profit from its interest in the cable TV
operator American Television and Communications Corp. rose 31
percent to $55 million.
   Time said its corporate interest expenses rose $10 million,
reflecting higher debt resulting from its purchase of a
half-interest in the media concern Whittle Communications LP and
ATC's investment in a Memphis cable system.
   In addition, Time said it incurred $15 million in costs relating
to its proposed merger with Warner Communications. The merger,
which Time hopes will be completed by fall, would create the
world's largest media and entertainmnet concern with revenue of
about $10 billion a year.
   Pulitzer, based in St. Louis, said it earned $3.1 million, or 29
cents per share, in the first quarter, up from $2.5 million, or 24
cents a share, a year earlier.
   First-quarter revenue rose 3.9 percent to $94.1 million from
$90.5 million in 1988.
   Pulitzer has interests in newspaper publishing including the St.
Louis Post-Dispatch and The Arizona Daily Star in Tuscon, Ariz.,
and owns seven network-affiliated television stations and two radio
stations.
</TEXT>
