<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru   04-14 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0334</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Stocks Rise, Buoyed By Wall Street Rally</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES throughout with close.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices rosel sharply on the London Stock Exchange
Friday, boosted by an early rally on Wall Street and by the release
of a series of favorable U.S. and British economic data.
   Shares began rising strongly in the afternoon, after trading
tentatively through the morning. The day's gains ended a string of
lackluster sessions this week as participants nervously awaited
Friday's key economic statistics.
   At the close the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index
was up 24.9, or 1.22 percent at 2053.6, its best level of the day.
   For the week, the index moved up 7.9 points.
   Volume, at 648.1 million shares, was brisk by recent standards,
but this was inflated by a substantial program trade around midday,
dealers said. On Thursday, volume totaled 464.3 million shares.
   The market's first boost came with the news that British retail
prices rose 7.9 percent in March from the previous year, in line
with economists' forecasts. Inflation fears have weighed heavily on
the market in recent weeks, and there were fears Friday's retail
price data could have been worse.
   The market was reassured further with the release of U.S.
statistics that also conformed to, or slightly bettered,
expectations. The data showed that U.S. producer prices rose 0.4
percent in March, copared with 1-percent rises in each of the two
preceding months.
   Also, the U.S. trade deficit widened in February to $10.5
billion from a revised $8.68 billion in January.
   ``The figures were quite good today,'' said one dealer. ``The
market seems to want to go higher.''
   Equities continued to advance after Wall Street opened strongly
higher. The Dow Jones industrial average was up 33 points at the
time of the London close.
   Dealers said the London market also was encouraged by news that
President Bush had worked out an agreement with Congress on the
fiscal 1990 budget.
</TEXT>
