<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern 1stLd-Writethru   04-14 0673</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern, 1st Ld-Writethru,0692</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pritzker Participates in Eastern Airlines Meeting</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New info and editing throughout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sources said billionaire hotelier Jay Pritzker
joined the wrangling for Eastern Airlines today in a meeting laden
with uncertainty following the failed deal to peddle the
strike-dogged carrier to former baseball boss Peter Ueberroth.
   The sources close to the situation said Pritzker, who reportedly
has offered $500 million for Eastern, was among those attending a
meeting of lawyers for creditors, the unions and the airline's
management at a Manhattan law firm. The sources asked not to be
identified.
   Pritzker, owner of the Hyatt hotel chain, had been interested in
buying Eastern but withdrew after Ueberroth announced his agreement
to buy it April 6. The deal collapsed Wednesday because of an
intractable dispute over whether an outsider would run the airline
until his group could assume control.
   Eastern's unions have been on strike since March 4 and the
moneylosing airline has been under federal bankruptcy court
protection since March 9.
   The unions have insisted that Frank Lorenzo, head of parent
company Texas Air Corp., surrender management authority to a
court-appointed outsider no matter what happens to Eastern.
   On Thursday, Lorenzo said he is turning attention to his plan to
reorganize Eastern as a much smaller airline.
   In Miami, meanwhile, American Airlines chief Robert Crandall
said American is interested in such Eastern assets as its Latin
American and Canadian routes. American, one of Eastern's leading
rivals, already is expanding to capitalize on the embattled
carrier's problems.
   While Lorenzo seemed to rule out the possibility of a sale,
federal bankruptcy judge Burton Lifland moved late Wednesday to
lure other buyers _ raising the possibility of an auction
supervised by his court.
   And some union leaders at Eastern insisted that Lorenzo's deal
with the former baseball commissioner could still be revived.
   ``Anyone familiar with these situations will tell you that deals
get done and undone many times, almost with predictable regularity,
before being finalized,'' Jack Bavis, head of the pilots union at
Eastern, said Thursday. ``We believe that Mr. Ueberroth is not
totally out of the picture yet, and there are other potential
players as well.''
   Eastern Machinists leader Charles Bryan, in a speech today in
Fort Lauderdale, Fla., said Ueberroth had called him this morning.
Bryan wouldn't disclose the nature of the call but said he doesn't
consider Ueberroth out of the game.
   In addition to Ueberroth and Pritzker, another potential suitor
is takeover strategist Carl Icahn, owner and chairman of Trans
World Airlines Inc., who said Wednesday he is still interested in a
possible bid for Eastern.
   Under Lorenzo's new plan, Eastern ``will be a lot smaller,''
said the chairman of Eastern's parent Texas Air Corp. However, he
asserted, ``We are not going to have any difficulty over time
building back.''
   At a separate speaking engagement, Ueberroth said in response to
a question on the Eastern situation, ``We're out of there, for
sure.''
   The former Olympics organizer said he had not been in touch with
any of the parties involved, including Lorenzo, Texas Air and
bankruptcy court officials. He would not try to get in touch with
them and did not expect to hear from them, Ueberroth told a
reporter after his speech on sports issues.
   ``The deal is now dead and there are no further negotiations
because we're not prepared to turn over interim control of the
company'' to a court-appointed trustee, the Texas Air chief said.
The trustee was a condition Eastern's unions demanded before they
would accept Ueberroth's bid.
   The statements by Ueberroth and Lorenzo came a day after they
announced their deal had fallen apart, thwarting efforts to restore
Eastern to a full flight schedule.
   Lifland immediately ordered the parties in the case to explain
on Monday why he shouldn't invite other bids for Eastern that would
include major assets it owned before Lorenzo bought the airline in
1986.
   The judge's move could put pressure on Lorenzo to revive his
deal with Ueberroth.
</TEXT>
