<FIRST>u f PM-LincolnSavings 1stLd-Writethru   04-14 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lincoln Savings, 1st Ld-Writethru,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Lincoln Savings and Loan Placed in Conservatorship</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 4th graf to CORRECT name of spokeswoman.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lincoln Savings and Loan Association,
which has been up for sale while its Arizona-based parent prepared
to file for bankruptcy protection, was seized by federal regulators
today.
   The action against the 29-branch S&amp;L was taken ``on the legal
grounds that the institution's assets had been substantially
dissipated and that it was operating in an unsafe and unsound
condition,'' according to a news release issued by the Federal Home
Loan Bank Board.
   On Thursday, the American Continental Corp., the luxury resort
developer that owns Lincoln, announced in Phoenix, Ariz., it was
seeking federal bankruptcy protection.
   Martha Gravlee, a spokeswoman for the bank board, said business
was being conducted as usual at all Lincoln branches. She said
representatives from the bank board, the Federal Savings and Loan
Insurance Corp. and Federal Deposit Insurance Corp. were in the
administrative offices here and in Los Angeles.
   But aside from a sign on the door, there was no noticeable
change in operations, she said.
   The FSLIC will act as conservator and the FDIC will provide a
managing agent to oversee the association's operations.
   F. Roger Clark was appointed by the bank board to serve as chief
executive officer. John H. Rousselot, named Lincoln's chairman and
chief executive officer on Tuesday, resigned those posts today.
   Rousselot led a group of investors negotiating to buy the
savings and loan, which lost $36 million in the first nine months
of 1988, but their offer was turned down because it failed to
include enough cash.
   ``Management appeared to operate Lincoln mainly for the benefit
of American Continental Corp. at the expense of the institution,
has repeatedly violated regulations relating to transactions with
affiliates, used poor underwriting and has refused to follow
supervisory directives,'' the bank board statement said.
   Lincoln Savings operates 29 branches in Southern California. The
association has $5.4 billion in assets, $5.1 billion in liabilities
and $20 million in regulatory capital, the bank board said. As of
mid-1988, it was the state's 18th-largest thrift measured by assets.
   The bank board said Lincoln's financial troubles started in
February 1984 when it was bought by American Continental.
   ``Management abandoned the thrift's traditional operations to
pursue a rapid growth strategy based on soliticing brokered
deposits to purchase real estate and to fund high risk acquisition,
development and construction loans, equity securities and junk
bonds,'' the bank board said.
   American Continental Chairman Charles H. Keating said Thursday
the bank board had changed rules as his company tried to sell
Lincoln and finally demanded that the company yield control of
Lincoln to the FSLIC.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
