<DOCNO> AP890414-0272 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0023EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-PenneyQuality Adv16   04-14 0499</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Penney Quality, Adv 16,0516</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, April 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>Penney's Scrupulous Testers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-Pretty Penney</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARYBETH NIBLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a sprawling warehouse-like building,
Jerry Oleksiw presides over machines that simulate sweat, test-rip
bluejeans and generally perform the industrial equivalent of trying
to gauge how many angels can dance on the head of a pin.
   Oleksiw recently recounted what he called a perplexing incident
at the J.C. Penney Co. Quality Assurance Center, set in an
industrial park on the outskirts of Dallas.
   Pink plastic bags containing ladies' imported raincoats had left
a residue of a powdery pink substance on the garments.
   Penney inspectors went to work, knowing that if any of the
30,000 coats reached customers in that condition the company's
reputation could be soiled. Their first thought was dry cleaning
but _ oops _ the cleaning chemicals damaged the water-resistant
fabric coating.
   Plan B went into action. All the coats would have to be
laundered and pressed. Little labels would have to be sewn inside
advising proper care.
   Such is a typical headache for an arbiter of quality standards.
   ``To many suppliers, this place is known as the graveyard of
many hopes,'' said Oleksiw, manager of quality assurance and
product service for J.C. Penney and a 28-year veteran of the
retailer.
   Members of his domain include white-coated laboratory
technicians who measure almost every conceivable thing that can go
wrong or wear out.
   They stretch and tug jeans to the ripping point. They plunge
boots into a sub-freezing chamber to simulate winter's worst. They
suck oil out of shoe leather, toast toast in toasters and zap food
in microwaves.
   There are devices to duplicate everyday conditions that can
cause problems for clothing, appliances and other goods. Simulated
sweat and fake pollution are just two of the hazards these testers
throw at merchandise guinea pigs.
   One machine has been designed to measure the durability of
clothing material in an unprecedented way, Oleksiw said during a
tour. It could be said to place Penney on the cutting edge of
fabric tearing.
   Elsewhere, overall-clad mechanics scrutinize gardening tools and
other gear. They've rigged a strobe light to calculate how fast the
tip of a lawn mower blade spins, because a federal safety
regulation requires blades to rotate less than 19,000 feet per
minute.
   Outside, a lush acre of fescue and Bermuda grass stands ready to
put the mowers through their paces.
   Much of the work that goes on here duplicates testing done by
manufacturers. Penney has developed a reputation in the retail
industry for being unusually scrupulous about testing, outside
analysts say.
   The quality control center is due to move to Plano, Texas, in
late 1992, when Penney's corporate offices are scheduled to leave
intermim headquarters in Dallas to take up residence at a new
429-acre site. There will be plenty of grass for lawn mowers to mow
and a pond with ducks to feed the toast.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Sunday, April 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890414-0273 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0733EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-PrettyPenney-History Adv16   04-14 0484</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Pretty Penney-History, Adv 16,0511</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Sunday, April 16</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are key years in the evolution of J.C. Penney Co. as a
leading U.S. retailer:
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   1902 _ James Cash Penney, 26, opens The Golden Rule, a clothing
store in mining town of Kemmerer, Wyo., in partnership with his
former employers, merchants Thomas. M. Callahan and William G.
Johnson. Suspenders cost 5 cents and petticoats 29 cents.
   1907 _ Callahan and Johnson sell their interest in what has
become a 3-store Golden Rule chain in Wyoming. Penney recruits
former sales clerks for new partners to expand.
   1908 _ Penney and partners open Golden Rule stores in Bingham
Canyon, Utah and Preston, Idaho, their first out-of-state expansion.
   1909 _ Penney moves to Salt Lake City to coordinate buying and
financing. 1911 _ Sales of Penney's 22 stores exceed $1 million for
the first time.
   1913 _ The J.C. Penney Co. is incorporated in Utah with 36
stores. ``The Penney Idea,'' seven principles the company says are
guidelines to this day, are formulated.
   1914 _ At Penney's urging, company's offices are moved to New
York to facilitate buying, financing and transporting goods.
   1916 _ First stores are opened east of the Mississippi River.
   1917 _ Penney becomes chairman of what has become a 175-store
chain.
   1924 _ With more than 370 stores in 27 states, Penney
reincorporates as a Delaware corporation and sets strict
manufacturing specifications for company brand names, which range
from Big Mac work shirts to Lady Lyke lingerie.
   1926 _ Company opens an 18-story office and warehouse in New
York. Newspapers proclaim Penney is ``the world's largest
department store chain.''
   1930 _ Now a 1,452-store chain, Penney's cuts inventories and
purchases goods at lower prices to adapt to Depression era.
   1931-36 _ Penney profits rise despite Depression. Sales over
$250 million in 1936.
   1942-46 _ Penney's stores sell record volume of war bonds.
Expansion in sales and store numbers continues.
   1951 _ Penney sales top $1 billion.
   1963 _ First Penney catalog is issued.
   1964 _ New 45-story office tower built in New York. Annual sales
exceed $2 billion.
   1966 _ Penney moves into insurance business by acquiring two
companies.
   1971 _ James Cash Penney dies on Feb. 12 at age 95. Catalog
operation goes into the black for the first time.
   1979-80 _ Catalog service is nationwide. Annual retail and
catalog sales at $11.4 billion.
   1982-83 _ Penney changes strategy to emphasize fashions and
discontinue some merchandise and services, such as auto care and
paints.
   1987 _ Penney moves corporate headquarters to Dallas area and
further narrows merchandising focus, dropping home electronics,
hard sporting goods and photographic equipment to make more room
for more women's apparel.
   1988 _ Penney's store and catalog sales about $14 billion.
One-third of 1,700 stores get revamped with rest due for change by
1990.
   End adv for Sunday, April 16
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890414-0274 </DOCNO>
