<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   04-14 0237</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0246</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dry Weather Fears Drive Crop Futures Up Sharply</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fears that drought conditions could persist for
another year in the Midwest drove grain and soybean futures up
sharply Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Despite the fact that spring planting of corn and soybeans has
not yet begun, bullish speculators seized controlled the futures
markets for those crops amid news reports of below-normal
springtime precipitation in some western Corn Belt states.
   ``Iowa is the real problem,'' said Cathy Leow, a grain-market
analyst in New York with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. ``During
the past month or so, they've only had about 50 percent of normal
precipitation.''
   States east of the Mississippi River have fared much better,
though, and some analysts said traders were simply looking for an
excuse to bid prices higher.
   The wheat market gained on rumors that the United States will
offer to sell the Soviet Union more wheat at subsidized prices,
although Agriculture Department officials said no such decision had
been made.
   At the close, wheat was 1{ cents to 3} cents higher with the
contract for delivery in May at $4.12{ a bushel; corn was 2\ cents
to 4} cents higher with May at $2.71 a bushel; oats were 5{ cents
to 7{ cents higher with May at $1.91{ a bushel; soybeans were 4}
cents to 10 cents higher with May at $7.32{ a bushel.
 
</TEXT>
