<DOCNO> AP890414-0275 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1521EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Northwest-Battle Bjt   04-14 0935</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Northwest-Battle, Bjt,0959</SECOND>
<HEAD>CEO Rothmeier Tackling Job Of Keeping Northwest Independent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY KENNEDY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It may not have the glitz of the Eastern
Airlines saga, but the battle for control of Northwest Airlines is
every bit as bitter and much more expensive.
   A $2.6 billion offer already has been made _ and rejected _ for
NWA Inc., parent of the nation's fourth-largest airline, and
several more potential suitors are waiting in the wings amid
speculation the bidding will top $3 billion.
   While the Eastern story features such names as former baseball
commissioner Peter Ueberroth, former defense secretary Frank
Carlucci and Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo, the Northwest
cast includes oil and movie mogul Marvin Davis and Nixon White
House staffer Frederick Malek, among others.
   The primary shark circling Northwest has been Davis, the former
owner of 20th Century Fox Film Corp. who made his fortune
``wildcatting'' in oil and is worth an estimated $1.6 billion.
Davis' proposed board of directors for Northwest includes Audrey
Meadows Six, who played Alice Kramden on the Honeymooners
television show.
   Leading the charge for Northwest, the nation's fourth-largest
air carrier, is its 42-year-old Chairman Steven Rothmeier, a former
Notre Dame fullback and Army lieutenant in Vietnam who gives ground
grudgingly if at all.
   The dollars in the Northwest deal dwarf those offered for
Eastern, which is ranked seventh among air carriers. Ueberroth led
a $464 million bid to acquire Eastern from its parent Texas Air.
   While Davis and Northwest battle toe to toe, other investment
groups await an opening.
   One group, Wesray Capital Corp., was founded by former Treasury
Secretary William Simon. The other, which Northwest has said holds
4.9 percent of its 29.1 million shares, includes Gary L. Wilson, a
Walt Disney Co. executive who left Northwest's board in November;
Al Checchi, a former associate of the wealthy Bass family of Fort
Worth, Texas, and Malek, who also was a campaign adviser to
President Bush.
   The crowd eyeing Northwest and its asset-rich balance sheet have
swung the odds against Rothmeier's efforts to keep the airline
independent.
   No less an authority on hostile takeovers than Minneapolis
financier Irwin Jacobs, a friend of Rothmeier, says the airline is
``definitely in danger'' of a takeover.
   ``Northwest has a lot of honey and Marvin Davis is only the
first bee,'' said Kurt Rivard, an analyst for Minneapolis-based
Dain Bosworth Inc. ``I think there will be others.''
   The honey was cured by a string of managers who hated debt and
managed conservatively. Texas Air's Lorenzo may be legendary for
his anti-union rhetoric and action, but he can't compare to a
cost-cutting predecessor of Rothmeier named Donald Nyrop, who once
removed the doors from the stalls in the men's room because he
thought executives were spending too much time reading there.
   The stingy leadership has given Northwest ownership of 222 of
its 312 airplanes, well above the industry standard. If Northwest
is sold, the new owners could sell part of the fleet and lease it
back, earning more on the planes than Northwest originally paid for
them. The revenue could be used to repay debt incurred in a
takeover.
   Also attractive to raiders are Northwest's domination of gates
at airports in the Twin Cities and Detroit, its downtown Tokyo real
estate holdings that could fetch $500 million, its rank as the
largest cargo carrier among U.S. passenger airlines and its No. 1
position in the world's fastest-growing airline market _ the
Pacific Rim.
   Rivard said there is room to expand the airline internationally
and nationally. Domestically, Northwest is strongest in the
Midwest, where Rothmeier grew up.
   Rothmeier was raised by a German-American father and
Danish-American mother in Faribault, a town of about 17,000 some 50
miles south of Minneapolis.
   His football career at Notre Dame was cut short by a knee injury
his sophomore season and he turned to business academics with such
Spartan-like intensity that he earned the nickname ``Sparty.''
   Before going on to earn an MBA at the University of Chicago, the
6-foot, 190-pound Rothmeier commanded a supply company for the Army
in Vietnam. His first job after graduation was at Northwest.
   Not known for flair, Rothmeier chose a neighborhood steak house
in St. Paul to finalize Northwest's $884 million deal to acquire
Twin Cities rival Republic Airlines in 1986. After weathering more
than a year of labor turmoil and a spate of passenger complaints
stemming from the merger, Northwest emerged with record profits for
1988 of $135.1 million, up 31 percent from 1987.
   ``When he gets up to go to the bathroom at night he probably
makes the bed,'' William Genoese, director of the airline division
of the International Brotherhood of Teamsters, said of Rothmeier's
need for order.
   Rothmeier's defense against Davis and the others so far has been
to adopt a ``poison pill'' anti-takeover defense that Davis and
dissident shareholders are challenging in court. Northwest also has
won a temporary restraining order preventing Davis from making
``disruptive'' contacts with the three labor unions representing
34,000 of NWA's 38,000 employees.
   Rothmeier is negotiating a new contract with his 5,000 pilots,
whose loyalty will be important to thwart a takeover. A negotiating
subcommittee has been formed to discuss the creation of an employee
stock ownership program, which would act as another anti-takeover
measure by putting more stock in friendly hands.
   Meanwhile, Davis has said he will spend up to $2 million to
stage a proxy fight for control of the NWA board of director at a
May 15 meeting. If he attracts enough followers he could gain
control of the board and throw Rothmeier out.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890414-0276 </DOCNO>
