<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1550EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Robins-Bankruptcy Bjt   04-14 0529</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Robins-Bankruptcy, Bjt,0545</SECOND>
<HEAD>Financial Picture Rosy For Maker Of Dalkon Shield, Even In Reorganization</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HILARY APPELMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three years after A.H. Robins Co. filed for
bankruptcy court protection in the face of thousands of claims from
women who used its Dalkon Shield birth control device, the
pharmaceutical company is still in court.
   But buoyed by sales of products like Chap Stick and Robitussin
cough medicine, Robins' earnings have soared to record levels and
its stock prices have quintupled.
   The Richmond-based company reported record sales of $933.8
million in 1988, up 9 percent from a year earlier. Its operating
earnings, $184.4 million, were also up 9 percent from 1987, giving
the company net earnings of $58.4 million, or $2.42 per share,
after accounting for bankruptcy-related expenses.
   Robins' financial success during its reorganization under
bankruptcy laws shows good management and the power of brand names,
Wilbur Ross of Rothschild Inc., financial consultants for Robins
stockholders, said Friday.
   ``The fellow buying Chap Stick doesn't really care if the parent
company is bankrupt or not,'' he said.
   Robins is currently awaiting a ruling on the appeal of its
Chapter 11 reorganization plan, which calls for it to be acquired
by American Home Products Corp. of New York for $3.2 billion.
   While most companies file for bankruptcy protection because of
debt, Robins filed under Chapter 11 in 1985 because of Dalkon
Shield litigation, Ross said. At the time of the filing, Robins had
already paid $520 million on 9,400 claims from women who used the
intrauterine device.
   Robins removed the Dalkon Shield from the market in the
mid-1970s after it was shown to cause sterility, birth defects and
other serious injuries.
   ``The whole bankruptcy was very unusual,'' Ross said. ``The
normal business was fine, stayed fine, and presumably will continue
to be fine if we ever get the deal with American Home.
   ``What's amazing is that the rest of the management didn't get
too distracted during bankruptcy,'' he said. ``The case was always
mainly about Dalkon Shield problems, and the management did a very
good job isolating those problems from the rest of the company.''
   The controversy over the Dalkon Shield and the bankruptcy court
filing apparently has not affected the company's sales, which have
climbed steadily throughout the decade.
   ``I don't really think it's been a factor,'' Robins spokesman
Roscoe E. Puckett Jr. said. ``The fact that sales have increased is
ample evidence that consumers have not had any worries about the
company's products.''
   Stockholders initially sold their shares when the company filed
for bankruptcy protection, bringing stock values as low as $5.50.
Robins stock is now worth about $26.
   American Home Products has the option to pull out of the merger
if the appeals process is not completed by this July 26, one year
after the plan was confirmed in bankruptcy court. But given that
Robins' value has continued to increase since the deal was made,
Ross said that possibility is slim.
   ``The least likely thing in the whole world is that American
Home will back out,'' he said. ``There'd be a line of other people
from Richmond to New York wanting to buy Robins.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890414-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1559EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-JunkBonds Bjt   04-14 0723</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Junk Bonds, Bjt,0741</SECOND>
<HEAD>The Market Milken Built Flounders as Junk Bonds Plunge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cloud hangs over the junk-bond market, where
prices have fallen 2 percent and more in the past week ahead of a
flood of new issues and amid fears that a recession could push some
companies to the brink of default on their interest payments.
   By Friday, traders said some junk bonds had touched new lows,
falling as much as $40 to $50 per $1,000 in face value in some
cases.
   Without the magic wand of junk-bond pioneer Michael Milken, the
$180 billion market can't seem to shrug off a sense of impending
doom. Milken, who was indicted last month on 98 racketeering and
fraud charges, had the ability to calm the high-yield, high-risk
market in times of turmoil.
   ``He was the biggest factor in keeping stability in the
market,'' said one trader who spoke on condition of anonymity.
There was a feeling among dealers that Milken ``would make sure the
market wouldn't go to hell in a hand basket.''
   Much of the market's concern centers on Solomon Asset
Management, whose founder David B. Solomon has been cooperating
with the government in its investigation of Milken and Drexel
Burnham Lambert Inc.
   Solomon is leaving Solomon Asset, and there is concern that the
firm might be forced to sell its huge portfolio of junk bonds to
meet cash demands from nervous pension clients.
   It also is rumored that a dozen or more junk-bond fund managers
have been subpoenaed in connection with the Drexel case. ``It
doesn't take much to make life miserable,'' said Advest Inc. trader
John Moran.
   In terms of prices, ``it's a really bad market all throughout,''
he said. Some issues had strengthened slightly Friday, but even
many of the better junk bonds were unable to recoup earlier losses.
   Moran pointed to Duracell's 13{ percent bonds due in the year
2000, which were up { point from Friday's low but still down 2
points from a week ago.
   Fundamentally, traders bemoaned redemptions by junk-bond mutual
funds. Small investors started pulling out of the funds a week ago,
but nervousness spilled over to institutional portfolio managers,
who also began withdrawing funds.
   Upcoming issues of $9 billion in new junk bonds, led by $5
billion in new debt to finance the mega-buyout of RJR Nabisco Inc.,
also weighed heavily on the market.
   ``People are in a cautious frame of mind and may not be a good
audience for those issues,'' one trader said. To lure reluctant
investors, underwriters might have to up yields on those issues,
which likely would depress prices of existing debt securities.
   Also dogging the market are fears of recession, which could make
it tough for companies laden with high-interest debt to make
interest payments to bondholders.
   ``Many companies with a great deal of debt may be very
vulnerable if there is a decline in business activity,'' one trader
said. ``Companies haven't been tested with all this debt before.''
   Several companies with outstanding junk bonds already are
experiencing difficulties. Analysts point to Wickes Cos. and
Interco, which they say are having trouble selling certain assets
as planned to help pay off their junk bonds. And junk bonds of
Resorts International, whose cash-flow from operations is not
sufficient to meet its interest obligations, have been weak.
   Traders also were talking about reports of an unpublished study
led by a Harvard University professor that tracked junk bonds
issued a decade ago and found the default rate was 34 percent, far
higher than other studies had shown.
   ``In the past when a study like that would come out, Mike
(Milken) did a good job of tearing it up,'' Moran said.
   Analysts were debunking the study, but none seemed to have
Milken's clout. Michael Dahood, a managing director at Smith
Barney, Harris, Upham &amp; Co., noted that the study only tracked a
dozen or so issues and that it was ``sensational'' to conclude that
of 100 now-outstanding issues, 34 will default.
   ``It's clear that there's going to be over time a greater loss
experience associated with below investment-grade bonds than what
historically the numbers might suggest ... but even if a company
does default, it does not necessarily mean a loss of value that the
word default conjures up,'' Dahood said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
