<FIRST>r f AM-SteelImports     04-14 0309</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Steel Imports,0320</SECOND>
<HEAD>February Imports In Check</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel imports in February were the lowest of
any month since October 1985 and were well within the limits of the
nation's steel import quotas, two industry groups said Friday.
   The American Iron and Steel Institute, representing domestic
producers from its base in Washington, D.C., said foreign producers
are shipping less steel to the United States because they can get
higher prices elsewhere.
   February's tonnage was 1.34 million tons, down from 1.78 million
tons in January and 1.91 million tons in February 1988, the AISI
said.
   Major countries who participate in the voluntary U.S. trade
system shipped only three-quarters of the metal authorized by their
negotiated quotas, the organization said.
   U.S. producers to lobbying the Bush administration to extend the
five-year quota plan beyond its Sept. 30 expiration. Even though
their profits have surging over the last two years, the companies
say they need continued trade protection to recover fully from
massive financial losses from 1980 to 1986.
   The lightest monthly import total before February was 1.30
million tons, or 17.3 percent of the market, in October, 1985.
   The February tonnage represented 16.8 percent of the domestic
market. The quotas were intended to limit imports to about 20
percent of the market.
   The rival American Institute for Imported Steel, a New
York-based association of importers, said that February's imports
represented 14 percent of the U.S. market, not counting 188,000
tons of semi-finished products ordered by U.S. steelmakers for
further processing on their mills. The quota's goal for finished
steel is 18.5 percent.
   ``The increasing volume of semi-finished steel imports, badly
needed by domestic rolling mills themselves, continues a trend
evident since the beginning of 1988,'' AIIS President John Griffin
said in a statement.
   Both organizations interpret information supplied by the
Commerce Department.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
