<DOCNO> AP890414-0286 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 0438EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>s f BC-PersonalFile-LowellMilken Adv16   04-14 1006</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Lowell Milken, Adv 16,1036</SECOND>
<HEAD>For ReleaseSunday, April 16</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Other Milken: Quiet, Unprepossessing, Indicted</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lowell Jay Milken is two years younger than his
better-known brother Michael. He never traded junk bonds, he isn't
Michael's right-hand man, he prefers the background _ and he faces
85 fewer charges of committing criminal acts.
   Friends dispute the perception of Lowell Milken as the guy in
the back room hunched over a ledger wearing a green eyeshade,
toiling away for his brother, as he was described in a 1988 book
about Milken and Drexel, ``The Predators' Ball.''
   ``Lowell has been very much his own man,'' said Martin Klein, a
New York lawyer and friend of Lowell's. ``Younger by two years but
certainly not any less creative or any less dedicated or any less
hard-working.''
   But as Michael Milken's star rose in the late 1970s and 1980s as
the architect of Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc.'s high-yield bond
department, Lowell's climbed with it, and the brothers earned
hundreds of millions of dollars.
   Now their fates are inextricably linked in the government's
massive racketeering and fraud indictment, which defense lawyers
contend includes The Other Milken only to pressure Michael into a
settlement.
   Friends describe Lowell Milken as a devoted family man,
hard-working, modest in taste and lifestyle despite his wealth,
devoted to running a charitable foundation formed four years before
the government began probing Drexel and the Milkens.
   Lowell Milken, 40, looks nothing like his brother, who stands
over 6 feet tall, wears black curly hair and has an angular face
and narrow eyes. Lowell has straight, sandy hair, and is shorter
and bespectacled. Both are described as sometimes abrasive at work.
   Like his brother, Lowell graduated from the University of
California at Berkeley in 1970, winning the business department's
top student award that eluded Michael two years earlier.
   Michael went east to the University of Pennsylvania's Wharton
School, but Lowell attended the University of California at Los
Angeles law school, where he was an editor of the law review. He
joined the Los Angeles firm of Irell &amp; Manella, where he is
remembered as assiduous and creative in the fields of tax and
corporate law.
   But he left the firm in 1978 to join his brother at Drexel's
high-yield bond department in Beverly Hills, Calif., where Michael
had moved the group from the investment firm's New York
headquarters.
   While Michael ran the X-shaped trading desk, Lowell worked in an
office on the other side of the floor. Michael won fame for
reshaping American business through the issue of high-yield,
high-risk bonds; Lowell worked on other less public tasks.
   To be sure, Lowell earned less than Michael's gargantuan $1
billion in compensation from 1983-87, but his $100 million hardly
could be considered a slight. He lives in a seven-bedroom home in
Encino, Calif., with his wife and three young sons. Friends say
family photos, not expensive artwork, fill the walls of the posh
suburban home.
   Drexel spokesman Steven Anreder and Lowell's attorney, Michael
Armstrong, said Lowell's job at Drexel involved administrative
matters such as finding and buying the junk bond headquarters; some
research duties on real estate and bankruptcy laws; and reviewing
personal investments by Drexel employees.
   ``His duties involved administrative and other duties that
simply were not involved with the matters the government has
mischaracterized in order to make its charges,'' Armstrong said.
   ``He's in this case primarily to put pressure on his brother, in
our view,'' he said.
   The 98-count indictment of the Milkens and former Drexel trader
Bruce Lee Newberg describes Lowell as ``his brother's principal
adviser in the conduct of the conspiracy.'' He also is said to be
the administrator of certain investment partnerships created by the
junk bond department.
   Lowell is charged with two counts of racketeering and 11 counts
of fraud in what prosecutors describe as a long-term scheme that
swindled clients and investors by manipulating stocks and skirting
laws during planned mergers or takeovers.
   According to the indictment, Lowell played no formal role in
making allegedly fraudulent stock transactions; in fact, he doesn't
even have a license to trade securities. But he allegedly
participated in the racketeering enterprise in other ways.
   In one count, Lowell is alleged to have joined a March 1986
telephone call regarding a $5.3 million payment with Ivan Boesky _
who provided much of the information leading to the Milken
indictment as part of a plea deal _ to settle fraudulent dealings
and then lied to accountants to cover it up.
   Lowell also is named along with Michael in the Securities and
Exchange Commission's civil suit charging them with insider trading
and securities fraud.
   Associates said Lowell Milken spends much of time administering
the Foundations of the Milken Families, which were set up in 1982
and have donated millions of dollars to city and state programs and
charities in education, human rights, and health and welfare.
   The market value of the foundation's assets grew from $43.9
million in 1985 to more than $193 million in 1987, in which it
handed out $15 million in donations. Lowell and his wife, Sandra,
set up their own charitable foundation in 1986.
   Recipients of Milken foundation money said that Lowell, like
Michael, has taken personal interest in the charities, and not
merely doled out the money.
   ``He really cares and believes in the things he's doing,'' said
Nancy Honig, president of the Quality Education Project in
California, which works with non-English speaking and disadvantaged
parents in poor areas. ``He's very clear about what he expects to
have happen.''
   Critics of the Milkens said they have played up their charitable
roles to try to counter the impression left by the government's
charges. But friends of the Milkens, including a public relations
firm they hired to speak for them, say the foundation contributed
millions before the government began its investigation.
   Said attorney Armstrong: ``It's hearts and flowers and I know
it's the old violin but that's the fact.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Sunday April 16</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890414-0287 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1700EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-14 0518</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0536</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed; Gold Prices Fall</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede LONDON BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished mostly lower in light
domestic dealings Friday after closing slightly higher overseas
following the release of a round of weak U.S. economic data.
   Gold prices fell sharply. Republic National Bank of New York
quoted a bid of $385.00 a troy ounce for gold, down $4.10 from
Thursday's late bid.
   Two key economic reports issued Friday were in line with market
expectations, which helped contain the dollar to a narrow trading
range.
   The Commerce Department said the trade deficit swelled 20.9
percent to $10.5 billion, up from a revised $8.68 billion in
January. Separately, the Labor Department said wholesale prices
rose 0.4 percent in March after rising 1 percent in each of the
previous two months. Analysts had predicted a 0.5 percent rise.
   ``Initially the news seemed neutral for the market since both
were within expectations, and the dollar was stable,'' said Earl
Johnson, a vice president at Harris Trust and Savings Bank in
Chicago.
   But the dollar came off as traders came to the conclusion that
the data pointed to a weakening economy. ``We've had a string of
weak economic numbers now,'' Johnson said, and this simply added to
it.
   Despite the batch of data, trading was lackluster. ``The market
seemed very thin,'' said Lou Calvello, a trader at Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc.
   ``People don't want to speculate on what's going to happen,'' he
said.
   In Tokyo, where markets close before Europe's trading day
begins, the dollar slipped 0.35 yen to a closing 132.45. Later in
London, the dollar traded at 132.35 yen. In New York, the dollar
closed at 132.05 yen, unchanged from Thursday.
   In London, the dollar rose against the pound. One British pound
cost $1.7000, cheaper for buyers than late Thursday's $1.7010. In
New York, one pound cost $1.7055, more expensive than $1.6981 on
Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late rates
Thursday, included: 1.8653 West German marks, down from 1.8723;
1.6465 Swiss francs, up from 1.6433; 6.3090 French francs, down
from 6.3395; 1,368.63 Italian lire, down from 1,374.13, and 1.1861
Canadian dollars, down from 1.1870.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday,
included: 1.8725 West German marks, up from 1.8720; 1.6510 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6422; 6.3350 French francs, up from 6.3335;
2.1145 Dutch guilders, up from 2.1080; 1,374.25 Italian lire, up
from 1,374.00, and 1.1875 Canadian dollars, unchanged.
   Gold prices fell. In New York, gold for current delivery settled
at $386.00 a troy ounce on the Commodity Exchange, down from
Thursday's $390.30.
   Gold traded in London at a late bid price of $386.50 a troy
ounce, down from $388.75 bid late Thursday. In Zurich, the late bid
price was $387, down from $389.15 bid late Thursday. Earlier in
Hong Kong, gold rose 92 cents to close at a bid $388.46 an ounce.
   Silver for current delivery on New York's Comex settled at
$5.805 a troy ounce, down from $5.867 on Thursday. Silver was
quoted in London at a bid price of $5.89 a troy ounce, up from
Thursday's $5.87.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
