<DOCNO> AP890414-0288 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 2037EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Alcoa     04-14 0165</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Earns-Alcoa,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alcoa's Quarterly Net Surges 54 Percent</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alcoa on Friday reported a 54 percent surge in
first-quarter profits amid strong worldwide demand for its aluminum
products.
   For the period ended March 31, the Aluminum Co. of America said
net income totaled $276 million, or $3.12 a share, up from $178.7
million, or $2.02 a share in the year-ago quarter.
   Revenue rose 25 percent to $2.6 billion, from $2.1 billion a
year ago. Aluminum shipments rose 14 percent during the period.
   Alcoa Chairman Paul O'Neill noted that the company's operations
in Australia and Brazil accounted for 44 percent of Alcoa's
first-quarter earnings due to higher prices for alumina and ingot.
   He also noted that world demand remains strong. ``Customers do
not appear to be building inventory,'' O'Neill said.
   The first-quarter earnings included a gain of $1.2 million
associated with favorable exchange rates, compared with a charge of
$21.2 million a year earlier.
   Alcoa is the world's largest producer of aluminum products.
</TEXT>
