<FIRST>r f AM-AirlineRoutes     04-14 0142</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Airline Routes,0149</SECOND>
<HEAD>Governments Approve Routes</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Transportation Department said Friday that
additional airline routes have been approved for non-stop flights
between Chicago and Stockholm and Mexico City.
   Denmark, Norway and Sweden, partners in the Scandinavian carrier
SAS, have agreed to accept American Airlines as a carrier between
Chicago and Stockholm starting May 1, the department said.
   SAS is the only carrier that currently connects the two cities,
offering service with a change of planes in Copenhagen.
   Foreign governments have the right to approve airline routes.
   Separately, Mexico has agreed to accept United Air Lines as an
additional non-stop carrier between Chicago and Mexico City.
Flights will begin July 1, the department said.
   American Airlines and a Mexican company, Mexicana Airlines,
currently fly non-stop between the two cities, and Delta Air Lines
offers service with an intermediate stop.
</TEXT>
