<FIRST>u f AM-Earns-Computers 1stLd-Writethru   04-14 0460</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Earns-Computers, 1st Ld-Writethru,0476</SECOND>
<HEAD>IBM Earnings Rise 1.8 Percent Excluding Accounting Change</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 3 grafs to include closing stock price; picks up
4th graf pvs, ``IBM's showing ....</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   International Business Machines Corp. said
Friday its first-quarter profit rose 1.8 percent excluding an
accounting change, and the stock market responded favorably to the
news.
   The gain came in spite of a chip problem that caused a delay in
shipment of mainframe computers, the biggest and most profitable
part of IBM's product line.
   IBM's stock rose $1.62{ to $110.87{ in consolidated New York
Stock Exchange trading, contributing to Wall Street's best day
since October.
   ``IBM's showing some great progress,'' said Don Young, an
analyst at Sanford C. Bernstein &amp; Co.
   The world's biggest computer company said it earned $950 million
in the three months ended March 31. IBM earned $933 million a year
earlier from normal operations, but final net income in 1988 was
$1.25 billion after inclusion of a $315 million gain from the
accounting change.
   Including the effect of the one-time gain in 1988, net income
fell 23.9 percent. The accounting change related to the treatment
of deferred taxes.
   Earnings per share were $1.61. That was up from $1.57 in 1988
before the accounting change, but down from the $2.10 recorded
after the accounting change.
   Revenue rose 5.6 percent to $12.7 billion from $12.06 billion.
   ``IBM's product and service offerings continue to grow stronger,
and we are benefiting from our improving customer partnerships as
well as our restructuring actions,'' John F. Akers, the chairman
and chief executive, said in a statement.
   ``Our expectations for 1989 remain unchanged,'' Akers said.
   Young said he was impressed that revenue grew 5.6 percent in
spite of the mainframe delivery problem and the rise in the dollar,
which makes revenue earned overseas worth less in dollars.
   IBM is successfully stretching out the life of its 4-year-old
mainframe line, while benefiting from strong sales of its new
AS-400 midrange computers and increasing acceptance of its Personal
System-2 personal computers, Young said.
   ``If not for the shipment shortfall on 3090s (mainframes) we
would have had a very superior quarter,'' said Jay Stevens, a Dean
Witter Reynolds Inc. analyst.
   IBM's results have been hurt by the slow growth in demand for
big mainframe computers, which are being overtaken by speedy
personal computers and workstations.
   Sanford C. Bernstein estimates that worldwide sales of
microcomputer hardware will surpass worldwide sales of mainframe
hardware for the first time this year, $49 billion to $45 billion.
   But IBM is well-positioned to cope with the changing technology
because of its strength in PCs, Young said. ``It's hard to say this
is a mainframe company. They're the world's largest PC supplier.''
</TEXT>
