<FIRST>u f AM-WallStreet 1stLd-Writethru   04-14 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wall Street, 1st Ld-Writethru,0522</SECOND>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates with closing prices throughout.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market ran up its sharpest gain in
nearly six months Friday, inspired by an apparent easing of
inflationary pressures.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials jumped 41.06 to
2,337.06, for its best single-day showing since it rose 43.92
points last Oct. 20.
   The average wound up the week with a net gain of 32.26 points.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declines by more than 5 to 2 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
1,074 up, 404 down and 474 unchanged.
   Volume on the floor of the Big Board came to 169.78 million
shares, up from 141.59 million in the previous session. Nationwide,
consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including trades in
those stocks on regional exchanges and in the over-the-counter
market, totaled 201.10 million shares.
   The Labor Department reported that the producer price index of
finished goods rose 0.4 percent in March, compared with 1 percent
increases in each of the two preceding months.
   The figure came in close to advance estimates. Nevertheless,
analysts said investors were relieved that the report didn't
contain another unpleasant surprise.
   Interest rates tumbled in the credit markets following the news.
Rates on short-term Treasury bills dropped 15 to 25 basis points,
or hundredths of a percentage point.
   Prices of long-term government bonds, which move in the opposite
direction from interest rates, rose more than $10 for each $1,000
in face value.
   Separately, International Business Machines reported
first-quarter earnings of $1.61 a share, up from $1.57 in the
comparable period a year ago.
   Wall Streeters generally responded positively to that showing,
in light of IBM's warning a few weeks ago that its results this
year weren't likely to live up to some of the most optimistic
estimates in the financial world. IBM shares gained 1| to 110~.
   On a busy day for government economic data, the Commerce
Department reported that the nation's trade deficit widened to
$10.50 billion in February and the Federal Reserve said industrial
production was unchanged in March from the month before. Both
numbers were pretty much in line with advance estimates.
   General Electric, which reported better-than-expected earnings
for the first quarter on Thursday, rose 1} to 47 in heavy trading.
   Other gainers among the blue chips included Merck, up 1{ at 67\;
McDonald's, up 1] at 53}; Philip Morris, up 2[ at 119|; Coca-Cola,
up 1] at 52, and DuPont, up 2{ at 106{.
   As measured by Wilshire Associates' index of more than 5,000
actively traded stocks, the market increased $39.03 billion, or
0.85 percent, in value.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed common stocks
gained 2.35 to 168.89.
   Standard &amp; Poor's industrial index rose 5.86 to 347.76, and
S&amp;P's 500-stock composite index was up 4.96 at 301.36.
   The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter market
picked up 3.82 to 417.68. At the American Stock Exchange, the
market value index closed at 335.82, up 2.38.
</TEXT>
