<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     04-14 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Petroleum futures prices finished higher in
moderate trading Friday, boosted by a late-afternoon rally in
gasoline prices.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May contract for West
Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S. crude oil, rose 40
cents to close at $20.69 a barrel, after trading as low as $20.13.
   Wholesale unleaded gasoline for May delivery jumped 1.21 cents
to 70.02 cents a gallon, with other months gaining less than a
penny.
   The May contract for heating oil advanced 0.77 cent to a
settlement price of 52.91 cents a gallon. Other contract months had
similar gains.
   Analysts attributed Friday's advances to internal market
influences, led by the gasoline contracts which have been rising on
a combination of seasonal demands and worries about the impact of
the Alaskan oil spill.
   ``Today was just a broad technical recovery from yesterday,''
said James Steel, an analyst at Refco Inc.
   Steel said crude prices also got a belated lift from Thursday's
announcement that Saudi Arabia is continuing to cut back oil
deliveries.
   ``The market didn't respond immediately, so the news had more of
an impact today,'' he said.
   Jack Unger, a trader with Merrill Lynch Energy Futures, said
crude prices were up early in the session, but by midday were
trading below Thursday's $20.29 closing price.
   Late in the day, gasoline prices spurted up, ``and that brought
the whole level of the market up.''
</TEXT>
