<FIRST>u f AM-Holly-Farms     04-14 0815</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Holly-Farms,0848</SECOND>
<HEAD>Holly Shareholders Vote On Proposed Merger</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holly Farms Corp. shareholders voted
Friday on a proposed $1.1 billion merger with ConAgra Inc. as Holly
Farms managers continued efforts to block a takeover by rival
poultry processor Tyson Foods Inc.
   R. Lee Taylor II, chief executive officer of Holly Farms, said a
preliminary vote count was expected Monday.
   ``If the merger is turned down, then the (Holly Farms) board of
directors will have to review all of the alternatives available to
the company,'' Taylor said, declining to outline what those
alternatives might be.
   Meanwhile, ConAgra stockholders backed the merger plan by a 96
percent to 4 percent margin during a special meeting Friday in
Omaha.
   Charles M. Harper, ConAgra's chairman and chief executive
officer, said he was ``hopeful, but not optimistic'' the merger
plan would receive the required two-thirds approval of Holly Farms
shareholders.
   Holly Farms has about 5,500 stockholders with 18.1 million
shares. About 200 people attended Holly Farms' shareholder meeting,
with much of the voting conducted by proxy.
   No matter how the Holly Farms shareholders voted, the merger
proposal is expected to end up in court, but Harper said he was
confident his company's plan eventually would prevail.
   ``I would be optimistic about the outcome in normal
circumstances. But these circumstances have become abnormal _ I
might even say bizarre,'' he said.
   ``Since Tyson learned on Nov. 17 that ConAgra had the highest
and best bid, Tyson has consistently tried to undermine the merger
and ConAgra's contract rights,'' Harper said.
   Tyson, the nation's largest poultry processor, is offering $1.15
billion for the Memphis-based Holly Farms, a national leader in
fresh poultry sales.
   Taylor and Tyson president Don Tyson of Springdale, Ark.,
addressed the Holly Farms shareholders prior to the vote. Both men
promised to make good use of the stockholders' money.
   The scramble for Holly Farms began last October when Tyson
offered a cash and stock swap valued at $49.50 a share for Holly
Farms stockholders.
   Tyson's current offer is $63.50 a share in cash, and although
Holly Farms shareholders did not vote on the bid directly, Don
Tyson urged them to keep it in mind.
   The ConAgra merger, a stock swap arrangement, would be worth
about $60 a share to Holly Farms stockholders.
   ``Tyson and Holly would be a perfect fit,'' Tyson said. ``That
is why we are offering more money for your stock than anyone else.''
   In urging stockholders to approve the merger with ConAgra,
Taylor praised his company's performance and promised continued
good business.
   Holly Farms expects average earnings per share of $6.11 for 1989
through 1993 at a time when chicken prices are expected to decline,
Taylor said.
   ``We're looking at some strong performance,'' he said. ``We hope
you will keep our outlook for the future in mind.''
   Market analysts have said Holly Farms would likely retain much
of its independence with ConAgra, while the same is not assured
with Tyson.
   A Chancery Court in Delaware, dealing with a suit brought by
Tyson, is reviewing an ``asset-option agreement'' in the proposed
ConAgra-Holly Farms merger that would allow ConAgra to buy prime
Holly Farms assets should the deal fall through.
   Tyson contends the agreement is an illegal attempt to make Holly
Farms unattractive to any buyer other than ConAgra. ConAgra has
vowed to defend the agreement in court.
   Tyson has conditioned its buyout offer on the removal of the
asset agreement, and that, in turn, has led Holly Farms to portray
Tyson's bid as unassurred.
   ``We would like our stockholders to receive a clean and clear
proposal from Tyson,'' Taylor said.
   Under the asset agreement, ConAgra would be allowed to buy Holly
Farms subsidiary Harker's Inc. of LeMars, Iowa, for $148.8 million,
Holly Farms of Texas Inc. for a like amount and Holly Farms
facilities in Wilkesboro, N.C., for $127.5 million.
   Those purchases would cover some 34 percent of Holly Farms'
total assets.
   Natalie Cockrell, a Holly Farms stockholder since the 1950s,
pulled Taylor aside after the meeting to ask about the asset-option
agreement.
   ``He explain to me that it was the only way they could get the
offer from ConAgra ... But I still don't understand what will
happen if the judge says it's illegal,'' she said.
   Harry Kingston, a Holly Farms stockholder with 1,440 shares,
said he voted for the merger since the ConAgra stock swap is
non-taxable.
   ``If you take the cash money it's going to throw you in a higher
tax bracket and I can't see giving the government that much
money,'' Kingston said.
   In his pitch to Holly Farms stockholders, Tyson said his company
``has been good to its shareholders.''
   ``If you bought 100 shares of Tyson when it went public in 1963,
it would have cost you $1,050. Today, that 100 shares, through
stock splits, would be 12,000 shares worth $180,000,'' Tyson said.
</TEXT>
