<DOCNO> AP890414-0296 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 1822EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-14 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp,0719</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Surge On Dry Weather Fears</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Fears that drought conditions will persist for another year in
the Midwest drove grain and soybean futures prices up sharply
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   ``The major concern is the lack of subsoil moisture,'' said
Charles Notis of Freese-Notis Weather Inc., a forecasting firm in
Des Moines, Iowa.
   ``The main concern is, will this dry weather continue, will we
have another lousy crop year?''
   On other markets, coffee futures surged; platinum gained while
gold and silver futures retreated; petroleum prices rose; and
livestock and meat futures were mostly higher.
   Wheat settled 1{ cents to 4 cents higher with the contract for
delivery in May at $4.12} a bushel; corn was 2 cents to 4} cents
higher with May at $2.70} a bushel; oats were 5{ cents to 7} cents
higher with May at $1.91} a bushel; soybeans were 5 cents to 10
cents higher with May at $7.33 a bushel.
   The wave of drought panic that swept through the grain and
soybean pits had only the slightest foundation in reality, where
spring planting has barely begun.
   Traders cited forecasts by private meteorologists, including
Freese-Notis, for at least another week of below-normal
precipitation in the Corn Belt, and they ignored or downplayed the
National Weather Service's 30-day outlook for normal precipitation
in the Midwest.
   ``I guess they've gotten it in their minds that we're going to
have another drought,'' said Cathy Leow, a grain-market analyst
with Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York. ``When you have
that kind of mentality going on, then of course the price is going
to go up.''
   Notis said the soil was driest in much of Iowa, northern
Illinois, northern Missouri, Nebraska and southern Minnesota.
   But he said there still was plenty of time for soil moisture to
improve before planting begins in earnest.
   After the close, the National Weather Service issued a new
6-to-10-day forecast predicting normal or below-normal rainfall in
the Midwest for the second half of next week.
   Coffee futures price leaped on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp; Cocoa
Exchange following reports that the United States, the world's
largest coffee consumer, had reversed its position at the
International Coffee Organization talks in London, indicating it
would consider a 1-year extension of the existing International
Coffee Agreement, which expires on Sept. 30.
   The United States had previously said it would not participate
in any agreement that did not address its demands for increased
availablity of high-quality arabica coffees and tighter limits on
sales by producer nations to countries that are not members of the
International Coffee Organization.
   Coffee settled 3.21 cents to 4.76 cents higher with May at
$1.3698 a pound.
   Platinum futures surged amid tight-supply fears in a
continuation of Thursday's explosive rally on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   Gold and silver futures retreated on New York's Commodity
Exchange in reaction to the Labor Department's report of a
smaller-than-expected 0.4 percent increase in producer prices last
month.
   Platinum settled $7.90 to $10.90 higher with July at $569.20 a
troy ounce; gold was $4.30 to $5.30 lower with June at $389.80 a
troy ounce; silver was 6.2 cents to 9.1 cents lower with May at
$5.825 a troy ounce.
   Petroleum prices recovered from Thursday's sell-off in a late
rally on the New York Merc.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 40 cents to 48 cents
higher with May at $20.69 a barrel; heating oil was .77 cent to .78
cent higher with May at 52.91 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.35 cent to 1.21 cents higher with May at 70.02 cents a gallon.
   On the Chicago Mercantile Exchange, cattle and pork futures
finished mostly higher in line with firmer cash prices.
   Live cattle were .15 cent to .33 cent higher with June at 71.10
cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent to .32 cent higher with
May at 76.27 cents a pound; live hogs were .13 cent lower to .63
cent higher with June at 46.22 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies
were .05 cent lower to .90 cent higher with July at 33.62 cents a
pound.
</TEXT>
