<FIRST>u f AM-GMProxy 1stLd-Writethru   04-14 0361</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-GM Proxy, 1st Ld-Writethru,0370</SECOND>
<HEAD>GM Releases Its Proxy Statement; Smith Gets $3.6 Million Last Year</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 5-7 with 2 grafs of UAW comment.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDERICK STANDISH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. Chairman Roger Smith
received about $3.6 million in salary and benefits last year,
placing last in terms of compensation among the chiefs of the
nation's Big Three automakers, GM said Friday.
   In its annual proxy statement, the nation's largest automaker
said Smith received $983,000 in salary, exercised $1 million in
stock options and had $68,833 contributed by the company to a
savings and stock purchase plan.
   Smith also received $1.5 million worth of stock which could be
held or liquidated during the following three years.
   The proxy statement said that in addition, Smith was paid $1
million early this year for the company's performance during the
five previous years.
   United Auto Workers President Owen Bieber and Vice President
Donald Ephlin, head of the union's GM Department, issued a joint
statement Friday afternoon criticizing the company's executive
compensation amounts.
   They said it was ``irresponsible for the ship's officers to be
seen feasting in the officer's mess when down below the waves are
pounding and the ship is taking on water.''
   Earlier this week, the nation's second-largest automaker, Ford
Motor Co., said its chairman, Donald Petersen, received $10.5
million in 1988 compensation, most of it coming in stock options.
   No. 3 Chrysler Corp. said its chairman, Lee Iacocca, was awarded
$3.7 million and future stock options from the nation's No. 3
automaker.
   The GM proxy statement also listed 1988 salaries, exercised
stock options and company stock and savings plan contributions for
four other officers: Executive Vice President F. Alan Smith,
$764,796; President Robert Stempel, $688,594; Vice Chairman Donald
Atwood, who is being considered to become deputy defense secretary,
$668,750; and Executive Vice President Lloyd Reuss, $535,000.
   The statement also contained a number of proposals presented by
shareholders to be voted on during the GM annual meeting May 19 in
Detroit, including three proposals for GM to cut its economic ties
to South Africa. The company's board of directors is recommending
votes against all three.
</TEXT>
