<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 2117EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-HuntBankruptcy     04-14 0471</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hunt Bankruptcy,0488</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sides Debate Hunt Brothers Debt Settlement Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A creditor payback plan proposed by the bankrupt
Hunt brothers amounts to ``blackmail,'' an attorney said Friday
during a hearing in the bankruptcy petitions of the two former
billionaires.
   Willam Herbert Hunt and Nelson Bunker Hunt filed bankruptcy last
September after Minpeco SA, a Peruvian mining company, won a $134.6
million judgment against them. Minpeco claimed the brothers had
conspired to commit fraud during their silver dealings in 1979 and
1980.
   The brothers also face multimillion dollar tax claims by the
Internal Revenue Service.
   Details of the brothers' plan remained under seal until late
Friday, but were discussed during a hearing before U.S. Bankruptcy
Judge Harold Abramson.
   Under the plan, the Hunt brothers' largest creditor, the IRS
would receive half of the proceeds from liquidation of assets over
and above those set aside for the brothers.
   The brothers each would retain 10 percent of the proceeds from
the sale of their assets. In Bunker Hunt's case, that 10 percent is
estimated to be $15 million. The brothers would also keep
possession of their Dallas homes and ``life'' interests in trusts
left to them by their father, H.L. Hunt. Their other holdings would
be liquidated and the proceeds split among about 4,000 creditors
each.
   But major creditors, including the IRS, Minpeco and
Manufacturers Hanover Trust Co. of New York _ which has a $36
million claim _ opposed the Hunts' plan.
   The IRS' claim, about $900 million against Bunker Hunt and $300
million against his brother, is the main sticking point in debt
settlement negotiations.
   A trial currently is scheduled for July on the IRS' contention
that each brother owes $300 million in taxes from 1982.
   ``They proposed blackmail to creditors,'' said Barbara Howse, a
Minpeco attorney, criticizing the part of the Hunts' plan that
includes proceeding to trial with the 1982 tax case.
   Should the brothers lose that case, it would wipe out virtually
all their assets, leaving nothing for other creditors, which
include silver speculators and people who say they lost money in
land deals involving the brothers.
   The IRS, Minpeco and Manufacturers Hanover together have
proposed an outline of liquidation plan they would like other
creditors to consider.
   The major difference between the two plans, according to
Manufacturers Hanover attorney Hugh Ray, involve who is in charge
of the liquidation.
   ``The real creditors don't want the Hunts managing this,'' Ray
said. ``The question is, `Who do you want running this? The
creditors who are owed the money or those who ran it into the
ground.'
   ``We may not be sage. We may not be wise, but we can do better
than this,'' Ray said.
   The Hunts asked Abramson to extend the period that they alone
may negotiate with creditors.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890414-0303 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-14-89 2153EST</FILEID>
<FIRST>d f PM-EconomyRdp     04-14 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Economy Rdp,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>Data Suggests Inflationary Pressures Subsiding</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For Saturday PMs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA C. MARTINEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock and bond markets rallied impressively after the
government released economic data suggesting that inflationary
pressures are subsiding and the economy is taking a breather from
the brisk pace of the last few years.
   On Wall Street, the stock market turned in its best showing in
nearly five months. The Dow Jones industrial average jumped 41.06
points Friday to 2,337.06, for its best single-day gain since it
rose 43.92 points last Oct. 20.
   In the credit markets, bonds scored their biggest gains since
early December. The Treasury's bellwether 30-year issue jumped
$12.50 for every $1,000 in face amount, as its yield dropped to
9.03 percent from 9.15 percent late Thursday. Short-term interest
rates were also sharply lower.
   The government reported Friday that wholesale prices climbed
more slowly in March than in the previous two months, while the
operating rate at the nation's factories slowed, business
inventories rose and sales plunged.
   At the same time, the government said the nation's trade deficit
widened in to $10.5 billion in February from a rtevised $8.98
billion in January.
   The reports were either better or consistent with expectations.
   ``What we have here is what (Federal Reserve Board Chairman
Alan) Greenspan and the Fed have been working for _ an economic
pause that refreshes as opposed to a severe slowdown or
recession,'' said Thomas F. Carpenter, economist with ASB Capital
Management in Washington.
   The Labor Department reported that the producer price index of
finished goods rose 0.4 percent in March. The index, which measures
inflation at the wholesale level, had increased 1 percent in each
of the two previous months.
   Also in March, the nation's factories operated at an 84 percent
rate, 0.2 percent slower than in February and the second
consecutive monthly decline, according to the Federal Reserve Board.
   The Commerce Department said business inventories rose 0.5
percent in February while sales plunged 0.9 percent in their
steepest decline in more than two years.
   With the exception of the trade figure, analysts said the
reports pointed to a slowdown in the growth of economic activity
and fit in with other evidence that the economy is easing off the
vigorous pace of recent years, including lackluster retail sales
and a slackening of employment growth in March.
   ``We expect a slowdown in the economy and possibly a resurgence
in growth later this year. At that point people will be concerned
about the economy again. But now, with the economy slowdown being
confirmed with retail sales and other numbers, the pendulum is
beginning to swing back to a more balanced view and less
inflationary fears,'' said Marshall B. Front, economist at the
Chicago investment and mutual-fund management firm of Stein Roe &amp;
Farnham.
   Carpenter cautioned, however, that it is ``premature to get on
the bandwagon and suggest that the economy is going to slow in a
meaningful way.'' With most of the weakness concentrated in the
automobile sector, the slowdown could be temporary as dealers add
incentives during the second quarter to help boost sales, he said.
   But Friday's data could fuel a reversal in interest rates,
predicted Peter Greenbaum, bond market analyst with Smith Barney,
Harris Upham &amp; Co. ``How much lower depends on what happens with
the dollar.'' Greenbaum said he expects the yield on the
government's long-term bond to decline to 8.75 percent by the end
of the year, from a peak of about 9.5 percent in the first quarter.
   In other economic news, a Federal Home Loan Mortgage Corp.
survey showed that fixed-rate home mortgages are currently
averaging 11.11 percent, up from 11.07 percent last week.
   On one-year adjustable rate mortgages, lenders were asking an
average initial rate of 9.41 percent this week, up from 9.39
percent the week before, Freddie Mac said.
</TEXT>
