<FIRST>u f AM-AmericanContract 1stLd-Writethru   04-14 0636</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-American Contract, 1st Ld-Writethru,0655</SECOND>
<HEAD>Transport Workers Picket American Airlines In Advance Of Mediation
Talks</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS new 5th graf to UPDATE with picketing at Kennedy Airport;
picks up 5th graf pvs bg'ng, The union's ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Airlines, fresh from a recent airplane
buying binge and already casting an eye toward troubled Eastern
Airlines, found itself the target of informational pickets at
numerous airports Friday as union members began clamoring for a
piece of the company's profits.
   ``American has become the biggest carrier in the country. They
are the most profitable in the country and the workers, `we've
worked hard; you've made a lot of money off our labor and we want
to share in that profit,''' said Jim Gannon, a spokesman for the
Transport Workers Union, which represents 22,000 of American's
67,000 employees.
   Union officials said a ``couple of hundred'' pickets were at
American's home terminal at Dallas-Fort Worth International
Airport, while a similar number were at O'Hare in Chicago. Small
numbers were reported at other airports where American operates.
   The pickets did not disrupt the airline's flight schedule.
   In New York, meanwhile, about 100 mechanics and ground service
workers demanding a new contract picketed American's terminal at
Kennedy International Airport, Port Authority police said.
   The union's contract with American was up for renewal on March
1, but a proposed new pact was turned down by a 12,143-to-5,140
vote last month.
   The company and union will sit down next week with federal
mediator Harry Bickford in an attempt to resolve the dispute, which
centers on wage scales and health benefits.
   If no agreement is reached, and Bickford declares an impasse,
there is then a 30-day cooling off period, after which the union
can strike and the company impose new contract conditions.
   Ed Koziatek, TWU's international vice president for American,
said he was not optimistic the mediation will be successful.
   ``We spent eight weeks in direct negotiations, and the parties
are locked up on some real major concerns,'' he said.
   ``We're frankly puzzled'' at the union's decision to picket,
American spokeswoman Mary O'Neal said.
   The rejected contract was worth $610 million over four years,
``more than anyone has offered, for example, to buy Eastern
Airlines,'' Ms. O'Neal said.
   It guaranteed raises for all employees, ranging from about 28
percent over four years to about 100 percent during the contract.
``That seems pretty generous,'' she said.
   Gannon said the union objected to the wage scale, under which it
takes new employees 12 years to reach top pay. The union wants that
reduced to five years.
   Also at issue, he said, is the company's plan to have employees
pay $10 per person _ and up to $30 per family _ toward health
insurance each month. The company previously has paid the entire
premium.
   Ms. O'Neal said the company was asking only for employees to pay
a part of increases. ``With rising health costs, the change is
inevitable for all employees at American,'' she said.
   Fort Worth-based American just completed its most profitable
year ever, with parent company AMR Corp. posting 1988 net income of
$476.8 million, a 140.3 percent increase from 1987 and 37.9 percent
higher than the previous record of $345.8 million in 1985.
   American President Robert Crandall said in Miami Thursday his
airline was considering buying some routes belonging to Eastern
Airlines, which has filed for bankruptcy after a machinists strike
essentially grounded the carrier.
   Last month, American also announced two plane purchases: a $3.09
billion deal with Dutch manufacturer Fokker for 75 F-100 planes and
options for another 75; and an approximately $2 billion purchase of
25 Boeing 757s and 10 Boeing 767s.
   On Feb. 7, American announced another $7 billion deal to buy
eight McDonnell Douglas Corp. jets with options for another 142.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
